<FIRST>r a AM-Marijuana-Professor     09-01 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Professor,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Professor Among 4 Arrested In Raid On Pot Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAMUL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 57-year-old San Diego State University
professor who once worked as a California Highway Patrol officer was
among four people arrested during a raid Thursday on a marijuana
farm, authorities said.
   Agents seized 800 marijuana plants, some as much as 14 feet tall,
and arrested Jack David Mooers, an associate professor of teacher
education at SDSU, Narcotics Task Force officials said.
   Also taken into custody at the farm outside Jamul in rural
eastern San Diego County were Mooers' wife, real estate developer
Betty Mooers, 65; James Wesley Johnson, 44; and Bartolo Espinoza
Mercado, 36.
   All four face charges of cultivating marijuana for sale.
   The 50-acre farm was raided after deputies in a sheriff's
helicopter spotted the marijuana plants while hovering over a nearby
methamphetamine lab in a raid two weeks ago, said sheriff's deputy
Steve Reed.
   Agents also found an underground drying room at the farm and
several platic trash bags filled with marijuana buds, said Reed.
   Mooers was a CHP patrol officer in the 1960s and a parole officer
before leaving law enforcement to teach, said San Diego police Lt.
Skip DiCerchio. Mooers began work at the university in 1968, a
campus spokesman said.
   His wife worked in the police department's business office in the
1950s, DiCerchio said.
</TEXT>
