<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-ForeignPolicy 740   09-01 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Foreign Policy, 740</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: President Entering A Difficult Second Phase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's meeting at the White House
today with embattled Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu touches
off a post-honeymoon foreign policy phase that will test Bush's
management of America's role in the world.
   His biggest decisions involve dealing with the Soviet Union, but
the issues closing in on Bush also range from the strenuous effort
to oust Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega from power in Panama to the
intractable Arab-Israeli dispute and the collapse of a 19-nation
conference on Cambodia.
   The first seven months in the White House have been relatively
easy ones for Bush. His only near-crisis in foreign policy involved
the American hostages in Lebanon and the slaying of Marine Lt. Col.
William Higgins.
   The hostage problem, which also dogged Presidents Carter and
Reagan, was not solved while Bush was on vacation in Maine. But Bush
isn't faced with threatening execution deadlines.
   However, in the months ahead, Bush will be wrestling with all
sorts of foreign policy questions. For instance, he has to decide
how much money he can find to assist Colombia in its war on drug
lords.
   The president has pledged $65 million, and is preparing a
comprehensive proposal to combat drugs to be announced next week.
But Colombian Justice Minister Monica de Greif has appealed publicly
for another $19 million to protect judges and other targets in her
country.
   The president is sympathetic, but can he dig down for Colombia
and argue at the same time that there's nothing more in the coffers
for Poland beyond the $119 million he promised before Solidarity
captured a power-sharing role in Warsaw and food shortages grew
worse?
   It gets to be a matter of priorities, and Poland's supporters in
Congress and among the American public are eager to have Bush expand
the modest aid he has offered and made conditional on the adoption
of economic reforms.
   Even trickier is the situation in the Baltic republics where
proponents of change are getting a far different reception from
Moscow than Solidarity has received.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has made Bush's life easier by
accepting the political and economic shifts in Poland. The country
remains committed to the Warsaw Pact while changes in its industrial
and agricultural policies could spare the Soviets some of the costs
of supporting Poland.
   But the Communist party's ruling Politburo is taking a skeptical
view of what it calls ``the virus of nationalism'' in Estonia,
Latvia and Lithuania and has warned of ``urgent measures'' to curb
radical changes in the once-independent republics.
   Asked about this development, Bush said he hoped peaceful change
would continue ``not only outside the Soviet Union, but in it.''
   The remark suggests Bush may take the same approach to the
Baltics as he has to Poland, carefully encouraging change without
saying how far he would like to see it go.
   The visit of Japanese Prime Minister Kaifu involves some touchy
presidential diplomacy as well.
   Bush has to juggle U.S. frustration with Japan's $50 billion
trade surplus against the possibility that pushing Kaifu too hard
might contribute to the downfall of his weak government. That could
pave the way for a left-wing coalition in Tokyo that Bush and his
conservative followers would findasteful.
   The collapse of the Paris conference on Cambodia means bracing
for an intensification of the civil war between go that include
Prince Sihanouk and the Khmer Rouge.
   The Bush administration had hoped the c would produce a
cease-fire and a transition government. Now the options are suddenly
bleak.
   In the Middle East, at some n Bush will have to decide whether
the Palestiniberation Organization can be coaxed into coope an
Israeli plan for elections on the West Bank The president and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III consider the proposal the most
practical way of gettingks started. But a PLO boycott could kill the
plan and that would leave Bush scratching his head for another
approach.
   In Panama, meanwhile, Gen. Noriega continues to outfox the Bush
administration, clinging to power through stand-inand defying all
pressures and stratagems. The term of provisional President Manuel
Solis Palma is expiring. What next?
  
</TEXT>
