<SECOND>PM-AIDS-AZT Price, Bjt,1003</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Day's Dose of AZT: $1.50 to Make, $9 to Buy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five capsules of the AIDS drug AZT, one day's
supply for infected people, contain an estimated 15 cents worth of
ingredients.
   They probably cost between $1.50 and $2.50 to manufactthe
drugstore for $9.
   By any standard, a lifetime of treatment with AZT will add up to
a lot of money. Is dicine really a bargain, as its maker maintains?
   The disagreement highlights the arbitrary, often mysteriou
fashion in which pharmaceutical companies decide how much to chrge
for the medicines they hold exclusive right ``The only thing we know
is there is no objective social way of determining what the price
should be except what the market will bear,'' said Dr. Donald Rucer
of the University of Illinois School of Pharn this case, the market
is likely to grow dramatically.
   AZT, known generically as azidothymidine and sold a the only
approved AIDS drug. Until recently, it was recommended only for the
4with AIDS or severe AIDS-related illness. But new research suggests
that the medicine can also forestall AIDS in people at earlier
stages of infection with HIV, the acquiredimmune deficiency syndrome
virus.
   Federal officials estimate that the drug could become routine
therapy for an additional 600,000 infected people _ those who have
very early symptoms or no signs of the disease at all except for
abnormal blood counts.
   Burroughs Wellcome Co., the only company that makes AZT, sells
the drug for $1.50 per capsule. By the time wholesalers and
drugstores take their markups, the retail price is about $1.80.
   Peopleth AIDS typically take about eight capsules a day, while
five capsules daily are recommended for those with no outward
symptoms. For them, the price is $9 a day, or about $3,300 a year.
SomIDS patients have spent about $8,000 a year taking 12 capsules
ly, a dosage no longer recommended.
   On Wednesday, 15 homosexual rights and AIDS activist
organizations asked Burroughs Wellcome to lower the cost.
   ``Absolutely, it's overpriced,'' sor of the Gay Men's Health
Crisis in New York. ``It's clear that at the current price, there
wll be people who won't be able to afford this drug.''
   Leonard Schifrin, an economist at the College of Wilows the
pharmaceutical industry, said that many drug prices are too high, in
part because companies often have no competition for several years
after they introduce innovative medicines.
   Big profits are a way of life, he said, and maintenance drugs
like AZT, taken daily for years, are especially lucrative.
   re used by large numbers of people with serious problems for lof
time,'' he said. ``That's a gold mine, and I hate to see AZT being
mined as gold. It's a basi problem of monopolistic producers and
helpless consumers.''
   Burroughs Wellcome, spokeswoman Karen Collins satried to price
this drug compassionately.'' Dr. David Barry, the vice president of
research, called AZT ``a bar
   Compared with drugs used for other chronic disorders, AZT is
relatively expensive. For instance, maintena Zantac, the ulcer drug,
and Vasotec, the high blood pressure medicine, both cost patients
about 70 cents a day.
   However, Barry noted that AZT is far cheaper than some new
anti-infection drugs that can cost $50 a day or more, although these
drugs are usually given for weeks at a time, not years.
   Barry said that many factors go into setting drug prices, the
cost of production, the number of patients who will take it, the
need for plant expansion cost of continuing to conduct research on
the medicine.
   Buhe overriding factor is the expense of paying foompany's search
for new treatments and cures, wh million last year.
   ``The successful drugs and the revenues obtained from them must
pay for all of the enoarch we do in basic scientific fields or in
applied fields that fail,'' said Ba ``The biggest element that
determines how much we charge for drugs is the bottom line _ how
much revenue do we need to get to keep our company out of the red
and to sustain our research program.''
   Barry said AZT is difficult to mak23 steps. But the manufacturing
cost is just one relatively minor factor in the price, and ``dbe
like determining the cost of surgery based on the cost of stainless
steel used in scalpels. It makes no sense at all.''
   Still, stock analysts do estimate such costs. Johannah Walton of
Shearson Lehton in London calculates that the raw material for
making AZT, mainly thymidine, costs $300 peruring costs between
$3,000 and $5,000 per kilogram.
   If she is right, this means the ingredients in a single 100
milligram capsule cost 3 cents, and manufacturing the product costs
30 to 50 cents.
   A few months after AZT was introduced in 1987, the company cut
its price 20 percent to the current level.
   Though the company refuses to speculate about further price cuts,
Walton said she expects another 20 percent price reduction within
the next year because of improvements in manufacturing, the growing
number of users and the likelihood that newer drugs will be easier
to make and probably cheaper.
   If the price stays the same, she said, sales of AZT could rise to
$800 million to $900 million in 1992.
   This prediction is based on the assumption that the drug will be
used by 40 percent of all people with serious symptoms of HIV
disease, 25 percent of those with early symptoms and 20 percent of
infected people with no symptoms.
