<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0300EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EnergyConflict     09-01 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Energy Conflict,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moore Says Ethics Ruling is New Blow to Yucca Mountain Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's ruling that an Energy Department
administrator committed an ethics violation will hurt the government
as it tries to revitalize its nuclear waste management program, the
agency's deputy secretary says.
   ``Of course it's a setback,'' Henson Moore said in a telephone
interview Thursday after the ethics finding was disclosed.
   U.S. Claims Court Judge Reginald Gibson found that Samuel Rousso,
acting director of the waste management office, violated a
conflict-of-interest law by helping award a $1 billion contract to a
group of companies that included one of his former employers.
   Moore said he was concerned that the ethics charge was another
blow to the department's credibility, which has been hurt in recent
years by a series of project failures. He suggested the blame should
be put on the Reagan administration.
   ``We're still seeing the fallout of things that happened before
we got here,'' he said.
   The 10-year contract in question calls for managing and
integrating the work of other contractors at the Yucca Mountain,
Nev., site where the department is trying to determine the
suitability of building an underground repository for nuclear waste.
   Gibson's finding was part of a broader ruling, released in
summary form last week, in which the judge blocked the Energy
Department from awarding the contract to Bechtel Management System
Inc., as Rousso and other department officials had recommended in
December.
   Among Bechtel's partners in the bid was Science Applications
International Corp., a San Diego-based engineering and consulting
company where Rousso worked from October 1985 to May 1986.
   The judge said the department could give the contract to no one
but TRW Inc., an unsuccessful bidder that sued the department on
grounds that Rousso's key role in the bid evaluation process had
biased the outcome in Bechtel's favor.
   Moore, the No. 2 Energy Department official, said the department
had not decided whether to appeal Gibson's ruling. He said senior
department officials would take a lengthy look at the situation,
which could lead to major changes in the Yucca Mountain project.
   Rousso joined the Energy Department in June 1986 _ one month
after leaving Science Applications _ and immediately became involved
in preparing for the Yucca Mountain bidding process. He was chairman
of a department panel that studied the various Yucca Mountain
contract bids and recommended Dec. 2 that the Bechtel team be chosen.
   Gibson said Rousso violated a federal ethics statute that
prohibits an Energy Department supervisor from participating in
department decisions involving any energy company that the
supervisor has worked for within the past year.
   Rousso declined to comment on the decision in a brief telephone
conversation Thursday. In an interview with The Associated Press
earlier this week, he said he had acted in good faith and believed
no conflict of interest had been shown.
   The conflict-of-interest statute at issue allows for civil
penalties of up to $10,000 for each violation, to be imposed by the
department head or a federal court.
   Agency spokesman Phil Keif said he didn't know whether the
department was considering seeking civil penalties against Rousso.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
