<HEAD>Quick Look At Heart Disease Survey</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-CDC--Heart Disease Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's a statistical portrait of people killed by
heart disease in the United States, from a survey of 6,665 deaths in
1986:
   Sex: Male (52 percent).
   Age: 65 or older (81 percent).
   Employment: Not working (87 percent).
   Health: Suffering from high blood pressure (54 percent).
Hospitalized or placed in nursing home during previous year (75
percent).
   Finances: Not wealthy. Family income less than $25,000 (82
percent), assets at death less than $50,000 (70 percent).
   Chief source of medical funds: Medicare (51 percent.)
