<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DrugHearing     09-01 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Hearing,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Wave of Narcotics Looming, Senate Committee Is Told</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new wave of narcotics with names such as
``croak,'' ``moon rock'' and ``parachute'' is hitting the nation's
streets along with a smokable form of heroin, authorities say.
   ``The drug cartels, like any successful marketers of a product,
are constantly working on new and improved models of their wares,''
Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said Thursday.
   ``Their innovation means more death and devastation for our
cities.''
   Methamphetamines, commonly called ``crank,'' as well as a mixture
of crack cocaine and heroin known as ``parachute,'' are among forms
of narcotics that could take root in the decade ahead, authorities
told a hearing of Biden's Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Also on the horizon are ``croak,'' a mixture of crack and
cocaine, and basuco, a cocaine derivative, authorities said. They
said users already are able to buy a synthetic form of heroin known
as ``P-funk.''
   Mixing crack and heroin staves off the suicidal depression, or
``crash,'' crack users feel soon after the burst of euphoria caused
by the drug, said Dr. Walter Faggett, substance abuse services
director at D.C. General Hospital.
   Heroin remains in wide use but is being sold in new forms, said
William Hopkins, director of street research for the New York State
division of substance abuse services.
   One is called ``his,'' or heroin in a straw. The powder is tapped
into the straw and the ends heat-sealed, Hopkins said.
   Pushers, he said, have taken to handing out business cards
stating the street corner where they can be found. The cards
sometimes contain partial phone numbers. ``At the last minute, they
add two digits,'' he testified.
   That makes it easy to shop by phone.
   ``You can order drugs and a kid will deliver them to you on a
bicycle,'' he said.
   Irate citizens are at times able to clear street corners of
pushers by holding anti-drug rallies, Hopkins said. But then
``steerers'' appear to herd addicts to corners a few blocks away
were sales are in progress, he said.
   Heroin is found in increasingly purer forms, Hopkins said.
   Young addicts are increasingly blending heroin and cocaine, he
said.
   ``Some of these young users shoot, some of them snort and some of
them smoke,'' he said. ``Some smoke it on joints, some smoke it on
tobacco, some smoke it on aluminum foil.''
   The drugs are burned on the foil while the users ``put a straw in
their nose and chase the fumes around the room,'' he said.
   David G. Binney, chief of the FBI's drug section, told the
committee that Chinese gangs have been active in importing heroin
from Burma, Thailand and Laos through West Coast ports in the United
States and Canada.
   Heroin production, primarily from the Mideast, Asia and Mexico,
appears to have doubled since 1985 and the evidence ``clearly
indicates that an increase of smokable heroin is on the horizon,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
