<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Benzene     09-01 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Benzene,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Curbs Won't Affect Major Source of Benzene Pollution: Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tighter controls are expected to sharply reduce
releases by industry of the cancer-causing chemical benzene, but
federal officials acknowledge the curbs won't affect the biggest
offender: the automobile.
   Industrial releases account for about 20 percent of all benzene
releases in the country, said Jack Farmer, director of the
Environmental Protection Agency's air emissions standard division.
   Most of the other emissions come from automobiles, although small
amounts also are found in cigarette smoke and various consumer
products.
   Benzene, a flammable, colorless and odorless liquid, escapes into
the air after evaporating either through various industrial
processes or from the automobile as the engine heats.
   Chronic exposure to benzene has been found to cause adult
leukemia, birth defects and other ailments.
   The EPA announced Thursday that it would impose new emission
control requirements on industry aimed at cutting by 90 percent the
more than 40,000 tons of industrial benzene released into the air
each year.
   Most affected will be the steel and petroleum industries, which
will have to install nearly $1 billion in emission-control equipment
at coke production plants as well as at gasoline storage,
distribution and marketing facilities.
   The EPA listed benzene as a hazardous air pollutant in 1977.
   The curbs on industrial benzene pollution were seen as a
significant step coming after a dozen years of debate, but EPA
officials acknowledged the rules address only a relatively small
percentage of the benzene spewed into the air each year.
   While the rules were expected to cut emissions in the steel
industry by 97 percent and in the petroleum industry about 65
percent, they don't address releases when gasoline is pumped into a
car or emissions during the vehicle's operation, officials said.
   However, William Rosenberg, assistant EPA administrator for air
and radiation, said the agency will propose separate regulations
next month aimed at dealing with toxic vapor releases from
automobiles as engines become hot.
   In addition to requiring changes in the composition of gasoline
to reduce vapor releases, Rosenberg said the agency will consider
requiring auto manufacturers to install additional equipment to
capture vapor emissions, including benzene releases.
   Clean air legislation before Congress includes provisions aimed
at reducing the release of toxic chemicals _ including benzene _
from motor vehicles both through tailpipe exhausts and vapor losses
from the engine and fuel systems.
   The EPA estimated overall costs for the new regulations on
industrial benzene pollution were at about $1.3 billion for initial
installation of equipment, with another $200 million annual cost for
maintenance and operation of the new equipment.
   ``These will be costly, but feasible controls,'' said F. Henry
Habicht, deputy EPA administrator, adding that they ``will protect
public health from the risks associated with industrial benzene
exposure.''
   Habicht said the emission reductions are designed to reduce the
chance of a person eventually getting cancer as a result of benzene
exposure to less than one in 1 million when considering the entire
population.
   The risk are higher _ perhaps as much as one in 10,000 _ for
people that live near industrial plants or facilities where there
continue to be high amounts of benzene, Habicht said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0527EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d p PM-BRF--Leland-Seat     09-01 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Leland-Seat,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Houston City Councilman Announces Bid for Leland's Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race to fill the the late U.S. Rep. Mickey
Leland's seat intensified with a Houston city councilman adding his
name to the list of candidates.
   Councilman Anthony Hall will be vying for the seat against state
Sen. Craig Washington and state Rep. Al Edwards, who announced their
candidacies for the 18th Congressional District last week. Hall, who
announced his candidacy Thursday, lost to Leland for the same seat
in 1978.
   Gov. Bill Clements set the special election for Nov. 7, the same
day as Houston's city elections. Hall will have to resign his
position as councilman at large to run for Congress.
   Earlier this week, Leland's widow, Alison, citing her family as
her primary concern, said she would not seek her late husband's job.
Mrs. Leland said she would support Houston City Councilman Rodney
Ellis, who has yet to announce his election plans.
   Leland and 15 others were killed Aug. 7 in a plane crash in
Ethiopia while on a hunger relief mission to a refugee camp.
