<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Barry-Drugs     09-01 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Calls New Allegations `Character Assassination'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry is calling new allegations
that he has used drugs part of a campaign by federal officials to
malign his character.
   Barry reacted angrily to news reports Thursday that a convicted
drug dealer who faces additional charges in the nation's capital has
told authorities that he and the mayor used drugs together.
   ``Through leaks to the press and other sources, federal
authorities have done what they set out to do _ to get headlines and
to assassinate my character,'' Barry said in a statement read by his
staff director, Maudine Cooper. ``This is lawlessness by the
government.''
   The mayor was vacationing in Rehobeth Beach, Del., and could not
be reached to comment beyond his prepared statement.
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens would not say whether Charles
Lewis, the drug suspect, has implicated Barry in interrogations by
federal agents. But Stephens said he wants the Justice Department to
investigate whether stories about Lewis' cooperation originated with
law enforcement officials.
   Lewis has been charged with perjury, cocaine possession and
trafficking in a federal probe that began last December, when
district police inexplicably called off an undercover attempt to
make a drug buy from him after learning that Barry was in Lewis'
hotel room.
   Lewis was convicted on drug charges in the Virgin Islands earlier
this year. Sentencing on that conviction has been postponed
indefinitely.
   For the past several years Barry has been dogged by persistent
rumors that he uses drugs. In his statement Thursday, he repeated
his declaration that he never saw or used drugs during at least six
visits to Lewis' hotel room.
   Despite those denials, top city officials said the newest rumors
about Barry's alleged drug use are harming his bid for re-election.
   ``I was up until 3 a.m. talking to some prior supporters about
this,'' said one top Barry aide, who asked not to be identified. ``A
number of these people say he just can't run for mayor, and they
won't support him.''
   Said another aide, ``All eight people I talked to this morning
said they would not back him. Some of these people were tireless
volunteers, others had been major contributors.''
   Barry is among four people who have announced their candidacies
for the Democratic mayoral nomination. And the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
who has moved to Washington, has failed to completely discount
rumors that he also will run.
   The mayor was scheduled to unveil district drug czar Sterling
Tucker's new anti-drug strategy Friday, but three top city sources
said Barry had scuttled that plan. Cooper said Barry would not
return to work until next Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
