<FIRST>r w PM-Noriega-Wealth     09-01 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noriega-Wealth,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagleburger Details Noriega's Wealth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has three yachts,
three Lear jets, a farm in France and a $600,000 mansion in Panama
City, Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger says.
   Speaking Thursday to the Organization of American States,
Eagleburger detailed what he described as Noriega's personal assets.
He estimated Noriega's fortune at between $200 million and $300
million.
   The Panama City mansion contains nearly 50 valuable oil
paintings, and Noriega also has a chalet near a Panamanian air strip
in Rio Hato, Eagleburger said.
   Noriega also owns a vacation home on Madden Lake, Panama, a
mountain retreat and several houses on 60 acres in Chiriqui
Province, Eagleburger said. The French farm is about 50 minutes from
Paris, and Noriega also has a luxury apartment in an elite section
of Paris, the U.S. official said.
   Noriega's wife bought furniture, art objects and antiques valued
in the millions of dollars for several luxury apartments he owns in
the Dominican Republic, Eagleburger said.
   He owns various aircraft, including three Lear jets and a
twin-engine plane. Eagleburger said Noriega bought a sophisticated
helicopter for his personal use for $2 million in 1984, and that a
$2.2 million Boeing 727 was used for money laundering.
   Noriega's three large pleasure yachts are called ``the Macho I,
Macho II and Macho III,'' Eagleburger said.
   In December 1987, Eagleburger said, Noriega decorated himself
with an $85,000 ``Eagle Medal,'' made of gold and precious stones.
   Eagleburger also told the OAS that one of Noriega's daughter's
reportedly spent $50,000 in a one-day shopping spree in New York.
The Noriega family ran up tens of thousands of dollars in charges at
the Helmsley Palace in New York, he said.
