<HEAD>Dollar Rises Sharply, Tokyo Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 3 grafs with closings; pickup 4th graf pvs, `Currency
dealers...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged against the Japanese yen Friday,
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell moderately.
   The dollar closed at 145.45 yen, up 1.17 yen from Thursday's
close. After opening at 144.95 yen, the dollar ranged between 144.80
yen and 145.58 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 82.98
points, or 0.24 percent, closing the week at 34,348.22. It lost
40.46 points Thursday.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's firmness followed its sharp
Wednesday afternoon rally in New York, sparked by speculation that
the U.S. Treasury Department was allowing the dollar's rise as long
as the American economy remains stable.
   ``It was mere speculation, but it worked'' to affect the exchange
market, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke anonymously.
   The dealer said the bullish sentiment for the dollar ``still
remains in the market.''
   He said the dollar has been relatively stable since Monday's
report that the U.S. merchandise trade deficit declined to $27.7
billion in the second quarter, down from $28.4 billion in the first
quarter.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed 215.99 points Wednesday, gained 33.13 points, or
0.09 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 34,504.79.
