<FIRST>r a PM-TimesPublisher     09-01 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Times Publisher,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Times Names David Laventhol Publisher, CEO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Corp. President David Laventhol
has been named publisher and chief executive officer of the media
company's flagship newspaper, the Los Angeles Times.
   Laventhol will replace W. Thomas Johnson Jr., who has been
publisher of the newspaper for nine years, said Robert F. Erburu,
chairman and chief executive officer of Times Mirror.
   With Laventhol's appointment, Erburu said Johnson will ``assume
new companywide responsibilities,'' including chairmanship of the
Times Mirror newspaper management committee, a policymaking group
that shapes the company's strategies in newspaper publishing.
   ``To be publisher of the Los Angeles Times is to be at the center
of the most exciting journalistic enterprise in the country,''
Laventhol said after the announcement Thursday. ``I am happy to have
this opportunity, and I'm grateful to Tom Johnson for leading the
Times through nine years of growth and editorial excellence.
   ``I look forward to working with the men and women of the Times
to produce an even better newspaper.''
   Johnson, speaking to the newspaper's executives, said: ``Things
are going so well here _ circulation is going up, profits are going
up, a new plant is going up _ that Bob Erburu thought I should be
going up as well. And I am, up to the sixth floor of Times Mirror.
   ``After 12 wonderful years _ three as president, nine as
publisher of the Times, it is now time for a change.''
   The newspaper's revenues during the past 12 years grew from $333
million to more than $1 billion. Circulation increased to 1.12
million daily from 1 million and to 1.43 million Sunday from 1.29
million.
   The paper won eight Pulitzer prizes in the last 12 years.
   Laventhol, 55, has been president of Times Mirror since 1987 and
will continue in that position. Laventhol was editor of Newsday, a
daily the company owns on New York's Long Island, from 1970 to 1978
and served as publisher of Newsday from 1978 to 1987.
   Laventhol previously worked at The Washington Post.
   Johnson, 47, will continue to serve as vice chairman of Times
Mirror, will oversee joint marketing efforts of the company's
newspapers and other media operations and will be involved in
acquisition of additional operations.
   Times Mirror also publishes The Sun in Baltimore, The Morning
Call in Allentown, Pa., and three Connecticut newspapers: The
Hartford Courant, The Advocate (of Stamford) and Greenwich Time.
</TEXT>
