<FIRST>r i PM-Mandela     09-01 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Government To Consider Mandela's Release After Next Week's
Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will consider
freeing Nelson Mandela after next week's elections and the
anti-apartheid leader won't have to renounce violence to get out of
prison, a newspaper reported.
   ``We are not wedded to the demand that he should distance himself
from violence before he is released,'' Justice Minister Kobie
Coetsee said in an interview published Thursday in Die Volksblad, a
newspaper supporting the National Party government.
   ``We will judge the matter objectively, not just on the grounds
of rejecting violence,'' Coetsee said. ``I think the matter will
undoubtedly get F.W. de Klerk's attention after Sept. 6.''
   De Klerk, the nation's acting president, is expected to be chosen
for a full five-year term following the election. He became acting
president after P.W. Botha resigned Aug. 14.
   Until last year, Botha insisted that Mandela, the 71-year-old
leader of the African National Congress, renounce violence in
exchange for freedom.
   Mandela, imprisoned since 1962, is serving a life term for his
conviction on sabotage and plotting to overthrow the government.
   Coetsee arranged a meeting between Botha and Mandela on July 5 at
the president's official residence. At that meeting, Coetsee said,
Mandela had ``endorsed peaceful development.''
   Mandela, the country's best-known black leader, has said he won't
renounce violence until the government dismantles apartheid and
legalizes the ANC.
   Coetsee said he believed Mandela was a moderate figure in the
circles that ``we normally describe as revolutionary.''
   He described Mandela as being a man who ``would not leave his
people in the lurch'' and as having ``an old world, almost an old
Roman'' approach to values.
</TEXT>
