<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0449EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-01 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar UP, Nikkei Sluggish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rallied against the yen today,
overpowering intervention by Japan's central bank to stem the
currency's upswing, while trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange was
sluggish.
   The dollar closed at 145.45 yen, up 1.17 yen from Thursday's
close. It opened at 144.95 yen and ranged between 144.80 and 145.58
yen.
   ``Dollar-buying pressure overpowered aggressive intervention by
the central bank, made intermittently throughout the trading day,''
said a dealer with Sanwa Bank, a major Japanese commercial bank, who
spoke anonymously.
   Currency dealers said the Bank of Japan stepped into the market,
selling dollars at about 144.95 yen. The Bank of Japan sold an
estimated $700 million during the day, market sources said.
   The central bank does not comment on its market activities.
   The Sanwa dealer said the dollar's strength was attributed to
predictions that U.S. unemployment figures for August, due out in
Washington today, would show an improvement.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 40.46 points Thursday, shed another 82.98 points,
or 0.24 percent, closing the week at 34,348.22.
   Yozo Asai of Yamaichi Securities said the stock market generally
remained weak, centering on major steels and constructions.
   ``A sluggish mood is caused partly by uncertainties over the
exchange-rate movements,'' Asai said.
   Volume traded on the first section totaled 600 million shares,
compared with 650 million shares Thursday.
   Meanwhile, Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto denied a rumor,
spread on the New York market Thursday, that he was involved in
insider trading in the merger of two major Japanese commercial
banks, Kyodo News Service said.
   ``I've never done it. These kind of rumors give me an extremely
unpleasant feeling,'' Kyodo quoted Hashimoto as saying.
   On Tuesday, Mitsui Bank and Taiyo Kobe Bank announced their plans
to merge in April. Together they would become Japan's second-largest
bank in terms of assets after the Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, the world's
largest.
</TEXT>
