<FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather     09-01 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Gabrielle Forms in Eastern Atlantic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gabrielle surprised weather experts with
its quick development from a tropical storm into the fourth
hurricane of the Atlantic season, forecasters said.
   ``It was a little faster than anticipated,'' Jim Gross of the
National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables said this morning.
   Gabrielle strengthened quickly as it pushed away from the African
coast and passed the hurricane threshold late Thursday. It had
maximum sustained winds of 75 mph, with higher gusts in squalls,
forecasters said.
   At 6 a.m. EDT, Gabrielle was centered near 11.9 degrees north
latitude and 33.8 degrees west longitude, or about 625 miles west
southwest of the westernmost Cape Verde Islands. It was moving west
at 17 mph.
   Meanwhile, Felix weakened again to a tropical depression in the
central North Atlantic as its winds dropped to 35 mph. Felix had
become a tropical storm for the second time briefly when its winds
picked up to 40 mph on Thursday.
   At 6 a.m. EDT, Felix was near 30.9 north latitude and 41.5 west
longitude, or about 700 miles southwest of the Azores moving to the
west northwest at 12 mph. The depression was expected to continue on
this course today with little change in strength.
   Neither storm is an immediate threat to land, Gross said.
   A depression becomes a storm when its winds hit 39 mph, and a
hurricane when they reach 74 mph.
</TEXT>
