<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Lebanon     09-01 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanon,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Guerrilla Near Lebanese Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops clashed today with several
guerrillas in Israel's self-declared security zone in south Lebanon.
An army spokesman said one guerrilla was killed and two escaped.
   Security sources in Lebanon said a fourth gunman may have escaped
after being wounded in the clash.
   During the fighting, two Soviet-made Katyusha rockets exploded in
northern Israel causing no damage, security sources said. The
rockets were apparently fired from outside the security zone near
the area of the clash.
   The clash happened before dawn near the village of Beit Yahun,
six miles northwest of the Israeli border, said an Israeli army
spokesman, who requested anonymity in line with military regulations.
   The spokesman said the dead gunman carried a Soviet-made AK-47
assault rifle and large amounts of ammunition and plastic explosives.
   Later, soldiers showed reporters the body of the dead guerrilla,
who was wearing a camouflage uniform. The soldiers also showed three
Kalashnikov assault guns, two of which apparently belonged to the
escaped fighters.
   On Thursday, another round of Katyusha rockets struck near a
house in northern Israel smashing windows but causing no injuries.
   Military spokesmen said they did not know which militia the
guerrilla killed today may have belonged to.
   The last attack in the security zone was on August 9, when a
suicide car bomb carrying 550 pounds of explosives was detonated
near an Israeli military convoy, wounding five Israeli troops and an
allied Lebanese militiaman. Two men in the car were killed.
   Hezbollah, the Shiite Moslem fundamentalist militia, claimed
responsibility for the attack and said it was in retalitation for
Israel's kidnapping of a pro-Iranian Lebanese clergyman. Israeli
troops abducted Shiite cleric Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid from his home
in south Lebanon. Israeli troops along the northern border have been
on alert in anticipation of Hezbollah attacks.
   Israel created the security zone in 1985 as a buffer zone after
withdrawing the bulk of its force following a three-year occupation.
   The 2-to-12-mile-wide zone is patrolled by Israeli soldiers and
the 2,500-member Israeli-supported South Lebanon Army militia.
