<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     09-01 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Leader Claims Moslem Infiltration Repulsed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops bombarded the Christian
heartland today in fierce artillery battles that left at least seven
people dead and 55 wounded.
   Police said the casualties came after midnight in clashes that
escalated after the Christian leader, Gen. Michel Aoun, claimed his
troops repulsed two infiltration attempts by Syrian-backed
militiamen during the night.
   The latest casualties raised the overall toll in nearly six
months of fighting to at least 819 killed and 2,409 wounded.
   Police said the Syrians were shelling the entire 310-square-mile
Christian enclave north of Beirut. The Christian port of Jounieh
north of Beirut was pounded by hundreds of shells and rockets.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said 80 shells a minute were hitting the enclave as
Christian gunners tried to knock out the Syrian artillery.
   Apartment buildings burned out of control in both parts of
divided Beirut and other areas as the Syrian army and Christian
forces battled through the night and morning.
   One Christian shell blasted the second-floor apartment of Mustafa
Najjar, 33, a soundman with the London-based Visnews television
agency, in the Aishe Bakkar neighborhood of Moslem west Beirut.
   Najjar carried his 8-year-old daughter and 7-year-old son through
the flames to safety. But his wife, Amal, 27, was burned to death,
neighbors said. She was one of seven civilians killed Thursday.
   Ambulances sped through the deserted, smoke-filled streets of
west Beirut taking casualties to hospitals.
   About 90 percent of the city's 1.5 million people have fled the
carnage in recent weeks, leaving an estimated 200,000 people
huddling in basement bunkers and underground garages in the
shell-blasted capital.
   Shells exploded around the once-thriving Hamra business section
and the once-fashionable Ras Beirut residential neighborhood in the
city's Moslem sector at noon.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command said the night-time attacks by
Syria's allies in Beirut and east Lebanon were apparent infiltration
attempt to probe Christian defenses.
   The spokesman, who declined to be named, said one group of 12
militiamen tried to penetrate from Syrian-controlled Moslem west
Beirut near the harbor on the eastern end of the capital's dividing
Green Line.
   Another group tried to ``infiltrate across our lines'' in the
Ein-Tuffaha sector on the mountainous eastern flank of the Christian
enclave.
   ``Both attempts were repulsed,'' the spokesman said. ``We believe
they were reconnaissance attempts by Syria's allies to feel out our
combat readiness.''
   He said Aoun's 155mm guns scored several direct hits on a Syrian
ammunition dump in the mountain town of Bolonia, 15 miles northeast
of Beirut.
   ``The depot exploded in a ball of fire that was followed by a
chain of blasts in the pine woods around Bolonia,'' the spokesman
said.
   The Christians claimed their forces knocked out a Syrian tank in
the Druse Moslem hamlet of Abadiyeh, six miles east of Beirut with
106mm cannons.
   Syrian headquarters in Lebanon declined comment on the Christian
claims.
   Police said Syrian guns in west Beirut were shelling the 28-mile
stretch of Mediterranean coast north of Beirut held by the
Christians.
   The enclave is ringed by Syrian troops and their allies on its
three landward sides. The coastal strip is the Christians' only
lifeline to the outside world.
   A witness in west Beirut said Syrian artillery fire forced ``a
big ship'' off the Christian-held coastline to flee when it tried to
run the blockade the Syrians imposed in mid-March to stop arms and
other supplies reaching Aoun's beleaguered forces.
   ``The ship turned around when the shelling started,'' said the
witness, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Shells are falling
around it. Aoun's men are shelling the Syrian artillery to take the
pressure off it.''
</TEXT>
