<FIRST>r a PM-Child-Kennel     09-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child-Kennel,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Charge Grandparents Of 4-Year-Old In Pen</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MUS1 of Aug. 31</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKOGEE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grandparents of a 4-year-old boy were
charged with keeping the child in a squalid outdoor pen during the
day, with no toilet and just a bottle of water, officials said.
   Gene and Joyce White said they built the caged pen for the boy to
keep him from roaming out onto a nearby highway.
   ``If that excuse is satisfactory, it will be up to a judge or
jury, but it is not satisfactory to me,'' District Attorney Drew
Edmondson said Thursday. ``The boy was kept in a 10-foot pen with a
wire fence on two sides and board fence on the other two sides so it
could not be seen from the highway.
   ``There was a bean bag-type chair and toys inside the pen. Water
was in a baby bottle, which was in the dirt, and there was no toilet
facilities except in a corner of the pen. There was no roof, and the
pen was covered only by a tree,'' he said.
   The Whites faced a misdemeanor charge usually filed in cases of
failure to pay child support. The ``omitting to provide'' charge
carries a year in jail or a $500 fine.
   Edmondson that was the only charge available to prosecutors. ``We
looked at the child abuse statutes very carefully, and our feeling
is it requires an injury or maiming of the child, which is not
present in this case.''
   The boy, his 11-year-old cousin and the Whites' 13-year-old
daughter who also lived in their recreational vehicle were taken
into custody Tuesday by the state Department of Human Services.
   Child welfare investigators will hold a hearing to determine if
the children should be returned to the home or placed in temporary
custody elsewhere.
   Investigators said the boy appeared to be well-nourished and had
no apparent injuries.
   The boy's mother left him with the grandparents when he was 2,
and the boy's father apparently works in another city, said
sheriff's Deputy Patrick Howland.
</TEXT>
