<DOCNO> AP890901-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0919EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeCollapse     09-01 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Study Scaffolding Used Before Bridge Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal highway officials scrutinized the
scaffolding used during the construction of a bridge that collapsed
on a major Baltimore-Washington thoroughfare, injuring 14 people.
   The overpass collapsed Thursday during the morning rush hour as
workers poured concrete onto the bridge.
   ``All of a sudden, I saw these big blocks of concrete hitting my
hood,'' said Earnest L. Izzard, 52. ``I thought I was a goner, but
something inside _ I'm sure it was God _ kept me calm.''
   ``It was like a mountain coming down toward you,'' said Thomas
Rogers, 53, of Baltimore, who was riding in the back seat of
Izzard's car. ``I don't know how we made it.''
   Another driver, Kimberly Sue Andersen, 30, of Elkridge, got
deluged with debris and was pinned in her car until rescue workers
pulled her out. She was taken to the Maryland Schock Trauma Center
with head injuries and a fractured jaw. She was listed in critical
but stable condition today.
   Four other passengers and nine construction workers were also
injured. Some of workers went down with the bridge when it fell.
   ``I was right on the bridge,'' said David Klein, 25, a
construction worker from Hanover. ``I heard the metal giving way. I
was wondering if I was going to be alive when I hit bottom.''
   Highway officials say they want to determine whether the bridge's
steel and wood scaffolding was damaged when it was moved from a
bridge that runs parallel to the one that collapsed.
   Such scaffolding is commonly used in bridge construction to
provide a temporary support of the wet concrete deck of the bridge
until the concrete sets.
   The collapsed overpass was one of four bridges being built as
part of a $6.2 million interchange project on the federally owned
parkway at Route 198. When the two bridges over the northbound
parkway lanes were built, the contractors dismantled the scaffolding
after finishing the first bridge and set it up again to build the
second bridge.
   Workers at the site said Thursday that the general contractors,
Associated Marjon Inc. of Ashland, Va., and J.P. Smith of Edgewater,
Md., used that procedure to save time. Construction on the bridges
began in March 1987 and was to be completed by this November.
   Company officials could not be reached Thursday, but federal
officials and the contractor on the first two bridges said the
practice is not unusual.
