<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Colombia     09-01 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Colombia,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Asks Israel's Help in Finding Israei Tied to Noriega, Report
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has asked Israel to help
persuade a former Israeli intelligence agent to leave Panama, where
he is a top adviser to Gen. Manuel Noriega, a newspaper reported
today.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said he has no information on any U.S. request concerning Mike
Harari, a former agent of Israel's Mossad intelligenge agency.
   The spokesman added that Harari is a private citizen and Israel
has no influence over his overseas activities.
   Harari is believed to be a security adviser to Noriega, the chief
of Panamanian Defense Forces, who U.S. official say plays a major
role in the flow of drugs into the United States.
   Also today, the Defense Ministry began evacuating from Colombia
the families of Defense Ministry and military industry officials,
Israel media reported.
   Israeli newspapers said Israel is concerned about threats to the
families that were made after reports surfaced that Israeli
ex-commandos trained militias for Colombian drug barons.
   The independent mass-circulation Hadashot newspaper said U.S.
officials believe Harari has detailed information on Noriega's
involvement in drug dealings and informed Israeli officials that
they are interested in questioning Harari.
   The newspaper quoted U.S. officials as saying that Harari's close
relationship with Noriega could cause damage to Israel.
   Hadashot said the United States has been interested in
questioning Harari for several months. The newspaper said Harari
flew to Miami in June on a forged passport but left before FBI
officials discovered he was in the United States.
   The independent Maariv newspaper said the order to evacuate the
families of Israeli officials and businessmen in Colombia was made
after some began receiving death threats from anonymous callers
believed tied to drug cartels.
   The Colombian drug traffickers, Maariv said, are angry about an
Israeli offer to aid Colombia in its fight against narcotics.
   Israeli officials said they have made little progress in an
investigation of four ex-commandos suspected of training hit squads
for drug dealers.
   The head of the police investigations unit, Yehoshua Caspi, said
no information has been found tying reserve Lt. Col. Yair Klein to
drug dealers.
   Klein has admitted giving paramilitary training in Colombia but
said it was for ranchers threatened with guerrilla attack and not
for drug dealers.
   Caspi said police are still waiting for information from the
Colombian police on Klein's involvement, and officials have said the
investigation may be dropped if such evidence is not provided.
   But an American journalist said he was shown a videotape Klein
made in Colombia in which know drug cartel figures appeared along
with the Israeli.
   Kenneth Freed of the Los Angeles Times said on Israel radio he
was shown the video by the head of Colombia's security services.
   He said that in the video ``there was a man named Vladimir, who
was one of the most notorious and well-known agents of the drug
traffickers.''
</TEXT>
