<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0951EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CrashRescue     09-01 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash Rescue,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boaters Rescue Three Whose Plane Crashed in Water After Running Out
of Gas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERLY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passing pleasure boat rescued three
people who ditched their single-engine plane in Rhode Island Sound
after running out of gas, the Coast Guard said.
   The plane, flying from Block Island to Westerly, sank in 60 feet
of water Thursday afternoon, but the pilot and two passengers clung
to lobster buoys for about 15 minutes until they were rescued, said
Petty Officer William Murray of the Point Judith Coast Guard
station. No one was injured, he said.
   The pilot, Nicholas Heineman, 61, of Stamford, Conn., told the
Coast Guard a faulty fuel gauge caused him to run out of gas about
two miles south of Weekapaug Point, Murray said.
   The crash of the single-engine, six-seat Cessna 210 was reported
about 1 p.m. by a passing sailboat, Murray said. He said fishermen
aboard the Mickey II rescued Heineman and passengers John Lehman,
48, of Greenwich, Conn., and John T. Dennis, 50, of Poughkeepsie,
after they spent about 15 minutes in the 65-degree water.
   ``They were lucky that they weren't injured in the crash,''
Murray said. ``They must have had a good landing in the water to get
out of it without injury.''
   One of the passengers, an amateur photographer, wanted to try to
re-enter the wreckage to retrieve his camera, but his companions
persuaded him not to, Murray said.
   He said he did not know who owned the plane. Marianne Brown, an
attendant at the Block Island State Airport, said it was a private
plane, not one of the charter aircraft that regularly fly between
Westerly and the island.
</TEXT>
