<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Plane     09-01 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Plane,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airliner With 54 People Still Missing After One Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pakistani airliner with 54 people
aboard was still missing today, a week after it disappeared on a
flight over the Himalayas.
   ``We're changing the strategy of the search,'' said Pakistan
International Airlines spokeswoman Azra Sultan.
   ``Aircraft have searched every nook and cranny of the mountains
at high altitude but now we're going to concentrate on the
valleys,'' she said.
   The propeller-driven Fokker 27 failed to arrive Aug. 25 on a
one-hour flight from the northern mountain town of Gilgit to
Islamabad, the capital, 175 miles to the south.
   It carried 49 passengers, including Americans Paul McGorrian of
St. Petersburg, Fla., and Vida Sibrys of Streator, Ill., and five
crew members. The Americans were believed to be the only foreigners
aboard.
   The Pakistan air force and army, PIA, the United Nations and
private groups have conducted the largest air and ground search in
the country's history.
   Many of the mountains are covered with snow that could make
wreckage invisible from the air, PIA officials said.
   Four Pakistani aircraft have crashed in the area since 1963. An
air force C-130 was missing for three months before mountain
villagers discovered it.
   The flight over and through Pakistan's northern mountains is
known as one of the most hazardous commercial air routes in the
world. PIA pilots fly it only in clear weather.
   It offers a breathtaking view of the western Himalaya range and
the winding Indus River valley.
</TEXT>
