<SECOND>PM-HUD-Ritz,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Former HUD Official Lobbied for Luxury Funding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former official with the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development was paid at least $200,000 to help
lobby for HUD financing of a luxury Manhattan apartment building, a
newspaper reported today.
   New York Newsday said HUD eventually agreed to provide an $85
million mortgage for the building.
   Alexander Naclerio was hired to lobby on behalf of the Ritz Plaza
developers in 1986, 11 months after he left his job as director of
housing in HUD's New York office and as top aide to former regional
director Joseph Monticciolo, Newsday said.
   The 479 apartments in the nearly completed 44-story building in
midtown Manhattan will rent for $1,702 to $3,929 a month.
   The project would have been eligible for a $35 million Federal
Housing Administration insured mortgage, but Naclerio argued that
housing costs were higher in New York and that the developer had
purchased neighboring air rights so the Ritz Plaza could be bigger.
   HUD officials agreed to the higher mortgage, the paper reported.
   Naclerio is expected to testify about his role in the Ritz
project when he appears before the House government operations
committee, which is investigating the awarding of federal housing
subsidies under the Reagan administration.
