<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Tritium 1stLd-Writethru a0450 09-01 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tritium, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Resumes Tritium Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with department resuming commercial sales of
tritium; picks up 5th graf pvs, `I have'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said today it has resumed
commercial sales of tritium after investigators concluded that
missing amounts of the radioactive gas were not diverted for use in
building nuclear warheads.
   In the meantime, a team of department specialists is pressing an
investigation of missing amounts of tritium shipped from the Oak
Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee to two British companies,
said Phil Keif, a DOE spokesman.
   Keif said discrepancies over how much tritium was shipped to
commercial customers had been resolved, except for the cases of the
British companies, Surelite and Saunders-Roe Developments Ltd. He
said department officials had discounted the possibility that the
missing amounts had been diverted to bomb production.
   ``I don't think anybody thinks that,'' Keif said.
   Tritium is used in biological and energy research and for
production of luminous lights such as those used on airport runways,
as well as signs, dials and watches. It is used in nuclear warheads
to boost the weapons' explosive power.
   The Energy Department had announced last July that it was halting
commercial sales until it could account for about 5 grams of mssing
tritium. Total annual commercial sales of the man-made gas are about
180 grams, it said.
   The decision to resume sales on a limited scale was made Aug. 16.
At the same time, a special team was formed to work out the shipment
discrepancies that had not been resolved during a two-month search
by a joint team of DOE and Nuclear Regulatory Commission officials,
Keif said.
   Keif said a series of eight tritium shipments to E.I. du Pont de
Nemours &amp; Co. for use in biomedical work started Aug. 25 and was
continuing. He said a full-scale resumption of sales would begin
sometime in September after the department had fully installed a set
of tighter controls at the Oak Ridge laboratory.
   Tritium is produced at the Savannah River nuclear reactors, near
Aiken, S.C., but all three active reactors there have been shut down
for more than a year to correct mechanical and management problems.
   DOE said Thursday that no decision will be made until spring on
an exact date for resuming tritium production. In a statement,
Energy Secretary James D. Watkins denied a Washington Post report
that he had decided to recommend to President Bush that the first of
the three reactors be restarted next July.
   ``I have made no final decision on a recommended restart schedule
for any of the department's Savannah River production reactors, and
do not intend to speculate prematurely on possible restart dates,''
Watkins said.
   Watkins also said that even after he makes a recommendation on a
proposed restart date, no exact date could be set until next spring.
Henson Moore, the deputy energy secretary, said in a telephone
interview that Watkins meant uncertainties about technical reactor
issues would probably persist for several more months.
   Moore said that while Watkins had made no final decision on a
recommendation, ``we have a target date in mind'' for restarting the
first Savannah River reactor. Moore said he couldn't disclose the
target date.
   The Post story said Watkins would tell Bush next week that
waiting another 10 months to restart the aging Savannah River
reactors would not jeopardize national security.
   Tritium production is vital to nuclear weapons production because
the gas decays at a rate of 5.5 percent a year and thus must be
regularly replenished to keep the nuclear arsenal fully ready.
   Becky McSwain, a spokeswoman for Westinghouse Savannah River Co.,
which manages the reactor complex under an Energy Department
contract, said Thursday the company would have no comment on the
Post report.
   Earlier, Ms. McSwain acknowledged that Westinghouse two months
ago had recommended to Watkins that the first of the three reactors
at Savannah River be restarted in September 1990, and that Watkins
had indicated he wanted an earlier restart.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Earthquake     09-01 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Earthquake,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tremor Causes Damage But No Casualties in Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake struck the Patras region in
western Greece today, damaging 22 buildings but causing no injuries,
police said.
   The Athens Geodynamic Institute said the tremor, which measured
4.8 on the Richter scale, occurred shortly after midnight and was
centered 105 miles west of the capital, on the Peloponnesus
peninsula just south of the city of Patras.
   A police spokesman in Patras said that 22 buildings in the city
had been damaged. Two apartment blocks suffered cracks on the ground
floor, he said.
   He said no injuries were reported but that there was widespread
panic in the city. ``We could not believe that the earthquake was
only of magnitude 4.8,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``It felt much stronger, and many people spent the rest
of the night in their cars or in parks.''
   Earthquakes are frequent in western Greece, with one registering
5.9 on the Richter scale being recorded on Aug. 20 and another
registering 5.7 being recorded on Aug. 24. No damage or injuries
resulted from those quakes.
   The Richter scale is a guage of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   A magnitude 5 quake can cause considerable damage.
</TEXT>
