<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1054EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     09-01 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Spills Crude Oil in Delaware River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARCUS HOOK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of gallons of crude oil spilled
into the Delaware River when valves were improperly set on an oil
tanker discharging its cargo at a refinery.
   The 865-foot tanker Minerva had unloaded about 480,000 gallons of
its 500,000-gallon cargo and was preparing to take on watter as
ballast when the accident occurred Thursday, said Chuck Webster,
spokesman for the British Petroleum Refinery where the tanker was
unloading.
   Webster said about 600 gallons of crude oil was lost, covering an
8-mile-long area of water. The Coast Guard, which initially
estimated the spill at 4,200 gallons, later revised its figure to
``at least 1,000'' but added that the British Petroleum estimate
could be accurate.
   Coast Guard officials said there were no reports of affected
wildlife.
   The Coast Guard said representatives from the ship and refinery
immediately notified authorities after the spill, and Webster said
booms were lowered into the river within five minutes of the spill.
   ``About half the oil spilled was contained by a boom in the
vicinity of the ship,'' Lt. Jim Weakley said.
   The Coast Guard reported that 500 gallons of oil had been
recovered as of late Thursday.
   The Minerva is owned by Argo Dua Shipping PTE Ltd. of Singapore,
Webster said.
   It was the second spill on the Delaware in less than three
months. The first occurred June 24, when workers on the Presidente
Rivera prematurely dropped anchor, sending the Uruguayan tanker out
of control. The tanker ran aground just south of the
Pennsylvania-Delaware state line, spilling 300,000 gallons of thick
heating oil.
</TEXT>
