<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0442 09-01 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Ally Sworn in as President of Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with president sworn in, Bush
statement. Pick up 10th pvs, `Panamanian authorities...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Francisco Rodriguez, a high school
classmate of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, was sworn in as president
today. President Bush announced there would be no diplomatic
contacts with the new government.
   In a televised ceremony at the Supreme Court, court president
Marisol Reyes de Vasquez administered the oath of office to
Rodriguez and Vice President Carlos Ozores. The proceedings were
closed to the press and diplomats.
   In a statement, Bush said the U.S. ambassador to Panama, Arthur
Davis, would not return. Davis was called back to Washington in May.
   Bush also said the administration will ``continue to take other
steps ... to deprive the illegal regime of funds that belong to the
Panamanian people.'' He did not elaborate.
   After the oath of office, Mrs. Vasquez and Rodriguez exchanged
the traditional embrace and he then donned the presidential sash.
The 10-member court attended the ceremony.
   The Council of State named the president and vice president on
Thursday. It declared that elections cannot be held until U.S.
economic sanctions and ``aggression'' end.
   The council, a body of Cabinet ministers and heads of the
military and agencies that Noriega is presumed to control, said it
will evaluate the situation in six months to determine whether
elections are possible.
   Noriega is head of the Panamanian Defense Forces, the nation's
military, and the de facto leader of Panama.
   The council said Rodriguez will head a provisional government
that will rule with a legislative commission of 41 appointed
members. It said the national legislature will be abolished and the
government will draft a new constitution.
   Rodriguez, a 50-year-old career bureaucrat, was a high school
classmate of Noriega and served in the Cabinet of the late Gen. Omar
Torrijos in the mid-1970s.
   Asked why diplomats were not invited to the swearing-in, a South
American diplomat said: ``I guess they do not want to run the chance
of being turned down by some.'' He noted that several ambassadors
had been recalled by their governments or had ``gone on vacation,''
apparently to show displeasure with the break in constitutional
procedure.
   Panamanian authorities decided to form a provisional government
after canceling the May 7 presidential election. International
observers said the opposition candidate won by a 3-1 margin, but the
government said the results were distorted by U.S. interference and
economic aid to the opposition.
   Opposition leaders have refused a government offer to share power.
   The opposition said this week that it planned no organized
protests of the new government to avoid bloodshed but that it will
continue to fight to have its election victory recognized.
   The Council of State said in a statement that it will consider
new elections only if the United States ``ends its aggression and
releases all funds'' it has frozen.
   ``Panama has suffered in the past two years the most merciless,
brutal and cruel aggression by the government of the United
States,'' the council said. ``The president of the United States, in
the use of his war powers, has decreed against Panama economic
sanctions and measures that government has never imposed against its
most bitter enemies.''
   Panama says its gross national product declined 17 percent in
1988, the worst drop since 1945, and that more than 30,000 jobs were
lost in the economic crisis aggravated by the two-year confrontation
with the United States.
   The Council of State said Panamanians must ``fight all attempts
by a foreign government to manipulate the judicial and political
organization of the Panamanian people.'' The comment was a reference
to U.S. policy not to resume relations with Panama unless Noriega is
removed from office.
   Noriega, who has been indicted on federal drug charges in
Florida, claims Washington is trying to discredit him in a plot to
renege on a treaty to return control of the Panama Canal to the
country in the year 2000, when all U.S. military installations in
Panama must be shut down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
