<FIRST>u i PM-Libya 2ndLd-Writethru   09-01 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0542,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Celebrates 20 Years in Power With Attack on U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 12th graf, `Assad and...' with 1 graf to CORRECT that Morocco
King Hassad did not attend ceremony. Pickup 13th graf, `Ortega spoke...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi, celebrating his 20th
year in power, declared his support for Panama today and said former
President Reagan has landed ``in the dustbin of history.''
   Gadhafi also took credit for inventing perestroika, the Soviet
Union's program of economic and political restructuring, and said
the state of Israel is an illegal entity.
   Gadhafi spoke at a special session of the General People's
Congress, Libya's parliament, to open the anniversary celebration
that has attracted an array of leaders from the Middle East and
revolutionary governments.
   The festivities mark the 20th anniversary of the coup that
deposed pro-Western King Idris and established Gadhafi and his
radical socialist revolution.
   The congress chanted ``one Arab people'' as Gadhafi arrived,
dressed in white slacks, a gray sports jacket, maroon shirt and a
white cape trimmed in gold.
   Gadhafi told the visiting revolutionary leaders, ``I stand with
you in the trenches.''
   Of Reagan, his former nemesis, the Libyan leader said: ``Reagan
has joined Hitler and Mussolini in the dustbin of history.''
   Gadhafi also said that ``the world must not be carved on
religious grounds,'' adding that Israel should not be a Jewish state.
   ``The Zionist entity is a strange entity left over from World War
II that must be removed the same way all the effects of World War II
have been removed,'' Gadhafi said in remarks coinciding with today's
50th anniversary of the war.
   The colonel also said Libya supports Panama and that ``we must
support people's struggles because if the people win it is a victory
for us.''
   President Hafez Assad of Syria and PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat,
who has been at odds with Gadhafi, joined in the anniversary
activities.
   Assad and Arafat sat beside each other on a platform, chatting
amicably before the session opened. Other leaders seated on the
platform included Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, Sudan's
military ruler Omar Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir, Algerian President
Chadli Bendjedid and Tunisia's Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.
   Ortega spoke briefly to the assembly, recalling the conflicts
both Nicaragua and Libya had with the United States under Reagan.
   ``Reagan is finished and Gadhafi continues on,'' Ortega said,
according to an unoffical translation of his comments in Spanish.
``In difficult moments he (Gadhafi) was always close. We both had
difficult moments. I owe him so much.''
   When Ortega finished, Gadhafi embraced him and then the two
clasped hands above their heads in triumph.
   The session was the first in a list of events today that included
an air show and a massive military parade through the central Green
Square, which was adorned with lights, pennants, brightly colored
helium balloons, hundreds of Libya's green flags and portraits of
Gadhafi.
   A Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Libya also sent invitations to President Bush and British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher, whose countries accuse Gadhafi of
supporting terrorism.
   The highest-ranking Western leader to attend was Foreign Minister
Gianni de Michelis of Italy, whose participation reportedly
irritated some Western governments.
   De Michelis, in comments apparently aimed at his country's
Western allies, said Italy welcomed efforts to resolve differences
with Libya so the nations can talk ``in a climate entirely free of
suspicions of any kind of action deemed unacceptable to the
international community.''
   His attendance and that of high-ranking envoys from Egypt and
Chad underlined the success of Gadhafi's efforts in recent years to
move away from a radical, go-it-alone policy to one of cooperation
with his North African neighbors and Western Europe.
   Libya was at its most isolated in April 1986 when U.S. warplanes
bombed this Mediterranean port and Benghazi, killing an estimated 41
people, including Gadhafi's baby daughter.
   Gadhafi's adventurism over the years has created other enemies he
now wants to turn into friends, aides say.
   On Thursday, Libya and Chad announced that they had signed an
accord to end 16 years of warfare and hostilities that began when
Libyan tanks invaded northern Chad and soldiers annexed the
mineral-rich Aouzou desert strip.
   The accord calls for the countries to reach a political agreement
over the 40,000-square-mile border region within a year or turn the
dispute over to the International Court of Justice at The Hague.
</TEXT>
