<FIRST>u i PM-PuertoRico-Killings 1stLd-Writethru   09-01 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico-Killings, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0559,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Investigate Medellin Cartel Link to Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 8th, `Police Superintendent...' to ADD
that police have not raised possibility of Medellin link. Pickup 9th pvs,
`The FBI...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were trying to determine
today whether drug lords ordered the slayings of five people to
retaliate for a U.S.-supported crackdown on Colombian narcotics
traffickers.
   A sixth victim of the shooting was reported in stable condition
in the San Juan Medical Center, where he was under police guard.
   The killings occurred Thursday in the third-floor offices of
Medical Collection Services, which handles accounts for medical
insurance programs, in the San Juan suburb of Rio Piedras.
   An anonymous caller to The Associated Press on Thursday claimed
responsibility on behalf of the Colombian Medellin drug cartel.
   The caller, speaking Spanish with a South American accent, said
the killings were retribution for ``the decision taken by President
Bush and his allies'' to help the Colombian government's war against
drug lords.
   He linked the killings to the jailing of six people in Puerto
Rico accused of running millions of dollars worth of cocaine for the
Medellin cartel. The six are due to stand trial this month.
   The caller said the attack ``constitutes a clear, precise and
final message that we know the (Puerto Rican) government will wisely
understand.''
   Police Superintendent Ismael Betancourt said in a radio interview
today that investigators were taking the call into consideration but
had not been able to determine its authenticity. He said no motive
had been established.
   There is no known connection between the collection agency and
the Bush administration, and investigators have raised no connection
between the shootings and the crackdown in Colombia.
   The FBI joined the investigation but had no immediate comment.
   Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon, in a statement, said: ``This is
totally abnormal. We haven't had an attack like this here in many
years. We don't know what is behind it.''
   Jose Montanez, supervisor of the police Homicide Division, said
police had ruled out robbery because of the method of the slayings.
Also, the company did not keep a large amount of cash on hand.
   ``It was an execution, obviously,'' Montanez was quoted by the
San Juan Star. ``Everything points to that conclusion. ... It was
not a robbery.''
   He said three men and a woman were found dead in a computer room,
each with a bullet wound to the back of the head. Another man was
shot in the back of the head and died after police arrived on the
scene.
   The only survivor, Carlos Cerra, 50, had a bullet lodged in the
back of the neck but stumbled out of the office and got help.
   Police theorized that the gunmen used silencers because no one
else in the building reported hearing any shots. The office is
located above a pharmacy in busy shopping district.
   Among the dead were Edwin Perez Perez, 36, and his wife, Carmen,
also 36, who owned the business. Police identified the others as
Jorge Alberto Fuertes Betancourt, 41, and Gerardo Clavell Torres,
19, both employees; and a visiting computer-programming student,
Julio Efrain Erazo Navarrete, 27, of Ecuador.
</TEXT>
