<DOCNO> AP890901-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     09-01 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Worried Juror's Illness Could Cause Mistrial of 3-Year Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0562 to RESTORE overline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious ailment that sent a juror in the
McMartin preschool molestation trial to the hospital has the
presiding judge worried the longest criminal trial in U.S. history
could end in a mistrial.
   Five of the original six alternate jurors have been excused
because of illness and job problems during the trial, now in its
third year. If the ill juror drops out, the last remaining alternate
would replace him, and if one more juror leaves, a mistrial would
end the case without a verdict.
   ``We have to have 12 of you to try this case,'' Superior Court
Judge William Pounders told the panelists who sat in the jury box
with one chair empty Thursday. ``If we're down to the final 12,
we're in desperate straits.''
   Pounders recessed the case until Sept. 11 to await a diagnosis of
the juror's problem and determine whether he will be able to return
to court.
   The jurors have been hearing testimony on charges against Raymond
Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62, who are named
in 64 counts of molestation and a shared count of conspiracy in a
series of allegations linked to their now defunct McMartin
Pre-School in Manhattan Beach.
   The defense rested last week and the prosecution began calling
rebuttal witnesses.
   The judge did not describe the ill juror's symptoms but said
pathology reports have not yet diagnosed the cause.
   Pounders said he would try to take advantage of the latest delay
by working with attorneys on jury instructions. He said he wants to
submit the case to jurors by December.
</TEXT>
