<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceTraining     09-01 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Training,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Says He Won't Prosecute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general said he will not
prosecute anyone in the 1988 death of a cadet at a police training
academy who died of heat stroke after a day of rigorous exercise.
   The death of Timothy Shepard, 25, of Pittsfield was ``tragic and
avoidable,'' but ``there is no one who can be fairly and responsibly
charged with criminal culpability,'' General James Shannon Shannon
said Thursday.
   He told Shepard's widow, Holly Shepard, and other family members
of his decision before making it public.
   Springfield District Judge Irving J. Goldblatt, who conducted a
two-month inquest into the death, had recommended that charges be
brought against two administrators and an instructor.
   Shepard and other cadets collapsed of heat stroke last Sept. 19
at the police training academy at Agawam. Shepard was the sickest of
the 16 cadets who were hospitalized with exhaustion and dehydration
following a grueling regimen of pushups, confusion drills and
punishment laps. He died Nov. 2.
   ``It makes no sense that he's not going to pursue this. It's
ludicrous, absolutely ludicrous,'' said Mrs. Shepard. She said a
civil suit is now inevitable.
   ``I do not condone the treatment of Timothy Shepard and the other
cadets of Class 12. I despise it,'' Shannon said. ``But I must not
be driven by vengeance. I cannot shape the law to fit my feelings or
the feelings and the irreplaceable loss of others.''
   Evidence showed that the cadets, on the first day of training to
be municipal police officers, participated in physically and
mentally grueling exercises and had limited opportunities to drink
water on a hot, humid day.
   Goldblatt recommended that involuntary manslaughter charges be
sought against Earl Harrington, former director of the Agawam police
academy; Gary F. Egan, former executive director of the state
Criminal Justice Training Council, and State Police Trooper C. Blake
Gilmore, who served as commandant of the state-run academy.
   ``Don't take it from me. Take it from Judge Goldblatt,'' said
Michael Hashim Jr., the family's lawyer. ``He came to a finding
there was probable cause for a finding of involuntry manslaughter to
be brought. For Jim Shannon to toss it aside ... in my opinion, it
just leaves me speechless.''
   Timothy Burke, general counsel for the Massachusetts State Police
Association, said he was pleased by Shannon's decision.
   ``As the factual circumstances reveal, there was never any
intention on the part of any of the state police officers involved
in the training to in any way harm the cadets present on Day One,''
he said.
</TEXT>
