<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Hailstorm,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hailstorm Kills 26, Injures 74</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hailstorm killed 26 people and injured 74 in
southwestern Guizhou province, which also has suffered severe
drought this summer, the official Xinhua News Agency said Friday.
   Storms in recent days have damaged 9,791 homes and 41,990 acres
of crops, the report said. It did not say when the storms began or
how the victims were killed or injured.
   Since July, the province has been suffering from severe drought
that has parched 2.79 million acres of farmland. More than 3.5
million people and 1.33 million domestic animals lack drinking
water, the news agency said.
   Authorities have raised $13.4 million to help disaster victims.
   Drought has hit from southwestern China's Sichuan province to the
northern cities of Beijing and Tianjin. East China's Shandong
province has been hit with its worst drought in 40 years, parching
half of its farmland.
   Earlier this summer, severe flooding killed about 1,800 people.
   U.S. Ambassador James Lilley on Friday presented Chinese
officials with a $25,000 check to provide medicine and medical
supplies to flood victims. Aid also has come from from the European
Comunity, which donated $550,000.
