<FIRST>r a PM-DeathWish     09-01 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Wish,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Sides With Man Who Wants Life Support Turned Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia's attorney general supports a
quadriplegic's request to turn off the respirator that keeps him
alive.
   Larry James McAfee, 33, wants a Fulton Superior Court judge to
let him activate a timer with his mouth that will turn off a
ventilator he has used since his neck was broken in a 1985
motorcycle accident.
   McAfee ``has both a constitutional and statutory right to refuse
medical treatment,'' Attorney General Michael J. Bowers said in
court papers filed Thursday.
   ``The fact that the exercise of his rights may result in
petitioner's death is a consequence to be considered by him, not an
invitation for the state to abridge his right to free choice,''
Bowers wrote.
   ``While suicide has enjoyed fervent debate among religious,
ethical, legal and medical scholars, it is not a crime in Georgia,''
Bowers wrote.
   Judge Edward H. Johnson scheduled a hearing Wednesday on McAfee's
petition. Last week, Johnson made Bowers a party to the case so the
state's position would be considered in the decision.
   Johnson conducted a bedside hearing two weeks ago to hear
McAfee's testimony before he was transferred from Grady Memorial
Hospital to a nursing home in Alabaster, Ala.
