<HEAD>Man Ordered to Stand Trial On Charges of Killing His Four Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to note no trial date set, move up arraignment
date from last graf pvs. Pickup 3rd graf, `DeLisle was calm...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WISNIEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who police say intentionally ran
his family station wagon into the Detroit River, killing his four
young children, was ordered today to stand trial on murder charges.
   Lawrence DeLisle, 28, was bound over to Wayne County Circuit
Court on four counts of first-degree murder in the deaths of his
children, Bryan, 8, Melissa, 4, Kathryn, 2, and Emily, 8 months. He
also will stand trial on a count of attempting to murder his wife,
Suzanne.
   No trial was set; Circuit Court arraignment was scheduled for
Sept. 14.
   DeLisle was calm when Wyandotte District Judge Lawrence Emmert
ordered the trial. Emmert made his decision after hearing two days
of testimony, including questioning of Mrs. DeLisle.
   Mrs. DeLisle said she tried to rescue her children from the car
after it crashed into the river Aug. 3. She said she screamed for
help when she escaped through a car window and swam to the surface
of the water, and that her husband, who had emerged a few seconds
earlier, was quiet and appeared in shock.
   She testified Thursday that her husband said a leg cramp caused
him to jam down on the accelerator. She said she tried to grab the
steering wheel and turn off the ignition when the car sped down the
street and through wooden barriers into the river.
   Police have said DeLisle told them he deliberately ran the car
into the river because of financial and family problems. Mrs.
DeLisle says her husband was coerced into the admission.
   Bryan Ross, who was boating in the river at the time of the
accident, testified that when he saw Lawrence DeLisle float to the
top, he threw him a ski jacket as a life preserver.
   Ross said he saw Mrs. DeLisle surface a few seconds later
screaming, ``My babies, my babies.''
</TEXT>
