<DOCNO> AP890901-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     09-01 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Session Meets Amid Party Divisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's top communists, divided over
the pace of reform and the move to a multiparty system, met in a
closed-door Central Committee session Friday.
   No formal agenda was announced, but political observers expected
the 108-member Central Committee to debate the increasingly open
rifts between reformers and orthodox communists, which some analysts
predict could lead to a formal split in party ranks at a national
party congress scheduled for Oct. 6.
   The four-man leadership named in June to run the party until the
congress formulates new policies in October is divided over
multiparty elections scheduled to occurr before next June and
negotiations with the opposition on how to run the ballots.
   Party General Secretary Karoly Grosz, a centrist who lost power
in the June reshuffle, has said he may quit altogether.
   Party president Rezso Nyers, who says he is ``first among
equals'' in the four-man leadership, has differed publicly with
leading reformer Imre Pozsgay over whether or not political parties
can continue to be active at workplaces.
   Opposition groups negotiating constitutional reform and a new
election law with the communists have demanded that political
parties be banned from workplaces.
   The communists, who for four decades have maintained extensive
organizations at factories and farms, are stalling on the demand,
and Nyers criticized a compromise put forward by Pozsgay.
   Popular with the opposition, Pozsgay is under fire from some
communists and opposition activists who suspect he is behind an
official youth league move to create a revamped, more powerful
presidency _ a post he is said to want.
   The communists and opposition also are at odds over what to do
with properties owned by the Communist Party, which the opposition
says should be shared among all political parties. The communists
insist the buildings are solely their property.
   Another obstacle to elections emerged this week when the official
trade union organization said it was pulling out of the forum, which
brings together the communists, opposition groups and social
organizations.
   Magda Kovacs-Kosa, a member of the trade union delegation at the
talks, told the Hungarian news agency MTI Wednesday the trade unions
pulled out because economic issues are being largely ignored at the
talks.
   This could isolate millions of Hungarian workers, who are more
concerned with rising prices and falling living standards than with
political reform, she indicated.
</TEXT>
