<FIRST>r a PM-Women-OnlySociety 1stLd-Writhethru a0477 09-01 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women-Only Society, 1st Ld-Writhethru, a0477,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Male Professor's Bid to Join Female Education Society</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New throughout with action dismissed. No pickup. Deletes BRF
designation from slugline.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSWEGO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A male college professor's attempt to join an
exclusive women educators society was rejected on a technicality by
a federal judge today.
   U.S. District Judge Howard Munson said Harold Nash's motion for
summary judgment on the society's admission policies cited laws
applicable to employers and not to private groups.
   Munson dismissed the motion and halted, at least temporarily,
Nash's five-year quest to join the Delta Kappa Gamma Society. Nash's
lawyer, former National Organization for Women President Karen
DeCrow, said she would refile the motion.
   Nash, an education professor at the State University of New
York's Oswego campus, said the group has rejected his applications
because of his sex.
   ``Neither men nor women can have it both ways these days,'' Nash
said. ``It seems to me that (applying) was the reasonable thing to
do in the spirit of equal opportunity.''
   Nash, who has taught at Oswego since 1963, wants to join the
society to share in its education conferences and journals, he said.
   Delta Kappa Gamma is an honorary society for women educators with
164,000 members. It annually presents an educators' award for women
authors and gives scholarships and fellowships for women.
   A lawyer for Delta Kappa Gamma, Nancy Pontius of Syracuse,
declined to comment.
</TEXT>
