<FIRST>r a AM-Half-BakedBurglary     09-01 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Half-Baked Burglary,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Janitor Pelts Two Burglars With Stale Bread, Rolls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A janitor at a Veterans of Foreign Wars post
who came upon two burglars made sure the thieves didn't get away
with much money by giving them a lot of bread.
   ``I had two bags of stale bread for the ducks I feed every
morning and a box of Entenmann's sticky buns. I started hitting them
with those,'' said Dean Mitchell.
   The two burglars ``were busy defending themselves'' from the
onslaught of baked goods before they took off, he said.
   ``I'm 70 years old and it would have been a chore catching up
with them. They lit out,'' Mitchell said.
   Mitchell came upon the break-in when he opened Post 2093, a hall
the veterans use for social and business events, about 5 a.m.
Thursday and stepped over two knapsacks _ one filled with liquor and
cigarettes.
   ``I knew something was funny. Then here's those two young kids
coming around the corner by the popcorn machine,'' he said. ``I let
out a big noise and said a few things.''
   The pair didn't make off with much _ maybe $150 worth of change
and cigarettes, said post commander George Gray.
   The burglary was the fourth in less than a year at the post.
Burglars once caused $5,000 in damage to the building's ventilation
system when they tried to crawl through the duct work.
   The Orange County sheriff's office reported no arrests in the
case.
</TEXT>
