<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Drill     09-01 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Drill,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>13 Million Japanese Join Earthquake Drill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of people jumped out of windows, ran
through smoke-filled stores and pried each other from crushed
vehicles Friday in a city-wide drill 66 years after the great
earthquake that took at least 150,000 lives.
   Safety officials used public address systems to issue mock
earthquake warnings in designated parts of the city and helped
volunteers and school children, many wearing protective padded
hoods, move to open areas.
   In a shopping center in Kichijoji western Tokyo, police and
firefighters rappelled down the sides of tall buildings to practice
rescuing trapped people.
   Others used power saws and crow bars to rescue volunteers from
cars piled on top of each other. Front-end loaders moved the cars to
the side of the road, clearing the way for firetrucks and other
safety vehicles.
   Volunteers jumped from a fourth floor window onto a giant
air-filled cushion, following directions barked through a bullhorn.
   Firefighters filled a department store and shopping arcade with
smoke to simulate an evacuation during fires likely to follow a
major quake. Girls holding handkerchiefs over their mouths ran
through the smoke in a line.
   ``We've lost some business today, but it's for a good cause,''
said the owner of a clothing store.
   At two minutes before noon on Sept. 1, 1923, the Great Kanto
Earthquake rocked the crowded Kanto Plain around Tokyo and firest
from coal cooking stoves quickly spread through the city's small
wooden houses. Most of the victims died in the fires.
   The intensity was estimated later at 7.9 on the Richter scale,
great enough to cause catastropic damage in populated areas. Experts
say another such quake could strike at any time.
   A police chief, speaking on condition of anonymity, acknowledged
Friday that equipment like front-end loaders probably would be
inadequate and not available where they were needed most. ``We'd
just have to work our way from place to place,'' he said.
   Toshiko Maeda, who watched some of the drills, said she worried
about what would happen in a real earthquake.
   ``I doubt things would go this smoothly,'' she said. ``There
probably would be pieces of buildings falling all around us.''
</TEXT>
