<FIRST>r w AM-Father'sRights     09-01 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Father's Rights,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Children's Advocacy Group Joins Embattled Father's Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national children's advocacy group said
Friday it has joined an unwed California father's petition to the
Supreme Court for a re-hearing in his case seeking visitation with
his daughter.
   The court in June upheld a California law that regards a woman's
husband as the father of her children, thereby denying Michael
Hirschensohn access to his child, said David Levy, president of the
National Council for Children's Rights.
   But one of the justices, John Paul Stevens, was ``mixed up'' on
the facts of the case, said Levy. He thought Hirschensohn had had a
hearing in California on the visitation issue, when he had not.
Whether the hearing had taken place was never argued before the high
court, Levy said.
   ``About half a million children are born out of wedlock every
year and in many cases the fathers are being cut out of their right
to know and raise their children,'' said Levy.
   ``What this is all about is an unwed father who wants to be
involved and is spending tens of thousands of dollars on legal fees
that could be spent on the child,'' he said.
   Levy said his organization and Hirschensohn are asking that the
Supreme Court order a hearing on the visitation question.
   The child's mother had a relationship with Hirschensohn when she
was separated from her husband and lived with Hirschensohn on and
off for several years, said Levy.
   Eventually, the woman returned to her husband and took the child,
who is now 7, with her. Hirschensohn said the move ended a
father-daughter relationship that had been established. He said
blood tests have verified that the girl is his daughter.
   ``A child is being deprived of the right to have the financial
and emotional support of her natural father,'' said Levy.
   ``There is no reason why the child and father in this particular
case should lose out because one of the justices thought a hearing
had already occurred,'' said Levy.
   The Supreme Court, which is in recess, resumes business in
October.
</TEXT>
