<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0634-a0565 09-01 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0634-a0565,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Greets `New Friend' Kaifu</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; deletes last 12 grafs pvs and trims elsewhere
to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush greeted Japanese Prime Minister
Toshiki Kaifu as a ``new friend'' today but immediately cautioned
that the health of the partnership of their countries will require
Japan to increase its imports.
   ``I share the prime minister's belief that while Japan is noted
as an exporting superpower, the time has also come for Japan to be
an importing superpower,'' Bush said.
   The president, interrupting his Maine vacation for the
get-aquainted session at the White House with the new Japanese
leader, said economic imbalances between the two allies were
discussed ``at length.''
   Kaifu, speaking after Bush in a brief departure ceremony after
their meeting, said Japan recognized the trade imbalance and said
his country would continue to ``make efforts for expanding imports.''
   At the same time, Kaifu noted that the United States must do more
to reduce its budget deficit, increase the rate of savings by
Americans and increase the competitiveness of U.S. industry.
   The United States is running a $50 billion annual trade deficit
with Japan, and Bush said, ``We know that the health of our
relationship partly depends on bringing our economic relatonship
into better balance.''
   The two leaders said their discussions also included talks about
China, Cambodia and international terrorism.
   ``While we met as new friends, our talks were conducted as old
friends,'' Bush said. He cited ``broad agreement on the major items
of our bilateral and international agenda.''
   Kaifu picked up on the theme, saying that ``I just completed my
first meeting with the president. Nevertheless, I was able to
conduct talks with the president as if I were meeting an old
friend.''
   Kaifu also said he proposed to Bush an international effort, to
be partly funded by Japan, to bring food and other relief to people
in developing nations. He said the effort would be named after the
late Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, killed last month while flying to
a refugee camp in Ethiopia.
   From the White House, Kaifu went to Capitol Hill to meet with
Senate leaders.
   In a separate meeting today, Secretary of State James A. Baker
III cautioned Japanese Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama that close
economic cooperation between the two nations was crucial because of
``rising protectionism'' in the United States, according to a
Japanese official.
   Baker pressed for movement on lowering Japanese trade barriers
against U.S. super computers, satellites and forest products, said a
Japanese official who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity.
   The official quoted Nakayama as reiterating the Japanese position
that these trade issues would be discussed, but not under the cloud
of threatened U.S. sanctions.
   The Baker-Nakayama breakfast meeting ranged from talks about
Cambodia and China to the current turmoil in Latin America, the
official said.
   As the two leaders began their two-hour round of talks, Kaifu
told Bush he had been to the White House 18 years ago when Gerald
Ford was president, and earlier as a newly elected member of
Parliament when John Kennedy was president.
   Kaifu, wearing his trademark polka dot tie, posed with Bush for
photos in the Oval Office before a session in the Cabinet room with
their advisers.
   The Kaifu visit entails some touchy matters for Bush, as the
United States wants to push its concerns over Japan's $50 billion
trade surplus, but guard against pushing Kaifu so hard that it
weakens his fragile new government.
   Although the two countries have very good economic relations,
``there are economic frictions over various issues,'' Kaifu said in
an interview on ``CBS This Morning,'' and ``Japan wishes to make as
much effort as possible in order to resolve those economic
frictions.''
   He said, ``I would like to, through my talks with the president,
make sure that this relationship of mutual trust will remain
unshakeable and firm.''
   The meeting came a day after Bush welcomed Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney and his family to the Bush family's seaside
home in kennebunkport, Maine.
   The leaders said they discussed many issues, including their
shared support for embattled Colombian President Virgilio Barco in
his attempted crackdown on drug traffickers.
   Kaifu is making his first trip to the United States after
recently taking office in the wake of sex and political scandal that
felled his predecessor and other prominent Japanese leaders.
   ``It is customary for new Japanese prime ministers to visit
Washington early on to establish a personal relationship with the
president,'' Scowcroft told reporters.
   ``This is one of our more important international relationships
and it is important that the two establish this kind of close
contact, and that's really the purpose of the visit.''
   The 58-year-old Kaifu is one of Japan's youngest prime ministers,
but he has served in parliament for 29 years and was twice minister
of education.
</TEXT>
