<HEAD>East German Border Guards Fire Shots But Fail to Prevent Escape</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Border guards fired shots in an unsuccessful
attempt to stop an East German man from fleeing his communist
homeland, police said Friday.
   The West German government and the Allied powers in West Berlin
protested the use of force. West Berlin police said the 24-year-old
man, who was not identified, managed to scale border fortifications
and flee unharmed to the West on Thursday.
   Police said border guards fired two shots despite East German
claims that a shoot-to-kill order had been lifted. It was not known
if the shots were fired directly at the man.
   The Allied powers in West Berlin _ the United States, France and
Britain _ lodged protests condemning the shooting incident and
called on the East German government to ``end the use of deadly
force which clearly violates all foundations of human rights.''
   The Berlin Wall and the frontier between East Germany and West
Germany are heavily fortified and guarded by armed troops,
electronic alarms and attack dogs.
