<FIRST>r w AM-US-Soviet-Jews     09-01 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet-Jews,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Jewish Emigration Rising, Group Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Jews left the Soviet Union in August than
in any month for the past 21 years, the chairman of the National
Conference on Soviet Jewry announced Friday, calling it ``a
development of major significance.''
   The conference, a nationwide group that has monitored Jewish
emigration from the Soviet Union since 1968, reported that 6,756
Jews left last month, surpassing the previous high of 4,746 in
October 1979. Of those who left in August, 793, or 11.7 percent,
went to Israel.
   ``This is a development of major significance, and we hope that
the upward trend in emigration, which we have witnessed since the
beginning of 1989, will continue,'' said Shoshana S. Cardin,
chairman of the conference.
   Soviet restrictions on Jewish emigration have been a point of
contention between U.S. and Soviet officials for years, although the
issue has been eclipsed recently by other human rights topics, such
as the drive for greater autonomy by the Baltic republics and
Moldavia, and demands by other ethnic groups.
   Bush administration officials and Jewish activists in this
country have said that higher levels of emigration and proposed
relaxations in Soviet visa law could prompt the U.S. government to
waive provisions of 1974 legislation linking emigration with trade
benefits.
   On June 13, the National Conference on Soviet Jewry passed a
resolution saying that if the favorable trends continued, it would
support waiver of portions of the Jackson-Vanik amendment.
   The bill, named after the late Sen. Henry Jackson, D-Wash., and
former Rep. Charles Vanik, D-Ohio, required higher trade tariffs on
Soviet imports as long as the president felt the Kremlin was
limiting emigration.
   The newly constituted Soviet parliament, the Supreme Soviet, is
expected to consider a new emigration law when it convenes later
this month, although it was not clear how liberal the new
legislation might be or when it might be passed.
   The National Conference said that some problems persist in Jewish
emigration from the Soviet Union. Ms. Chardin said in June that some
400,000 invitations had been mailed to Soviet Jews to emigrate,
although it was not clear how many actually wished to leave.
   Since January, 33,444 Jews have been allowed to leave the Soviet
Union, and the total for 1989 could surpass the previous high of
51,320 set in the 1979, according to officials of the National
Conference on Soviet Jewry. In July of this year, 4,537 Jews
emigrated.
   Last year, 18,965 Jews emigrated from the Soviet, up sharply from
the 1987 figure of 8,155 and the 1986 figure of 914, the conference
reported.
   A State Department source said the U.S. government had no
immediate reaction to the figures, but noted that the Bush
administration has been keeping close tabs on Soviet emigration
policy with an eye to possibly easing enforcement of the
Jackson-Vanik amendment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
