<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-China     09-01 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-China,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing Forbids Papal Plane from Overflying China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has denied permission to Pope John Paul II to
fly in Chinese airspace on a pilgrimage to the Far East in October,
an Alitalia airline spokesman said Friday.
   The Beijing government had not given an official explanation for
the decision, said the airline spokesman, Gianpiero Piva. The
Italian carrier is to fly the pope Oct. 6 to Seoul, the first stop
on the 10-day trip.
   China severed diplomatic relations with the Vatican in 1957 and
allows worship only under the guise of the Chinese Patriotic
Catholic Church, which consecrates its own bishops. The church
claims more than 3 million members and an unknown number of other
Catholics remain secretly loyal to the pope.
   Piva said an alternate air route had not yet been chosen and it
was not clear if the delay would lengthen the flight considerably.
   The pontiff's 44th foreign trip also includes visits to
Indonesia, East Timor and Mauritius.
</TEXT>
