<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1558EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-War-Germany     09-01 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War-Germany,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Expresses Sorrow Over War, Tries to Ease German Guilt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-War, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl expressed grief
Friday over the horrors of Nazi Germany but called for a fair
judgment of Germans who were ``blinded and deceived'' by Adolf
Hitler.
   On the anniversary of the Nazi attack on Poland that plunged
Europe into World War II, Kohl tried in a solemn parliamentary
speech to ease German guilt while acknowledging the importance of
``keeping the horror in our minds, keeping it present.''
   In Communist East Berlin, ailing leader Erich Honecker missed the
memorial ceremony in the 500-member People's Chamber, where Foreign
Minister Oskar Fischer delivered the main address.
   Fischer called Friday a day of ``recollection and sorrow'' and
said the government was committed ``to do everything in our power to
ensure that war and fascism never again threaten our lives and the
lives of our children.''
   Kohl declared West Germany's commitment to reconciliation with
Poland and mending of the tear in Europe inflicted by the war.
   ``The wounds caused by World War II have not healed yet. They are
burnt into the minds of nations,'' Kohl stated.
   But he alluded to ``encouraging developments'' in East-West
relations and vowed the full support of West Germany for
reform-oriented Soviet bloc nations as payment for past wrongs.
   ``We Germans are under a special obligation to do so,'' Kohl
said. ``This stems not least from the Hitler-Stalin pact of 1939.''
   Secret protocols to that pact deeded the Baltic states to the
Soviet Union and allowed the Nazis to invade Poland on Sept. 1, 1939.
   ``We feel sorrow at the untold suffering inflicted on people and
nations by Germans and in the name of Germany, and we mourn the many
innocent victims from the midst of our own nation,'' Kohl said.
   ``People still vividly recall the cattle wagons of the `death
trains,' packed with people destined for the extermination camps .
..'' recalled Kohl, who said the scenes of suffering were sharp
among his childhood memories.
   ``It is true that too many people in Germany and some abroad were
blinded and deceived by that tyrant,'' Kohl said, referring to
Hitler. But he said ``we should beware of making hasty judgements
from today's vantage point.''
   ``Who among us can say with a good conscience that, confronted
with such evil, they would have summoned the strength to be martyrs?
And who among us can judge what it meant at that time to risk not
only one's own life but the lives of one's family as well?'' he
asked.
   ``People today are no better and no worse than the people of that
era, but they are not under compulsion to make decisions in the
conditions prevailing under totalitarianism.''
   Kohl's 50-minute speech was interrupted by applause only once,
when he expressed West Germany's wish for the success of Poland's
new leadership.
   Kohl plans to visit Poland this fall, but the trip hinges on
resolution of remaining political differences between the two
states, as well as a package of economic aid.
   The still-fragile relations with Poland also figured prominently
in the anniversary addresses of President Richard von Weizsaecker
and former Chancellor Willy Brandt.
   ``Countless are the victims and indescribable is the suffering
which the people of your country had to bear during and after the
war,'' Weizsaecker wrote in a letter to Polish President Wojciech
Jaruzelski on the occasion.
   ``My country has given a binding promise that it will neither now
nor in the future make any territorial claims on Poland,''
Weizsaecker vowed.
   The Bundestag members voted unanimously to endorse Weizsaecker's
call for reconciliation with Poland.
   Nearly one-third of present-day Poland was once part of Germany,
and Poles consider any claims to that property to indicate
revanchism among West Germans.
   Suggestions among West German conservatives that reunification of
Germany could some day take place within the pre-war borders are
among the wedges that continue to separate West Germany and Poland.
</TEXT>
