<DOCNO> AP890901-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ConstructionSpending     09-01 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Spending,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slight Rise Gives Hope That Slump May End</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending recorded a slight
increase in July as strength in non-residential building offset
weakness in housing and government projects, the Commerce Department
reported Friday.
   The department said that spending rose by a tiny 0.02 percent, a
gain of $100 million, putting the seasonally adjusted annual rate at
$415.7 billion in July.
   The increase followed a 0.9 percent decline in June and an
advance of 0.8 percent in May.
   While the July rebound was modest, analysts said it offered at
least the hope that the lengthy construction slump may be coming to
an end.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co., noted that new
home sales and construction starts for new homes, were beginning to
advance after a steep drop in the first part of 1989. He said that
rebound would soon be reflected in the construction spending report
and would help to lift the overall figure.
   ``Construction is on its way up because the lower mortgage rates
have boosted sales,'' he said.
   Sales of both new and existing homes fell sharply earlier in the
year as mortgage rates climbed to a high of 11.22 percent in late
March. Rates then began falling and dropped as low as 9.81 percent
in late July.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said that rates have been
rising slightly in recent weeks and as of Friday the national
average for fixed-rate mortgages stood at 10.22 percent.
   Analysts said they did not believe the small increase in rates
would be enough to dampen demand as long as mortgages don't rise
much further.
   In July, all of the strength came in non-residential
construction, which was up 0.9 percent to an annual rate of $99.7
billion. It was the third consecutive monthly gain in this sector,
following even stronger increases of 1.4 percent in June and 1.1
percent in May.
   The July increase was led by a 3.4 percent jump in spending for
hotels and motels and a 3.1 percent gain in factory building
projects.
   Residential construction edged down 0.2 percent to an annual rate
of $198.2 billion with single-family construction dipping 0.1
percent while multi-family building was off a sharper 1.7 percent.
   Government construction spending fell by 1.2 percent in July to
an annual rate of $80.9 billion as the biggest single government
category, highway construction, dropped 4 percent.
   The total construction figure was up a slight 1.2 percent from
the level of building a year ago.
</TEXT>
