<HEAD>Beirut Ravaged By Shellfire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE casualties; picks up 5th graf,
``Barrages from ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shellfire blanketed Beirut on Friday,
smashing apartments, setting woodlands ablaze and gutting the
hilltop Casino de Liban, a relic of the days when this devastated
city was the playground of the Middle East.
   At least 11 people were killed and 66 wounded in one of the
fiercest exchanges of the 6-month-old artillery war between the
Christian army units of Gen. Michel Aoun and a Moslem alliance led
by the 40,000 Syrian troops in Lebanon.
   Police said 80 shells and rockets a minute fell on the city and
surrounding wooded hills hills at the height of the battle. Some
neighborhoods on both sides of the sectarian dividing line became
infernos of flaming buildings.
   At least 823 people have been killed and 2,420 wounded, by police
count, since the shelling began March 8. Nearly all the casualties
have been civilians.
   Barrages from long-range Syrian artillery covered virtually all
the besieged 310-square-mile enclave north and east of Beirut, in
which 1 million Christians have been trapped for months.
   Aoun's artillery hammered Syrian-controlled west Beirut, the
Druse Moslem stronghold in the Chouf Mountains southeast of the
capital and the main Syrian supply route through the Bekaa Valley of
east Lebanon.
   Fighting intensified Thursday after reports that the peace
mission of French envoy Francois Scheer had collapsed. France, which
governed Lebanon by mandate until 1943, seeks an end to arms
supplies for all factions, withdrawal of foreign forces and reform
of sectarian power-sharing.
   Scheer left Beirut on Wednesday for Saudi Arabia to meet with
King Fahd, head of a three-member Arab League committee trying to
find a solution to the 14-year-old civil war.
   Police said 130mm Syrian artillery in the central mountains hit
the state-owned Casino du Liban north of Beirut with at least 80
shells, setting it on fire.
   The landmark casino overlooking the Mediterranean was the largest
in the Middle East, a symbol of the carefree days before the war,
which has taken 150,000 lives.
   Associated Press newsman Bahjat Jaber reported by telephone from
the Christian port of Jounieh, north of Beirut, that ``hundreds of
shells and rockets'' were landing.
   ``They're shelling the coast, the mountains, the towns and the
road network,'' Jaber said. ``The whole area's burning.''
   Voice of Lebanon, a Christian radio station, said the ``Syrian
death mill toils without letup, spitting out destruction in every
direction.''
   Beirut Radio, controlled by Aoun, said the escalated shelling was
Syria's ``reply to efforts aimed at finding a settlement.''
   Forest fires raged out of control in the hills around Beirut. In
the city, ambulances raced through smoky streets filled with rubble
from wrecked and blazing apartment buildings.
   Hospitals are short of space and medicine. Shellfire has damaged
most of them. Barbir Hospital was hit 130 rounds in one four-day
period.
   Casualties appeared amazingly low given the level of shelling,
but most of Beirut's 1.5 million people have gone abroad or fled to
safer parts of the country. The approximately 150,000 still in the
city spent Thursday night and Friday in underground shelters.
   Police said Christian gunners knocked out a radar-controlled
130mm howitzer nicknamed ``Abu Abdo'' on the seafront road in Moslem
west Beirut. Several Syrian guns along that stretch have been
destroyed in recent weeks.
   Abu Abdo _ which translates roughly to ``Father of the Tough
Guy'' _ and other 130mm guns have fired on ships trying to reach
Christian ports north of Beirut with arms and other supplies.
   Police said a freighter dashed into Jounieh with a cargo of fruit
and vegetables soon after the gun was silenced. They said it was
driven back by Syrian fire on its first try earlier Friday.
   On Tuesday, Syrian gunners hit a Maltese-flag tanker bound for a
Christian port and set it afire, killing nine of the 11 crewmen.
   Aoun's command said its men repulsed two overnight probes by
Syrian-backed militias along the southern and eastern flanks of the
Christian enclave.
   A spokesman, who would not let his name be used, said Christian
gunners destroyed a Syrian ammunition dump in pine woods near
Bolonia, 16 miles northeast of Beirut. He said at least two howitzer
shells hit a Syrian army base in an unfinished seven-story building
in west Beirut.
   The Syrian command does not comment on its losses.
   Syrian soldiers are in Lebanon under an Arab League peacekeeping
mandate issued in 1976, a year after the sectarian civil war began.
Aoun calls them an occupation force and has declared a ``war of
liberation'' to drive them out.
</TEXT>
