<FIRST>r i AM-Honecker     09-01 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker Released From Hospital; Recovering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker has been released
from the hospital and is recovering well, the state-run ADN news
agency said Friday.
   Honecker, 77, was taking a vacation to rest and recover from
recent gall-bladder surgery, the news agency said in a one-sentence
dispatch.
   Honecker's operation has prompted a flurry of speculation about
his health. East German media reported Thursday that Honecker's
recovery was proceeding slowly, but denied West German reports that
the operation had to be abandoned because of the ``condition of the
tissue.''
   East German officials called reports that Honecker was seriously
ill with cancer ``totally unfounded.''
   Western diplomatic sources have said Honecker would not travel to
Leipzig to open the international trade fair there Sunday and he was
not present at ceremonies in East Berlin Friday called to mark the
50th anniversary of the beginning of World War II.
   Honecker underwent a gall-bladder operation two weeks ago and has
not been seen in public since.
   The orthodox communist leader has ruled the country of 16.6
million people since 1971.
