<FIRST>r a AM-Drownings     09-01 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drownings,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Faces Trial on Charges of Murdering His Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WISNIEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of drowning his children by
ramming the family station wagon through a barrier and into the
murky Detroit River was ordered Friday to stand trial on four counts
of first-degree murder.
   Lawrence DeLisle, 28, also will be tried on a charge of attempted
murder for allegedly trying to kill his wife, Suzanne DeLisle, 32,
who was in the car and frantically tried to save their four children
Aug. 3.
   Police say DeLisle confessed to crashing deliberately to be
relieved of his ``burdens.'' But he later renewed his original claim
that it was accidental, and that a leg cramp made him jam down the
gas pedal, and his wife said the confession was coerced.
   DeLisle's eyes watered when District Court Judge Lawrence Emmert
bound him over for trial after a preliminary examination in this
Detroit suburb.
   Emmert, who reviewed videotapes, audio tapes and a manuscript of
DeLisle's lie-detector test and police interrogation, said the
defendant's confession was not coerced and may be used as evidence.
   DeLisle's attorney, Frank Eaman, said the tapes shouldn't be used
because police pressured DeLisle. He said he plans to appeal.
   Wayne County Assistant Prosecutor Kevin Simowski maintained
DeLisle was questioned properly.
   ``Police never threatened him. Police, if anything, were
sympathetic,'' he said. ``He didn't break down during any of the
interviews.''
   Emmert said critical testimony came from two witnesses who saw
DeLisle's car accelerate straight toward the river.
   ``Neither of them indicated that the car deviated at all,'' he
said.
   Mrs. DeLisle, who says she believes her husband is innocent,
testified Thursday that as her husband's leg cramped, she grabbed
the steering wheel and pulled to the right while he pulled to the
left and tried to grab his foot off the gas pedal. Police tests of
the car found no mechanical defects.
   She said she tried to save her children after the car hit the
bottom of the river. The couple were rescued by boaters who then
tried to dive for the children.
   Bryan, 8; Melissa, 4; Kathryn, 2; and Emily, 8 months, died at a
hospital within hours of the crash.
</TEXT>
