<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CropPayments     09-01 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crop Payments,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Can Apply for 1989 Crop Losses, USDA Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers whose 1989 crops have been wiped out or
reduced sharply by drought and floods can begin applying for federal
payments on Sept. 15, Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said
Friday.
   Applications can be filed at county offices of the department's
Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service through April
27, 1990, he said.
   Congress authorized nearly $900 million in federal payments under
the Disaster Assistance Act of 1989 for farmers who suffered crop
losses of more than 35 percent to 50 percent of normal production,
depending on whether they participated in this year's commodity
programs.
   ``Our ASCS field staff will process disaster payment requests as
quickly as possible to get financial aid to those farmers who have
suffered crop losses due to drought, excessive moisture and other
perils,'' Yeutter said in a statement.
   One of the USDA provisions will deduct the value of a replacement
crop to determine a farmer's disaster payment for losses on his
first crop.
   For example, if a farmer's winter wheat crop was wiped out and he
planted grain sorghum to replace it, the grain sorghum's value would
be considered in computing the disaster aid that was due.
   A formula will be used to account for the production costs of the
planting and harvesting the replacement crop on so-called failed
acres. The idea is to come up with a net value figure for the
replacement crop.
   An agency official, Tom VonGarlem, explained the formula
operation in an example:
   Suppose a farmer planted grain sorghum, or milo, on failed winter
wheat land, and harvests 30 bushels per acre this fall. The formula
calls for 75 percent of the output to be the farmer's net production
of sorghum _ 22.5 bushels per acre.
   At around $2 per bushel, the sorghum would have a value of $45
per acre. VonGarlem said this is what would be deducted from the
disaster payment that the farmer otherwise would get for losing his
winter wheat.
</TEXT>
