<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     09-01 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clergy Accuse Roh of Suppressing Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of clergymen accused President
Roh Tae-woo's government Friday of suppressing political opposition
and stalling on democratic reforms. They backed radical students'
demands for unifying South and North Korea.
   ``The government is causing people's life to collapse with the
suppression of human rights,'' the Korean National Council of
Churches said in its first major stand against Roh.
   Riot police battled about 1,500 students who hurled rocks and
firebombs as they demanded Roh's ouster and the disbanding of the
government intellence agency.
   The agency quoted a jailed student leader as saying his group had
received $30,000 from a pro-North Korean student alliance in Japan
to support its protests.
   The church statement came from the council representing more than
1,800 Christian ministers who claimed more than 800 political
prisoners have been arrested in recent months.
   They also accused Roh of being more undemocratic than his
dictatorial predecessors.
   ``The church will stand in the vanguard in the fight for
democratization of South Korea and unification of the two Koreas,''
said the statement issued after an overnight prayer meeting at a
downtown Anglican church.
   ``Movements for independence, democratization and unification
have been denounced as leftist and pro-communist,'' said the
statement.
   It said violence, torture and surveillance are ``threatening the
people's rights to survival and causing the people to tremble in a
sense of crisis.''
   The council, the largest Christian group in South Korea where
one-fourth of the 42 million people are Christian, was an active
political force during past authoritarian regimes.
   Roh has carried out wide democratic reforms since he took office
in February 1988 but critics argue he has not done enough.
   Opponents are especially critical of his failure to clear the
legacy of his disgraced predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan, who is under
public fire for alleged corruption and power abuse involving his
family and former aides.
   Later Friday, some 1,000 radical students attacked police in
front of Seoul's Joongang University Campus to press demands that
the Agency for National Security Planning be disbanded.
   Students claimed the agency, the main government intelligence
body, is blocking democratic development and efforts by South
Korea's ``democratic forces'' to promote unification with communist
North Korea.
   At Korea University, also in Seoul, 500 students yelled
``Overthrow Roh Tae-woo!'' as they attacked riot police. They
demanded the release of a radical student under arrest for an
illegal trip to North Korea. Police retaliated with tear gas.
   The government intelligence agency announced a major radical
student group, the National Council of Student Representatives, had
received $30,000 from a pro-North Korean student alliance in Japan.
   The agency quoted Oh Yong-shik, a former head of the Seoul-based
group student group who is now in jail on anti-state charges, as
confessing he was given the money in August 1988 for anti-government
campus and street demonstrations.
</TEXT>
