<FIRST>r a AM-Poland-Mondale     09-01 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Mondale,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mondale, Domenici, Baker Plan Trip To Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale
and four current and former legislators will travel to Warsaw this
month to advise Poland's new leaders on how to run a parliamentary
government, Mondale said.
   Mondale, Sen. Peter Domenici, R-N.M.; and former Sens. Howard
Baker, R-Tenn.; and Thomas Eagleton, D-Mo.; are traveling as private
citizens, not as representatives of the government, Mondale said
Thursday. The delegation is also to include former Rep. Jim Jones,
D-Okla.
   The U.S. group will advise Polish leaders on such parliamentary
matters as rules, powers and conducting debates, said Mondale, who
was a senator from Minnesota before becoming vice president in the
Carter administration.
   The trip follows the appointment last month of Solidarity editor
Tadeusz Mazowiecki as prime minister in a power-sharing arrangement
with the Communist Party, which has dominated Poland for more than
four decades.
   Mondale said that if Poland became independent of the Soviet
bloc, it would be a boost to U.S. security.
   ``If we can create and help create an independent Poland, that
would do more for the national security of this country than another
hundred billion dollars of guns, because if Poland is free, the
Russians could never fight a war in Europe,'' he said.
   The group, which also will include former U.S. Rep. Jim Jones,
D-Okla., will be attending a Sept. 21-23 conference on the role of
parliaments in developing economic policy, said Sue Grabowski of the
National Democratic Institute for International Affairs, which is
sponsoring the meeting.
   The event is not being held at the Polish government's
invitation, but parliamentary leaders have indicated they approve,
Grabowski said.
   Mondale is the institute's chairman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
