<DOCNO> AP890901-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2315EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Princess     09-01 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Princess,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Royals, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Royal Couple Cope With Public Curiosity About Separation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As news of Princess Anne's broken marriage swept
the British press, the separating couple and people close to them
fended off questioning journalists Friday.
   Anne, only daughter of Queen Elizabeth II, stayed through the end
of the International Olympic Committee's annual meeting in Puerto
Rico and left by private plane for a visit to Belize.
   Her husband, Capt. Mark Phillips, and their two children stayed
out of sight at their country estate in western England.
   Royal Navy Cmdr. Timothy Laurence, whose letters to Anne made
headlines this spring, told reporters he would not leave his house
until they went away.
   By the time Buckingham Palace confirmed Thursday that Anne, 39,
and her husband of nearly 16 years would separate, speculation about
Laurence's relationship with the princess was rife.
   Laurence, 35, told a reporter from an evening paper he was tipped
off Wednesday that a statement about Anne's marriage would be made
by Buckingham Palace and had decided to stay at home.
   ``Quite honestly, I'm prepared to stay here all day or as long as
it takes,'' he said.
   His neighbors in Winchester, 66 miles southwest of London, were
not so patient.
   The Daily Mirror said an elderly woman came out to harangue
reporters surrounding Laurence's house. It said she called them
``rotters,'' then sang three choruses of ``God Save The Queen,''
Britain's national anthem.
   Laurence was linked to Anne on April 8 when Buckingham Palace, in
an attempt to stop media speculation, announced that he was the
author of letters to the princess that were stolen from her home.
   On Friday, The Daily Mirror reported that a Canadian woman often
linked in news reports with Phillips also was besieged by reporters.
   The newspaper said Katherine Birks called police after
journalists surrounded her home in Caledon, Ontario. It said police
sealed off the street and escorted her jeep out of the driveway at
dawn.
   Lack of access to those involved has not stopped Britain's
tabloids from reporting on the royal separation.
   Most speculated on financial arrangements, although nothing is
known about what personal income Anne might have and little is known
about the income Phillips, 40, derives from his farming and
equestrian ventures.
   That did not keep The Sun from headlining, ``1 Million Pounds For
Mark,'' which it called ``a payoff from the queen,'' suggesting that
would keep him from telling his story of the marriage.
   Another paper, Today, decided it would be a ``3 Million Pound
Payoff'' for Phillips, basing its estimate on a lawyer's opinion
that he was entitled to 250,000 pounds ($390,000) for every 1
million pounds of Anne's money. It did not say how it determined how
much she had.
   The Star came down in the middle: ``2 Million Pound Kiss-Off to
End Royal Marriage.''
   At the Daily Mail, Anne was blamed for the separation with
headlines saying ``Anne Wanted Her Freedom,'' and ``Mark Hoped They
Would Stay Together But the Princess Decided to End the Sham
Marriage.'' It quoted Phillips' father as saying the decision had
not been mutual and his son would have been happy to continue the
marriage.
   ``When they married, everybody expected that Mark was going to be
hanging on her coattails,'' it quoted Maj. Peter Phillips as saying.
``Right from the word go he said he was going to do his thing and
she hers. He would not want to be a hanger-on. That is not his way
of life, I'm pleased to say.''
</TEXT>
