<FIRST>u i AM-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0669 09-01 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Celebrates 20 Years in Power With Attack on Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs, UPDATING with details of late celebrations,
Gadhafi quotes. Picks up 8th graf, Libya will ... with minor editing to
trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi celebrated 20 years in
power by pledging support Friday for ``freedom fighters'' in Panama
and elsewhere and declaring that Ronald Reagan had been consigned to
``the dustbin of history.''
   He proclaimed Libya's solidarity with ``the people of Panama in
confronting American imperialism.''
   Gadhafi was an obscure, 27-year-old army signals corps officer
when he led a coup Sept. 1, 1969, while King Idris was abroad.
   On the anniversary of the coup he addressed a special session of
Libya's parliament that also was attended by at least 19 heads of
state.
   Friday's festivities included an air show and a nighttime
military parade through Tripoli's central Green Square, which was
adorned with lights, balloons, Libya's green flags and portraits of
Gadhafi.
   Gadhafi, in olive fatigues, watched from a platform as soldiers
from Libya and other African and Middle East countries marched by.
   Other marching groups included foreign civilians. One group,
identified by Libyan officials as members of European Greens
environmental organizations, wore T-shirts and baseball caps adorned
with pictures of Gadhafi.
   Gadhafi did not speak during the parade, which lasted two hours
and 15 minutes.
   When Gadhafi went to address the General People's Congress
earlier, he was greeted by delegates and guests shouting ``One Arab
people!''
   ``I stand with you in the trenches,'' said the Libyan leader,
clad in white slacks, a gray sports jacket, maroon shirt and a white
cape trimmed in gold.
   Gadhafi took aim at former President Reagan.
   ``The empires of colonialization are now in the dustbins of
history. The conquerors who believed that they made themselves
divine on this planet ... Alexander the Macedonian, Hitler,
Mussolini and Reagan, are in the dustbin of history,'' he said,
according to an official translation.
   Libya will offer ``supplies and support'' to revolutionary
movements around the world, he said, and declared:
   ``We delightedly announce here to all freedom fighters in
Nicaragua, Panama, New Caledonia, Reunion, Mayotte, South Africa,
Namibia, Palestine, Caledonia, French Guyana and in Central America;
we happily announce to them that your ally is becoming stronger and
will not abandon you. We will be victorious.''
   ``The Libyan revolution ... has entered the Pacific Ocean,'' he
said, ``inciting peoples to seek freedom, supporting the small
peoples whose islands France has turned into a scene for nuclear
tests.''
   Singling out Panama, Gadhafi said the United States demanded that
he withdraw support for Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega as a condition
for resumption of U.S.-Libyan dialogue.
   ``Libya is present in Panama, the Sept. 1 revolution is present
in Panama,'' he said. ``We say this: We will not withdraw our
position, which fully and absolutely supports the cause of the
people of Panama in confronting American imperialism.''
   He said the United States also wants Libya to recognize Israel,
but ``there is no question of recognizing Israel. The Zionist entity
is a strange entity left over from World War II that must be
removed. ... Palestine is for the Palestinians.''
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua spoke briefly, recalling
conflicts both countries had with the United States.
   ``In difficult moments, he was always close,'' Ortega said of
Gadhafi, according to an unofficial translation of his remarks in
Spanish. ``We both had difficult moments. I owe him so much.''
   Hafez Assad, president of Syria, and chairman Yasser Arafat of
the Palestine Liberation Organization, who have been at odds for
years, chatted before the parliament session began.
   Other leaders attending included Omar Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir, the
military ruler of Sudan; President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria, and
Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, president of Tunisia.
   There were reports that a summit was possible of five countries
trying to form a North African economic union, but a Western
diplomat said disagreements has arisen over finances. The nations
are Algeria, Libya, Mauritania, Morocco and Tunisia.
   On the eve of the anniversary, Gadhafi acted to bury the hatchet
with Chad, Libya's southern neighbor and adversary in a 16-year war.
The two countries signed an accord Thursday in Algiers declaring a
formal end to over the mineral-rich Aouzou border strip.
   Western European diplomats estimated Gadhafi spent hundreds of
millions of dollars preparing Tripoli for the festivities.
   In the past year, Gadhafi has loosened restrictions on Libyan
commerce and tried to mend fences with Arab neighbors and reduce
tensions with the West.
   A Western diplomat said the Libyan leader even invited President
Bush and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain. The
highest-ranking Western visitor was Gianni De Michelis, Italy's
foreign minister. Libya was once a colony of Italy.
   U.S. relations with Libya have been sour for years. Reagan
ordered the bombing of Tripoli and Benghazi in April 1986 because of
Gadhafi's alleged support for international terrorism.
</TEXT>
