<FIRST>u a AM-MilitaryFuneral     09-01 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Funeral,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>World War II Veteran Buried Nearly 50 Years Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEAVENWORTH, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a half century ago, a young Army
airman left his wife and family in Wichita to fight World War II
over the skies of the Pacific Ocean.
   On Friday, 1st Lt. Robert Schwensen was finally laid to rest
here, a year after his remains were discovered by Australian gold
miners atop a mountain in a dense jungle of New Guinea.
   Schwensen and four other men aboard a C-47 had been listed as
missing in action since their aircraft was shot down by Japanese
fighter planes in February 1943.
   Schwensen was buried under overcast skies with an honor guard and
a 21-gun salute at Fort Leavenworth's National Cemetery, close to
the grave of his oldest brother, Capt. Justus Schwensen, who died in
a bomb run over Hamburg, Germany, in 1945. Another brother, 1st Lt.
Richard Schwensen, was killed by small arms fire at Remagen,
Germany, less than a month before Capt. Schwensen's death.
   ``At last, he's going to finally be home where he belongs,'' June
Rockhill, the woman Robert Schwensen left behind in the fall of
1942, said in an earlier interview. She was 18 at the time and
married just three months.
   After coming to terms with her husband's disappearance and
apparent death, she married Kenneth Rockhill of Eureka in 1947.
   ``This has been very trying for me and my husband. It brings back
a lot of memories,'' she said. ``But my husband's been wonderful
through the whole thing.''
   Mr. and Mrs. Rockhill and Schwensen's two surviving brothers _
E.W. ``Swede'' Schwensen of Del Mar, Calif., and Dr. John Schwensen
of Mansfield, Texas _ were among the hushed audience of about 100 at
the rites.
   `I thought the ceremony was lovely,'' said Mrs. Rockhill, who
cried during the service. ``There have been so many memories over
the years, and this sort of finalizes everything.''
   A C-47, an olive-colored World War II transport, circled the
cemetery before the ceremony. Later, three fighter jets flew over
the cemetery, covered with rows and rows of small white grave
markers.
   Chaplain Col. James H. McKinney officiated at the service and
said, ``The jungle of New Guinea has given us back those remains so
we can bury a ghost.''
   Brother Swede Schwensen described his brother as ``just a tough
kid.''
   ``We're glad that it's all put to rest now. We can pay our final
respects,'' he said after the ceremony.
   He walked a few steps to the grave of Richard Schwensen after the
ceremony and prayed.
   John Schwensen, who is a minister, gave the eulogy. In an
interview after the ceremony, he said of his dead brother: ``He was
in New Guinea and now he is at rest in our own minds here. It does
give us some consolation. My only wish is that my parents were
here.''
   He said he was just 12 years old when he learned that his brother
was missing in action. ``At first, I didn't understand it, but then
I realized that life has death in it,'' he said.
   Air Force officials in Washington said it is rare to find the
remains of missing servicemen so long after World War II.
   They said identifying Robert Schwensen's remains was difficult
because the Air Force no longer had records of his relatives. Both
his parents had died.
   Swede Schwensen contacted the Casualty Memorial Affairs Office in
Alexandria, Va., and made the arrangements for his brother's remains
to be flown to Kansas for burial at Fort Leavenworth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
