<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-Drugs     09-01 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Drugs,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Mayor Complains to Thornburgh About Leaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry asked Friday to meet with
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh over press reports that federal
investigators have been told the mayor smoked crack on several
occasions.
   In a letter to Thornburgh, Barry said disclosures concerning the
Justice Department's investigation into his links with convicted
drug dealer Charles Lewis have damaged his ability to govern the
city.
   He said he hoped Thornburgh would follow U.S. Attorney Jay B.
Stephens' request for a full investigation into the disclosures..
   ``This is an issue bigger than Marion Barry Jr. and the politics
of the District of Columbia,'' Barry said in the letter. ``It is
about the fundamental principles upon which our system of laws is
based.''
   David Runkel, the Justice Department's chief spokesman, refused
Friday to comment directly on the mayor's request, but indicated
that an inquiry is standard in such cases.
   ``You can assume whenever there is an unauthorized disclosure of
information, there will be an investigation,'' Runkel said.
   Earlier this year, Thornburgh ordered an investigation into leaks
that Rep. Bill Gray, D-Pa., was being questioned by federal
investigators.
   Gray, then in a campaign for the Democratic whip's post in the
House that he went on to win, also had complained to Thornburgh
about leaks from the Justice Department.
   The Justice Department responded by declaring that Gray was not
the target of an investigation and Thornburgh went as far as saying
he was willing to subpoena reporters' telephone records in order to
find the source of the leaks.
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens declined Friday to comment on
whether Lewis has implicated Barry in interrogations by federal
agents. But Stephens said he wants the Justice Department to
investigate whether stories about Lewis' cooperation originated with
law enforcement officials.
   In his letter to Thornburgh, Barry said everyone involved in the
investigation of his contacts with Lewis is a Justice Department
employee.
   ``There seems to be one or more persons who, with impunity, are
systematically leaking information that is part of an on-going
investigation,'' Barry's letter said. ``The reality of all of this
is that once published, unsubstantiated allegations take on a life
of their own and are repeated as fact.''
   Quoting unnamed sources, The Washington Post has reported that
Lewis identified to federal investigators four women in the Virgin
Island who he claims can back up his allegations that Barry used
crack and other drugs there.
   At least one woman has given investigators a statement backing
Lewis' account that Barry smoked crack on one occasion, the Post
quoted the sources as saying.
   WUSA-TV earlier quoted sources as saying that Lewis has told
investigators he smoked crack with the mayor in Lewis' hotel room in
December.
   Another station and newspaper, WRC-TV and The Washington Times,
have carried stories in the past two days saying federal
investigators believe they have enough evidence to seek an
indictment of Barry on perjury and obstruction of justice charges.
   Lewis has been charged with perjury and cocaine possession and
trafficking in connection with a federal probe that began last
December after city police inexplicably called off an attempt to
make an undercover drug buy from Lewis when they learned Barry was
in Lewis' hotel room.
   For the past several years, Barry has been dogged by rumors that
he uses drugs. On Thursday, he repeated his claim that he never saw
or used drugs during at least six visits to Lewis' room.
   Barry had been scheduled to appear Friday with the city's new
drug czar, Sterling Tucker, but the news conference was canceled
Thursday. About two hours before the news conference, city officials
also canceled Tucker's appearance.
</TEXT>
