<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Trial     09-01 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Trial,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Cuban Interior Minister Given 20 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Abrantes, a former interior minister of
Cuba, was sentenced to 20 years in prison for abuse of office and
other charges related to the drug trafficking scandal in Fidel
Castro's government.
   Prensa Latina, the Cuban government's news agency, said Friday
the same military court that orderd the prison term for Abrantes
sentenced six other officials to terms of up to 12 years. The
dispatch, monitored in Mexico City, said the Communist Party
newspaper Granma reported the sentences.
   Abrantes, who was fired in June for failing to detect drug
trafficking in his ministry, was convicted of abuse of office,
improper use of financial resources and property, and negligence in
service, according to the report.
   The Communist Party's Central Committee expelled Abrantes and
Pascual Martinez, a former vice minister of the interior, from the
party and Abrantes lost his post as a deputy in the Mariano
municipal assembly, the dispatch said.
   The court reported that lieutenant colonels Manuel Gil and
Rolando Castaneda were demoted to private and army authorities would
be asked to take similar steps against Abrantes and Martinez, who
are both division generals, and Brig. Gen. Roberto Gonzalez, Prensa
Latina said.
   It said the Council of State would be asked to cancel honorary
titles and decorations held by the defendants and advise government
agencies of any illegal transfers of property that were revealed.
   Martinez was sentenced to 12 years in prison; Gonzalez to 10
years; Lt. Col. Oscar Carreno to seven years; Castaneda, six years;
Gil, five years, and civilian Hector Carbonell, eight years, on
various charges.
   President Castro personally ordered Abrantes to investigate
reports that Cuba was a transit point for tons of Colombian cocaine
en route to the United States, Prensa Latina reported during the
trial.
   During the four-day trial that ended Sunday, prosecutors said
Abrantes' mistakes were so bad in handling the narcotics
investigation they appeared to have been deliberate, but not enough
evidence existed to accuse him of treason, according to Prensa
Latina.
   It reported the prosecutors said Abrantes knew in February that
officials in his ministry were involved in drug trafficking but took
no action.
   Four military officers were executed in July for their roles in
the trafficking and 10 others drew sentences of up to 30 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
