<DOCNO> AP890901-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2220EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Giamatti     09-01 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Giamatti,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Contribution to Ethics, Education</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine _ President Bush paid tribute Friday evening
to A. Bartlett Giamatti, saying the late baseball commissioner stood
``for the highest possible ethical standards.''
   ``Bart was a close friend of mine for many, many years,'' Bush
said. ``I just want to pay my respects. He was a great person.
   ``He loved the game of baseball and in a short time made a real
contribution to the game, standing for the highest possible ethical
standards.''
   Both men had graduated from Yale, where Bush was captain of the
1948 baseball team and Giamatti became president before becoming
baseball commissioner.
   Bush added Giamatti's ``contribution to higher education in this
country is well known, and on top of all that, he was a thoroughly
decent human being.''
   Bush's son George recently became part owner of the Texas
Rangers, and the president and Giamatti attended several major
league baseball games together this season, including the Rangers at
Baltimore.
   Speaking of Giamatti's decision to ban Pete Rose from baseball
for life for gambling, Bush said: ``That was not an easy matter for
him. I had not commented on it, but I have talked to him at great
length about it.''
   Bush said he had tried to get in touch with Giamatti recently to
talk about the Rose case and ``just missed'' the return call a few
days ago.
   ``All through that I was thinking of the difficultly that he had
in setting these standards that high and staying with it,'' said
Bush.
</TEXT>
