<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2044EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CrashRuling 2ndLd-Writethru a0692 09-01 0863</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Ruling, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0692,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Blames Crew, Absolves Weather Service in Delta 191 Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to emphasize finding that Delta crew was at fault;
UPDATES throughout with quotes and details on ruling. Edits to conform.
No pick up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA WEISGERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Friday blamed the crew of a
Delta Air Lines jet for a 1985 crash that killed 137 people, even
though air traffic controllers had failed to warn the crew of severe
weather.
   In a 72-page opinion, U.S. District Judge David O. Belew Jr. said
Delta had failed to prove that the National Weather Service and
controllers at the Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport were
negligent.
   In the longest major aviation trial in U.S. history, attorneys
for Delta had argued that the weather was to blame for the crash
because crew members didn't have sufficient warning about the
severity of a thunderstorm at the airport.
   The airline had sought to make the government pay all or part of
the millions of dollars in claims arising from the crash.
   The Atlanta-based airline said it would appeal the decision,
saying it was ``in direct conflict with the recent jury verdict ...
in Fort Lauderdale holding Delta blameless in all respects for the
accident.''
   Delta ``continues to believe that the facts surrounding this case
clearly establish total government responsibility for the tragic
accident.''
   In Washington, Joe Friday, assistant administrator for weather
services at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration,
said: ``We are continuing to work with the FAA (Federal Aviation
Administration) and the aviation industry to improve our science and
technology so that this kind of tragedy will not be repeated.''
   The Lockheed L-1011, en route from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to
Dallas, crashed trying to land at DFW on Aug. 2, 1985, when it was
caught in a downburst of wind during a thunderstorm. The accident
killed 137; 27 people on board survived.
   Windle Turley, a Dallas attorney representing a dozen victims of
the crash, said he was pleased with the ruling. ``We're very happy.
We felt from the beginning that Delta was the only negligent party
in this case,'' he said.
   Belew said the crew of Delta Flight 191 knew, or should have
known, that there was severe weather on the approach to the airport,
and that the thunderstorms were likely to cause dangerous wind
shear, an abrupt change in wind direction and force.
   A National Transportation Safety Board investigation had blamed
wind shear for the crash.
   In his ruling, the judge said that ``attempting to land the
aircraft in a thunderstorm constituted negligence on the part of the
crew of DL191, and proximately caused the crash.''
   The government, however, did not escape criticism.
   Belew said DFW tower personnel should have taken steps to be sure
that incoming pilots were aware of the weather's severity, and that
a meteorologist should have been sure that the weather was being
monitored continuously while he took a long dinner break.
   But Belew cited other cases in which a controller's failure to
warn pilots of bad weather was not considered negligent when the
pilot already was aware of conditions.
   He said the failure of air traffic controllers to route the plane
to another runway was not negligent, particularly because the pilots
did not request a new runway.
   Yet ``the court considers the failure of governmental employees
to pass on weather information to have been inconsequential to the
fate of (Flight) 191 in that there is no evidence that the crew
would have acted differently with this confirmation of information
already known.''
   The trial began in March 1988 and lasted almost 14 months,
although it recessed several times so Belew could clear backlogged
criminal cases.
   The government argued that the flight crew didn't heed FAA tower
warnings, didn't ask for weather information and decided to fly into
the storm. The government also says the jet's radar should have
warned the pilots of weather conditions.
   The flight crew was killed in the crash.
   Delta has paid at least $66 million in death, injury and damage
claims from the Flight 191 crash, but in those cases, survivors
waived the issue of liability.
   In the only previous case that considered liability, a U.S.
District Court jury in Fort Lauderdale determined that Delta was
blameless in the crash.
   Delta attorney John Martin, during final arguments in the Fort
Worth case after testimony ended in April, said the pilots did not
know about the ``nightmarish wind shear.''
   ``The pilots of 191 were certainly not aware of impending doom,''
he said.
   Wind shear is considered particularly dangerous at low altitudes
and when pilots are taking off and landing. Such a downburst of air
can cause a plane to lose altitude quickly.
   The judge said Delta's overall training program for pilots in
wind-shear situations was ``lax,'' but not negligent.
   Belew ruled out the possibility that tranquilizers Capt. Edward
M. Connors might have been taking at the time of the accident
contributed to the crash, saying the evidence was too speculative.
Government attorneys had argued that Connors' use of Valium and
Stelazine might have impaired his ability to properly respond to the
situation.
</TEXT>
