<FIRST>r a AM-BangladeshiGirl     09-01 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladeshi Girl,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Lets Bangladeshi Sex Abuse Victim Return To Foster Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTESANO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old Bangladeshi girl molested by
the man who brought her to the United States was ordered returned
Friday to her foster home, which state officials previously had said
wasn't ``culturally relevant.''
   Grays Harbor County Superior Court Judge Michael Spencer
overturned a court commissioner's ruling that let state Child
Protective Services take the child, known as Kushi, from her Hoquiam
home on the central Washington coast and place her with her sister
in nearby Lacey.
   Kushi, a Moslem, was brought to the United States along with
several other family members by Stefan Christopher, a former United
Nations consultant who had the family live and work on his farm.
   Christopher, 52, married one of Kushi's older sisters, divorced
her and then married Kushi's 12-year-old sister.
   On Sept. 11, he faces sentencing for guilty pleas to taking
indecent liberties with the girl and two other children. Sheriff's
department officials say Christopher ``physically and
psychologically tortured'' the family.
   The Superior Court commissioner had decided after a closed
hearing that the foster home didn't offer a ``culturally relevant''
upbringing as required by the state. Neither foster parent is Moslem.
   More than 200 people marched on the state capitol Monday to
demand the girl be returned to foster parents Bob Martin, a chemical
engineer, and Betsy Seidel, a middle school English and geography
teacher.
   ``I'm happy for now,'' said Seidel. ``I realize it's just
temporary but I'm thrilled. Kushi is coming back into our home.
That's where she belongs.''
   Details of Spencer's closed-door hearing were confirmed by state
officials and by Tom Copland, the child's court-appointed guardian.
   Copland sought the court hearing after being barred from the
earlier closed hearing that resulted in Kushi's removal from the
Martin-Seidel home. The girl will be returned there this weekend.
   ``Judge Spencer simply ruled that, under the facts of this case,
the Superior Court had the authority to require a (full court)
hearing prior to Kushi's removal from the foster home,'' said
Copland, an Aberdeen attorney.
   ``It was nothing more than a procedural ruling on an issue of law
and had nothing to do with the merits of the case or the actions or
motives of any party.''
   Howard Shuman, spokesman for the state Department of Social and
Health Services, said officials would continue trying to contact
Kushi's parents in Bangladesh to learn where they would prefer she
stay.
   Kushi currently is living with a sister who declined to comment
when contacted by The Associated Press. But Seidel said Kushi was
excited about the prospects of returning to their home.
   ``She called us collect last night and said she wanted to go to
school. She didn't understand why she couldn't,'' Seidel said.
</TEXT>
