<FIRST>a i PM-ArgentinaNow Adv08   09-01 0934</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina Now, Adv 08,0958</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs Sept. 8 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>In Two Months as Argentina's President, Carlos Menem Gains Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his first two months in office,
President Carlos Menem has imposed drastic measures on Argentines to
bring their chaotic economy back into line _ and he is winning their
support.
   He has more than tripled prices for public services _
electricity, gas and water rates; subway, bus and train fares _ and
has temporarily shored up an economy that had set off food riots and
forced the Radical Civic Union's Raul Alfonsin out of the presidency
22 weeks before his term was up.
   And while one of every two Argentines did not vote for Menem, the
Peronist, in May's presidential election, he now is gaining favor
for what he has done so far.
   ``There is more stability,'' said Juan Manuel Casa, a 29-year-old
car salesman who didn't vote for Menem. ``He's doing the right
things.''
   ``I think Menem is the only way to save the country,'' said
Ricardo Gutierrez, a suit salesman, who also did not vote for Menem.
   The public-service price increases have narrowed an unsustainable
budget deficit, while a 54 percent devaluation has stabilized the
austral currency and brought down interest rates.
   Wage and price guidelines have cooled hyperinflation. While the
cost of living rose by 197 percent in July, the rate for August is
projected at 35 percent and for September at 10 percent or less.
   ``What's most important is that it is going down,'' said Victor
Vazquez-Presedo, a business school dean, noting that inflation had
not risen for the first time since last November. ``Everyone thought
we were mired in hyperinflation and that was frightening.''
   Stores in Buenos Aires are well stocked now. Merchants are no
longer worried about inflation rising from day to day and accept
credit cards again. The price of a steak or a quart of milk no
longer is front-page news.
   Early rains have bolstered predictions of a 41 million-ton farm
harvest, including wheat, soybeans and corn, which would mean a 60
percent increase over last year's harvest. Central Bank reserves
have increased to about $1 billion. The International Monetary Fund
has resumed negotiations on Argentina's request for a $1.5
billion-loan.
   Although taking a taxi and dining out still are relative luxuries
for most Argentines, real wages are about 30 percent higher than
they were in June, if still 30 percent below what they were in
January.
   ``I have friends who renewed their passports in anticipation that
things would not get better,'' said Isidro Soloaga, an economist
with the Latin America Research Foundation. ``Now, no one talks
about that and hardly any left.''
   Menem's popularity has increased since the election May 14. To
his Peronist Party's base of organized labor, he has attracted
middle-class support by appointing a conservative Cabinet, pledging
to sell off state industries, and lowering taxes on farm exports.
   Two polls have put his public approval rating at 80 percent or
better. In the election, he won just under 50 percent of the vote in
the multiparty race.
   ``What our polls are showing is that ... when people are shown
economic plans they have faith in, even though there must be
sacrifices, there is public support,'' said Marbita Carballo de
Cilley, who directed the Gallup poll that gave Menem a positive
rating of 87 percent.
   Menem has persuaded organized labor to accept wage increases
below inflation rates, big business to contribute to social welfare
programs, provinces to forgo federal subsidies, farmers to plant
more wheat and soybeans.
   He also has taken the political risk of talking to the British
about restoring the diplomatic relations broken off when the
Argentine military governnent then in power launched an invasion of
the Falkland Islands in 1982 _ only to go down to defeat.
   Human rights groups aren't happy, however, about a pending pardon
or amnesty for military officers accused of torturing and executing
people they suspected of being leftist subversives during the
1976-83 dictatorship.
   ``I don't think people will react violently to a pardon,'' said
Hebe de Bonafini, president of the Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo,
whose children disappeared or were killed in the military years.
``People are hemmed in by the economy, by hunger.''
   While Menem apparently is off to a good start, success remains a
long way off.
   An estimated 9 million of Argentina's 32 million people live at
or below the poverty line, and about one of every seven workers is
unemployed. Soup kitchens set up three months ago are still open.
   Unions representing doctors, teachers, commuter-train personnel
and others have gone on strike for higher wages or have announced
plans to do so. Police in northwest Tucuman province 25 had to use
tear gas Aug. 25 to break up a sit-in by several hundred public
employees.
   The political coalition Menem forged after taking office has
approved legislation transferring authority from Congress to the
presidency to sell state companies, but it is fraying over proposals
to suspend subsidies to businesses and the provinces.
   Organized labor fears the selling of state-run companies may lead
to cutbacks in jobs and wages, despite Menem's assurances to the
contrary. Political opponents worry that Menem might be
concentrating too much power in the presidency.
   The coalition may or may not hold together for other pending
legislation, including tax reform and updating the constitution to
allow a president to seek re-election.
   But for now, Argentines are taking Menem on faith.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
