<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv05   09-01 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 05,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday, Sept. 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stock Analysts Explore New Territory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market's strength has presented a
special challenge for a breed of Wall Streeters known as technical
analysts: How do you interpret charts and indicators when prices
reach levels never seen before?
   All but the newest of newcomers have experience dealing with this
kind of situation, from the day in early 1983 when the Dow Jones
industrial average hit 1,070 for the first time through the top at
2,722 in August 1987.
   But all that practice wasn't enough for them to find any
foolproof system for determining when a market at new peaks has
further to go and when it is running out of steam.
   Most do agree that stocks now are nowhere near the extreme
``overvalued'' levels they reached two years ago, so easy to spot
now with the advantage of hindsight.
   Still, a good many chart-watchers see cause for concern, or at
least caution, heading into the last four months of 1989.
   Consider that most basic of measures for evaluating the market,
the ratio of stock prices to corporate earnings.
   As measured by the leading market indexes, the price-earnings
ratio of a typical stock recently stood at about 13 to 1, down from
about 20 to 1 in 1987.
   ``P-E ratios at 13 or so don't seem `too high,''' said Martin
Zweig, editor of the investment advisory letter The Zweig Forecast.
   ``But what are `peak earnings' worth? The business cycle has been
up for seven years. If we're headed for recession, stocks are
anything but cheap.''
   Zweig also notes that stocks are trading at more than 2.5 times
their book value, or theoretical worth if the companies they
represent were liquidated. Only twice before has that ratio been
higher, just preceding the crashes of 1929 and 1987.
   Short-term measures of sentiment, or enthusiasm for stocks,
``deteriorated expectably in August,'' said Philip Roth, technical
analyst at the securities firm of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Roth also observed, however, ``The trend is up. We would become
more negative on it only if volume stays high but prices fail to
move ahead.''
   Andrew Gold at Prudential-Bache Securities says several measures
of ``momentum,'' such as the cumulative number of stocks advancing
minus those declining, topped out a few weeks ago, before the Dow
Jones industrials and other market indicators pushed on to new highs.
   This and other signals ``suggest the market is headed for an
intermediate-term peak sometime this fall,'' he contends.
   But amid all the wariness, some analysts cast ringing votes for
further market gains.
   ``At no time in the past 18 months have conditions been more
bullish than they are today,'' proclaims Stephen Leeb, editor of the
advisory letter Indicator Digest.
   ``Some might argue that stocks are no longer cheap, since P-Es
have risen. While that is true, it is also true that inflation has
fallen.
   ``What really counts is not the absolute level of P-Es, but how
high P-Es are relative to inflation. By that measure stocks are
about as cheap as they have been in the postwar period.''
   Leeb says he believes the bull market has at least another year
to run. ``There are going to be reactions along the way, maybe some
as severe as 7 percent or 9 percent,'' he concludes.
   ``But the big rewards will continue to go to those who play the
big trend rather than the short-term swings.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues Sept 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0533EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-Labor'sDay Adv04   09-01 1236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Labor's Day, Adv 04,1270</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday AMs Sept. 4 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Labor Celebrates Success Abroad, But Questions Abound At Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern Airlines employees, coal
miners and phone workers are the symbol of both the uncertainty and
solidarity the American labor movement reflects on this Labor Day.
   In an extraordinary year, labor has suffered some major losses
yet won some impressive victories, although the spotlight on the
negatives has tended to obscure the bright spots.
   A number of unions have proven that labor-management cooperation
can work but, as in the case of the United Auto Workers, learned as
well that too much of a ``good'' thing can prove troublesome.
   Others have found hope in their solidarity _ particularly in the
Eastern and miners' strikes _ but will spend labor's traditional
holiday wondering if their jobs are the price they will pay for
their pride and determination.
   The movement has lost one nemesis, Ronald Reagan, but gained
another, Frank Lorenzo.
   Union workers here can take pride in remarkable developments in
Poland _ their dues helped support the Solidarity trade union from
its underground days to its historic rise as leader of the first
non-communist government in the East bloc. Through the AFL-CIO, U.S.
unions funneled thousands of dollars worth of printing equipment and
other supplies to Solidarity while it was outlawed.
   ``I think the role of the American trade union movement in this
should not be overlooked,'' AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said
last week.
   Kirkland, head of the 14-million member AFL-CIO, the major
umbrella group for the nearly 18 million Americans who belong to
unions, says those who are eulogizing the labor movement don't
understand it.
   ``The key to any evaluation of the labor movement ought to
examine what we regard as the most important measure and that is
internal cohesiveness and solidarity,'' he said. ``And I think it's
fair to say that we do have a higher degree of solidarity and
cohesion today than we've had in many, many years.''
   A number of developments bolster Kirkland's point. Among them:
   _The virtually unprecedented support of the pilots' union when
the Machinists union struck Eastern on March 4.
   _Joint negotiations between former enemies, the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, with AT&amp;T and the ``baby Bell'' regional telephone
companies. That solidarity continued in a number of strikes against
the regional companies.
   _Nationwide wildcat strikes to support 1,700 miners who struck
Pittston Coal Group after lengthy and bitter negotiations failed to
bring a settlement. Pittston is seeking to halt its contributions to
union pension funds, a move that likely would cause other companies
to follow suit.
   Still, there have been setbacks for labor as well.
   A trickle of defections among union pilots turned into a steady
flow that has allowed Eastern _ and Lorenzo _ to move ahead with
plans to reorganize the carrier as a smaller, non-union airline.
Labor still hopes to use Congress and bankruptcy court to oust
Lorenzo but its chances appear slim as the strike reaches the
six-month mark on Labor Day.
   The most highly publicized failure of ``Big Labor'' was the Auto
Workers' defeat in an election at a Nissan plant in Smyrna, Tenn.,
its first attempt to organize a U.S. plant fully owned by the
Japanese. The UAW lost by a 2-1 margin in a fight many within labor
said the UAW was too hasty to bring to a conclusion by calling the
election.
   The vote came just weeks after UAW President Owen Bieber beat
back a drive by a dissident group that sought to oust the union's
leadership because of labor-management cooperation the group said
had gone too far.
   At Nissan, and at other industries that traditionally have been
the backbone of trade unions, the labor movement is running into two
main obstacles: management programs to undermine union support by
giving workers more say and perks, and intricate anti-union
campaigns to defeat organizing drives including screening applicants
to determine their attitudes toward unions.
   At Smyrna, Nissan screened more than 100,000 workers for about
3,000 jobs.
   But Kirkland said the Japanese aren't to blame for doing that.
   ``They are led into this course in some cases not by anything
inherent in their culture or their own countries, because in many
instances they have a history of dealing with trade unions in their
own countries with good faith, but are following the advice of
hustlers, American hustlers, who have made a new profession out of
trying to guide employers for a fee,'' Kirkland said.
   To counter such tactics, labor is changing the way it looks at
organizing and now accepts as ``associate members'' workers at
plants where organizing efforts failed and immigrant workers looking
for residency status in the United States.
   By getting its foot in the door, and offering those workers
benefits such as cut-rate credit cards, insurance and legal
services, unions hope to foster goodwill that will bring success in
later elections.
   Such a concept, once reviled by traditionalists in the movement,
has brought in 300,000 associate members in the past three years
and, according to Kirkland and other federation officials, is
beginning to pick up steam.
   The federation also is now stepping in to avoid most fighting
among unions by deciding which affiliate should get the chance at
non-union companies targeted for organizing. And the affiliates are
making fresh efforts at attracting women, minorities and workers in
the growing service sector.
   The noisy year for labor has to some degree obscured some
remarkable contract agreements.
   The Steelworkers union won back many of the concessions workers
were forced to give earlier in the decade when the industry was
nearly crippled.
   The CWA and IBEW came out of the AT&amp;T talks and the regional
negotiations settled so far with contracts that include innovative
packages of parental leave, elder care and child care benefits.
   And UAW workers at a joint Chrysler-Mitsubishi plant in Illinois
last week agreed on a new contract believed to have the best
job-protection provisions ever included in a major industrial
contract.
   In the final months of 1989 the Eastern strike and legislative
initiatives are likely to dominate labor's agenda.
   Pending on Capitol Hill are efforts to raise the minimum wage and
a number of other labor-backed measures, including expanded child
care benefits and a number of bills designed to curb mergers and
acquisitions. Also pending, but unlikely to pass, is a measure
designed to force President Bush to intervene in the Eastern strike.
   Kirkland refers to Bush as ``Reagan Lite,'' sharing his former
boss' pro-management bent but not his virulent anti-union
philosophy. Bush is regarded as no friend of the labor movement, but
not as its No. 1 enemy, as was Reagan.
   That designation has been passed to Lorenzo, who was successful
in making Continental Airlines a non-union carrier and appears on
the verge of winning again at Eastern.
   His recent talk of selling Continental has sparked hope in the
labor movement that the airline unions might yet pull a victory out
of defeat.
   Kirkland said there will be no winners even if the carrier
returns to the union fold. But his contempt for Lorenzo was clearly
evident as he added a caveat.
   ``Scorched earth on both sides is not a victory,'' he said. ``Of
course it's better than scorched earth on just one side.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs Sept. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:FallFilms Adv05   09-01 1171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Fall Films, Adv 05,1206</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, Sept. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Autumn Movie Season Features Return of Screen Legends</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marlon Brando, Paul Newman, Gregory Peck and
Audrey Hepburn return to the screen this fall, adding starpower to
new films that are expected to continue the industry's
record-breaking year at the nation's theaters.
   ``The autumn movies look better than last year's; every company
has promising films,'' comments John Krier of Exhibitor Relations
Co., which compiles box-office figures. ``It's a well-balanced fall.
   ``In addition to the new films, several of the summer movies will
continue into the fall. `Batman' and `Lethal Weapon 2' are holding
well, and there is also strength in `Parenthood,' `When Harry Met
Sally ...' and `sex, lies and videotape.'''
   Drama is the strong suit in the Hollywood autumn this year. The
most anticipated return is that of Marlon Brando, missing from the
screen for nine years. He stars with Donald Sutherland in ``A Dry
White Season,'' about a white family and a black family in 1976
South Africa.
   Brando also just finished shooting ``The Freshman'' with Matthew
Broderick in Canada. He predicted the movie would be a flop, and
announced to the Canadian press that he was fed up with moviemaking
and ``The Freshman'' was his last film.
   ``I wish I hadn't finished with a stinker,'' he said.
   Paul Newman, whose last film was his Academy Award-winning ``The
Color of Money,'' will be seen in two movies. In ``Fat Man and
Little Boy'' he takes part in the building of the first atomic bomb.
In ``Blaze,'' he's Louisiana governor Earl K. Long, who had a
much-publicized romance with a stripper, Blaze Starr (Lolita
Davidovich).
   Gregory Peck returns in ``Old Gringo,'' playing the American
iconoclast Ambrose Bierce in a Mexican revolution adventure also
starring Jane Fonda and Jimmy Smits.
   A film directed by Steven Spielberg is always an event. This fall
will bring his ``Always,'' loosely based on the World War II
fantasy, ``A Guy Named Joe.'' The stars: Audrey Hepburn, Richard
Dreyfuss and Holly Hunter.
   Other star turns include:
   Bette Midler in ``Stella,'' the fourth version of the tearjerker
``Stella Dallas.''
   Jessica Lange as a criminal lawyer defending her father on war
crime charges in ``Music Box.''
   Jane Fonda and Robert De Niro as a widow and a fellow factory
worker who can't read in ``Stanley and Iris.''
   Jack Nicholson in ``The Two Jakes,'' the long-postponed sequel to
``Chinatown.''
   Tom Selleck as a airline worker serving time after a frameup by
crooked cops in ``An Innocent Man.''
   Al Pacino and Ellen Barkin in ``Sea of Love,'' described as ``an
erotic suspense thriller.''
   Jack Lemmon, Ted Danson and Olympia Dukakis in a generational
drama, ``Dad.''
   Tom Cruise in ``Born on the Fourth of July,'' based on the life
of the handicapped Vietnam veteran Ron Kovic.
   Bruce Willis and Emily Lloyd in Norman Jewison's ``In Country,''
about a family struggling to heal Vietnam war wounds.
   And for one of the biggest star casts in years, see ``Steel
Magnolias,'' from the hit play by Robert Harling about life in a
Southern beauty parlor. The players: Sally Field, Dolly Parton,
Shirley MacLaine, Daryl Hannah, Olympia Dukakis, Julia Roberts, Tom
Skerritt and Sam Shepard.
   ``The Fabulous Baker Boys'' stars Jeff and Beau Bridges as
brothers who are cocktail-lounge piano players. Into their lives
falls Michelle Pfeiffer.
   Helen Mirren and Paul Scofield in ``When the Whales Came.'' Set
on the Isles of Scilly at the beginning of World War I, the film is
about our relationship with the natural world, specifically with
narwhals.
   ``Enemies, a Love Story'' is director Paul Mazursky's adaptation
of Isaac Bashevis Singer's novel about a man (Ron Silver) and his
entanglements with three women: Anjelica Huston, Lena Olin and
Margaret Stein.
   Milos Forman's films are much anticipated. This time he has
undertaken another version of ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses,'' the last
being ``Dangerous Liaisons.'' Forman's is called ``Valmont.''
   Also in the dramatic vein: ``To Kill a Priest,'' Ed Harris and
Christopher Lambert; ``Johnny Handsome,'' Mickey Rourke and Morgan
Freeman; ``Welcome Home,'' Kris Kristofferson and JoBeth Williams;
Jessica Tandy, Freeman and Dan Aykroyd in the Broadway hit ``Driving
Miss Daisy.''
   Comedy isn't overlooked. Woody Allen returns in a film as yet
untitled, but he has revealed the cast: himself, Alan Alda, Daryl
Hannah, Anjelica Huston and Sam Waterston. Eddie Murphy and Richard
Pryor will appear in ``Harlem Nights,'' written and directed by
Murphy who was also executive producer.
   ``The War of the Roses'' features Michael Douglas, Kathleen
Turner and Danny DeVito in a comedy directed by DeVito. Douglas and
Turner star as a wealthy couple whose divorce attorney is played by
DeVito.
   Robert De Niro and Sean Penn undertake comedy in ``We're No
Angels,'' based on the Humphrey Bogart-Aldo Ray movie about escaped
cons. Glenn Close and James Woods also abandon drama for a humorous
look at parenthood in ``Immediate Family.'' Michael J. Fox and the
whole gang return in ``Back to the Future Part II.'' Look for Part
III next year.
   Monty Python's Terry Jones directs a spoof, ``Erik the Viking,''
with buddy John Cleese and Tim Robbins. Christopher Guest of
``Saturday Night Live'' takes on the New Hollywood in ``The Big
Picture,'' with Kevin Bacon as a film student turned hotshot
director.
   ``Worth Winning'' stars Mark Harmon as a handsome TV weatherman
whose dating habits are put to the test when a friend bets that he
can't get engaged to three women within three months.
   Chevy Chase and Beverly D'Angelo return as the troubled Griswolds
in ``National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation.'' John Laroquette and
Bronson Pinchot appear in a cop comedy, ``Second Sight.''
   Adventure is in fairly short supply. ``The Bear'' is based on
James Oliver Curwood's ``The Grizzly Bear,'' directed by
Jean-Jacques Annaud. ``The Bear,'' which stars a bear, is a French
movie released through Price Entertainment. It was released in Japan
and throughout Europe in 1987 and is coming to England. It has done
more than $90 million overseas.
   Sean Connery, Dustin Hoffman and Matthew Broderick play three
generations of robbers who attempt a big heist in ``Family
Business.'' Broderick and Denzel Washington star in ``Glory,'' about
a black fighting regiment in the Civil War. Michael Douglas is a New
York cop who braves the Japanese underworld in ``Black Rain.''
   Sylvester Stallone is back in the slammer again in ``Tango and
Cash,'' along with Kurt Russell; they're rival Los Angeles cops
framed by drug dealers. ``Next of Kin'' offers Patrick Swayze and
Liam Neeson in a Chicago police story.
   Two new animated features will provide some entertainment for the
younger crowd and their parents: ``The Little Mermaid,'' the first
Disney fairy tale since ``Sleeping Beauty'' in 1958; ``All Dogs Go
to Heaven,'' from Don Bluth (``An American Tail,'' ``The Land before
Time'').
   Awards for the busiest actors of the fall go to Olympia Dukakis
and John Goodman, each with three films. How does he ever find time
away from ``Roseanne''?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
