<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv04   09-01 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 04,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday Sept. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Specialty Retailers and Apparel Makers in Fashion Among Stock Pickers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big-ticket items ranging from refrigerators to
cars have moved slowly out of stores this year, but clothing has
been selling at a healthy rate.
   This pattern has drawn attention to stocks of retailers
specializing in apparel, particularly women's fashions, and clothing
manufacturers.
   Several Wall Street analysts expect the trend to continue and
recommend investing in selected retailers and apparel makers that
stand to profit from current spending preferences.
   The latest results from the country's major retailers showed
apparel sales rose again in August from the past year's blah pace.
The buildup in sales momentum was given an extra nudge by
back-to-school business.
   Jeffrey Feiner, a retail analyst at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., says
part of the pickup in August reflected the weakness at apparel
stores a year earlier when women rejected clothing styles. Women are
busily replacing worn out wardrobes this year after finding few
fashions that suited them for the last two years.
   ``We believe that the somewhat better-than-expected August sales
increases continue to reflect some shift in consumer spending away
from automobiles, houses and bigger ticket durables and toward the
enhancement of wardrobes,'' Feiner says, noting that high credit
costs and an uncertain economic outlook have made consumers
reluctant to make large outlays for expensive goods.
   ``We also believe this trend bodes well for retailers' profit
outlook,'' Feiner says.
   Cash registers at accessory and cosmetics counters also are
ringing up better sales.
   Low inflation in clothing prices should help maintain the rebound
in apparel spending, says Deborah Bronston, a textile and apparel
analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   With the memory of poor business in recent years still fresh,
manufacturers and specialty retailers have made an effort to control
price increases. Prices for materials and imports aren't rising as
fast as they had in other years in this decade, which makes
controlling markups somewhat easier.
   Clothing makers across the board are benefiting, says Bronston,
citing Leslie Fay Cos., Liz Claiborne Inc., Oshkosh B'Gosh Inc. and
Russell Corp. as examples.
   Elizabeth Armstrong, an analyst at Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben Inc.,
says her company also considers several clothing makers to be fine
investments right now, mentioning that prospects appear good for
Phillips-Van Heusen Corp. especially because of the improving
profitability at the G.H. Bass &amp; Co. shoe manufacturing division it
acquired in 1987.
   Robert Raiff of C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc. said that as
a group, apparel makers haven't really responded yet to the apparel
spending recovery, which means opportunities exist for significant
appreciation in stock prices.
   Among the clothing companies he thinks have substantial room for
improvement are Brown Group Inc., Hartmarx Corp., V.F. Corp., and
Kellwood Corp.
   Christopher Vroom of Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc. points out that
specialty apparel retailers have consistentedly outperformed mass
merchandisers, such as Sears, Roebuck and Co. and K mart Corp., this
year.
   Chains including Limited Inc., one of the country's leading
specialty apparel merchants, appear on investment firms' lists of
recommendations. Others talked about favorably on Wall Street
include Charming Shoppes Inc., Claire Stores Inc., Deb Shops, Gap
Inc. and Merry Go Round Enterprises Inc. as well as numerous
department stores that emphasize apparel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
