<FIRST>a w AM-NewstoUse Adv06   09-01 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-News to Use, Adv 06,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Sept. 6, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Woodcutting Time: Play Safe With Chainsaws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the arrival of autumn, thoughts begin
turning to keeping warm in winter's chill. That anticipation sends
thousands of Americans into the woods with chain saws, exacting a
heavy toll of fingers and toes among the unwary.
   In a typical year, the Consumer Product Safety Commission
reports, as many as 125,000 people are treated in hospital emergency
rooms for injuries related to chain saws.
   The largest share of injuries, nearly one in three, occur when
the saw operator is moving the saw, or changing his position, and
touches the moving cutting chain. The answer is simple: carefulness.
   Kickback is the No. 2 cause of injury, causing some 20 percent of
chain saw accidents, according to the safety commission. And
kickback injuries are often the most severe, with the chain striking
the head or face.
   Improved saws are reducing that toll, with the new models less
likely to kick back at the operator. This can still occur, however,
and the solution is the same: be careful.
   An example is remembering to hold the saw off to the side when
using it, so that if it does suddenly catch and jump back it will
miss the head and face.
   Cutting with the tip of the saw is particularly dangerous and
should be avoided.
   Saws skating or bouncing along instead of cutting account for 13
percent of saw accidents. Other major problems include loss of
balance, saws pinching and getting stuck, and tree branches falling
on the saw operator.
   Either gasoline and electric chain saws can be dangerous.
Gasoline saws can cause burns and fires; the electric ones can
result in shock if misused.
   The safety commission's advice is direct. To begin with, be sure
you know how to operate the saw correctly and that it is oiled, the
chain tension is set correctly and generally the machine is in
proper working order.
   Clear the work area so the chain will not contact anything other
than the wood to be cut. And place gasoline saws on the ground
before starting them; do not start them on your leg or knee.
   When using the saw, gloves can be a big help in maintaining a
grip. Always hold the saw firmly with both hands, and be sure of
your footing so you don't slip or lose your balance.
   When cutting larger pieces of wood use wedges to hold the sides
apart so they don't pinch the saw.
   When cutting logs, stand on the uphill side so the log doesn't
roll down on you when it comes free.
   And be very wary of cutting branches that are under tension; they
can spring loose suddenly, causing you to fall or lose control of
the saw.
   The safety commission urges dressing properly for chain-saw
cutting. This, the agency says, includes gloves and safety shoes,
eye goggles and relatively snug clothing so loose ends don't catch
on branches or the saw. A hard hat is also recommended, as are
hearing protectors in the case of gasoline-driven saws.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Sept. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
