<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FallTV-News Adv01-03   09-01 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fall TV-News, Adv 01-03,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01-03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 1-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fall News Programs Accented by Tabloid Television</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics and pressure groups might dislike
tabloid television, but the format will be back in force this fall.
   Led by the new syndicated shows ``Crimewatch Tonight,'' ``Hard
Copy'' ``Missing-Reward'' and network shows ``Rescue: 911'' and
``Unsolved Mysteries,'' a flurry of reality-based ``news'' programs
will play a conspicuous role in the coming television season.
   Along more conventional programming lines, CBS News will
broadcast three weekly magazine shows: Thursday's ``48 Hours,''
Sunday's ``60 Minutes'' with additional correspondents Meredith
Vieira and Steve Kroft (and no more Diane Sawyer) and ``Saturday
Night With Connie Chung,'' a retooled version of the network's
``West 57th.''
   CBS has yet to announce what Chung, who recently left NBC, will
do in her new program.
   Anchorman Dan Rather will return with a three-hour special
edition of ``48 Hours: Return to Crack Street,'' an update of CBS'
ground-breaking 1986 documentary on the drug trade. ``48 Hours:
Return to Crack Street'' will be shown on Sept. 14 at 8 p.m.; after
that, ``48 Hours'' will run one hour each week.
   CBS' ``Rescue: 911,'' following emergency personnel on their
rounds, will be narrated by William Shatner and is scheduled for
Tuesdays.
   In addition to Wednesday's ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' NBC's answer
to Fox's crime-busting series ``America's Most Wanted,'' the peacock
network is set to produce occasional episodes of ``Yesterday, Today
and Tomorrow.''
   ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow,'' which was slammed for its use
of news re-enactments when it debuted with three episodes this
summer, may return in January as a mid-season replacement, NBC says.
It is anchored by Mary Alice Williams, Maria Shriver and Chuck
Scarborough.
   ABC has two magazine shows, its returning ``20-20'' on Friday
nights and ``PrimeTime Live,'' a one-hour show built around the top
news stories of the week. Teaming Sam Donaldson with Sawyer,
``PrimeTime Live'' will be shown on Thursdays.
   Only a few small changes are planned for the network newscasts:
Rather is considering relating the day's events for the ``CBS
Evening News'' from a standing position, and Forrest Sawyer has
replaced Donaldson as anchor of ABC's ``World News Sunday.''
   The Fox Broadcasting Corp. will present its reality-based shows
``Cops'' and ``The Reporters'' in new time periods on Saturdays. The
science-themed program ``Beyond Tomorrow'' now runs 30 minutes on
Saturdays.
   ``America's Most Wanted'' will be shown in its regular slot on
Sundays.
   Among syndicated shows, ``Crimewatch Tonight'' will debut on
Sept. 11. With host Ike Papas, an ex-CBS newsman, ``Crimewatch
Tonight'' will chronicle breaking crime stories.
   ``Hard Copy,'' premiering Sept. 18, will feature three segments:
``Off the News,'' about the day's news, ``Centerpiece,'' highlighted
by point-of-view reporting, and a personality piece.
   Stacy Keach will host ``Missing-Reward,'' debuting Sept. 23. John
Majhor and Heidi Bohay, formerly of ``Hotel,'' will co-anchor
``After Hours,'' a late-night soft news magazine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 1-3</NOTE>
</DOC>
