<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest retailers issued mixed sales reports for
August, with apparel retailers and department stores faring better
than mass merchandisers during the back-to-school season.
   Industry analysts Thursday continued to detect signs that
consumers are hesitant about making big purchases.
   Consumer spending accounts for about two-thirds of U.S. economic
activity and retail sales are considered a key indicator of spending
trends.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories slumped 1.7 percent in
July to the lowest level in eight months, the government says.
   The report Thursday indicated that although a recession appears
remote, growth remains subdued.
   The Commerce Department said orders for both durable and
nondurable manufactured goods were at the lowest levels since
November. It was the second decline in three months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products dropped 1.4
percent from July to August, leaving the monthly average at a
year-ago level, the Agriculture Department says.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in its
preliminary report Thursday that lower prices for soybeans, corn,
lettuce and potatoes were mostly responsible for the decrease.
   Prices rose for cattle, apples, eggs and grapefruit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An index measuring the ability of the typical
American family to buy a home fell in July to the lowest level in
nearly four years, reflecting rising home prices.
   The National Association of Realtors said Thursday that a family
with a median income of $32,876 had only 98 percent of the income
necessary to buy a median-priced existing home costing $96,400.
   That was the index's lowest level since September 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish automaker Saab-Scania AB, facing
mounting losses and lay-offs, refused to confirm or deny news
reports that Ford Motor Co. is a leading suitor for its ailing
passenger car division.
   Following a board meeting Thursday, Jan-Erik Larsson, head of
Saab's auto division, declined to clarify a report in the Stockholm
tabloid Expressen that a takeover deal with Ford was imminent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has issued tighter
controls on cancer-causing benzene.
   The new restrictions will eliminate 90 percent of benzene
releases from industrial sources ranging from steel plants to
service stations, the Environmental Protection Agency said Thursday.
   But the curbs are expected to be quite costly _ and they do not
cover the primary source of benzene pollution, automobiles, the EPA
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Energy Department official illegally
participated in the award of a $1 billion contract to a group of
companies that included one of his former employers, a federal judge
found.
   Samuel Rousso was involved in a plan to award a contract to a
group led by Bechtel Management Systems Inc., U.S. Claims Court
Judge Reginald Gibson said in a finding released Thursday.
   The award would have been for a repository for high-level
radioactive waste.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $1 million bomb detector that the Federal
Aviation Administration starts operating Friday at a New York
airport is not sensitive enough to spot an explosive like the one
that destroyed Pan Am Flight 103 last December, Science magazine
reports.
   The magazine said the bomb detector is being set at a sensitivity
that will uncover about 2.5 pounds of plastic explosives.
   Science said British experts believe the bomb that brought down
the Pan Am flight in Scotland contained only about one pound of
explosive. The crash killed 270 people.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said it has abandoned an earlier
plan to sell its Latin American routes, which means the strikebound
carrier will have about $370 million less in cash by yearend than
first projected.
   But Rolf Andresen, Eastern's vice president of finance, insisted
Thursday that the cash balance of nearly $400 million now expected
to be available for operations and paying debts is ``an amount
that's very adequate for our needs.''
   Andresen reiterated Miami-based Eastern's pledge to pay all
creditors 100 percent with interest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A published report has raised the possibility
that convicted financier Ivan F. Boesky may have been cooperating
with federal investigators when he met with junk-bond trader Michael
Milken to allegedly plot a criminal coverup.
   The Washington Post reported Thursday that Boesky, now a key
government informant, allegedly met with Milken in July 1986, before
Wall Street's insider trading scandal erupted.
   A confidential Securities and Exchange Commission memorandum
indicated the two met ``to discuss how to `conceal the true nature'
of a $5.3 million payment from Boesky to Drexel,'' the Post said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved ahead Thursday. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials ended at its second-highest close, climbing 9.12 to
2,737.27.
   The dollar rose sharply Thursday against all key currencies,
reaching a two-month high against the Japanese yen.
   Bond prices fell.
   Copper futures prices surged on New York's Commodity Exchange.
Frost fears sent most grain and soybean futures higher; pork belly
futures rose sharply while livestock futures were mixed; precious
metals retreated; and energy futures advanced.
