<FIRST>r f PM-Matsushita-Motorola     09-01 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Matsushita-Motorola,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Matsushita to Buy Transistors for VCRs From Motorola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. Ltd., maker of
Panasonic, Quasar and Technics products, says it will buy about 5
million transistors a month from Motorola Inc. starting in September.
   The announcement Thursday in Tokyo follows up on an agreement
between the companies announced earlier this year. It marks the
first time a Japanese consumer electronics maker has made large
purchases of semiconductor devices custom-made by a U.S.-based
company.
   The transistors will come from a Motorola factory in Malaysia, so
the sales won't help American workers or the U.S. trade balance, but
Motorola spokesman Jeffrey Gorin said it was a good sign for other
sales.
   ``We see a thawing of trade restrictions,'' Gorin said.
   Motorola's sales of transistors to Matsushita are scheduled to
rise to 10 million a month in about a year, Matsushita said.
Motorola said it hopes to sell the transistors to other Japanese
companies as well.
   Matsushita uses about 50 million transistors a month in making
video cassette recorders. That is what the Motorola devices will be
used in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
