<DOCNO> AP890901-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0144EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BankReserves     09-01 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bank Reserves,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks May Have To Add To Loss Provision: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. banks likely will have to increase
their loan-loss provisions this year to protect themselves from
shaky foreign loans and an ``irreversible process of forgiveness''
initiated by the federal government, according to a leading Wall
Street credit rating firm.
   But the study by Moody's Investors Service warned that some banks
may be forced to restructure their operations as a result, and that
could mean future staff cuts or asset sales.
   Banks added more than $20 billion to their provisions for loan
losses in 1987, resulting in huge earnings declines or losses that
year for many. The credit ratings of many of the major money center
banks also were lowered.
   The Moody's report, released Wednesday, said more steps may be
needed because the Third World debt problem ``appears to be
unraveling further.''
   ``They (U.S. banks) are not all out of the woods yet,'' it said.
   The extent to which banks need to pad their loan-loss reserves
remains in dispute.
   Last spring, the General Accounting Office, the auditing arm of
Congress, said Third World countries were falling behind on $70
billion in debt repayments to U.S. banks and that American
regulators should make banks put up more reserves to protect
depositors against loan losses.
   But more recently, the U.S. comptroller of the currency
reportedly has proposed accounting changes that could discourage
banks from making large additions to their loan-loss reserves, in
order to avoid jeopardizing their quarterly dividend payments.
   Nonetheless, Moody's says, U.S. institutions still lag behind the
reserves taken by big European banks.
   Britain's central bank, for instance, recently required the four
big British banks to raise their loan-loss provisions so they would
amount to nearly half of their credits to troubled debtor nations,
up from around a third. The U.S. average is 30 percent.
   The Moody's report said the U.S. plan for reducing the $1.3
trillion Third World debt, known as the Brady plan, has begun ``an
irreversible process of forgiveness.'' The debt initiative places
more emphasis on having lender banks cut debt and interest payments
than on providing new loans.
   ``The U.S. government has shifted from one focused on protecting
the banks ... to one focused on protecting the political and
economic stability of the borrowers by encouraging debt reduction,''
the report said.
   Mexico in July became the first nation to reach a debt
restructuring agreement under the Brady plan, although a number of
its creditor banks reportedly have been slow to participate in the
plan.
   In that pact, banks were given the choice of reducing interest or
principle on the old debt or lending new money. At least one bank,
Citicorp, the nation's largest, said in a recent published report
that it would opt for making new loans.
   Moody's predicted the agreement with Mexico ``will provide the
country with very modest relief,'' and that further bank concessions
might be necessary ``unless officials sources step up their help.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
