<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   09-01 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abandons Plan to Sell Latin Routes, Foresees $370 Million Less in
Cash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said it has abandoned an earlier
plan to sell its Latin American routes, which means the strikebound
carrier will have about $370 million less in cash by year end than
first projected.
   But Rolf Andresen, Eastern's vice president of finance, insisted
Thursday that the cash balance of nearly $400 million now expected
to be available for operations and paying debts is ``an amount
that's very adequate for our needs.''
   In an operating plan presented to creditors in April, Eastern
projected a year-end cash balance of $774 million, but Andresen said
that will be reduced because the Latin American routes won't be sold.
   Andresen reiterated Miami-based Eastern's pledge to pay all
creditors 100 percent with interest.
   ``We have a profitable and totally financially viable airline,''
he said in a telephone interview.
   Earlier Thursday, Eastern President Phil Bakes, Andresen and
other senior officials told creditors that the airline's operating
results are better than projected in its April plan and it has
dropped intentions to sell any South American routes.
   The officials made a two-hour presentation to a meeting of the
creditors committee in New York, following speculation in recent
days that Eastern faces a revenue shortfall of up to $500 million
and may have to revise its plan for emerging from Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection.
   The Wall Street Journal quoted sources earlier this week as
saying that parent Texas Air Corp. may underwrite some of Eastern's
operations because the negotiations with rival American Airlines on
the sale of the usually profitable Latin American routes had stalled.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo announced last Thursday that he
is considering selling a minority or controlling interest in
Houston-based Continental Airlines, Texas Air's other airline
subsidiary.
   Bakes and other senior officers told the creditors they
anticipate profits before taxes of $62 million next year and $140
million in 1991.
   Attorneys representing the creditors committee didn't return
phone calls Thursday seeking comment.
   A spokesman for the pilots union, one of three that has been on
strike against Eastern since March 4, called the airline's admission
of a shortfall ``a clear indication that the (bankruptcy)
reorganization plan is doomed to failure.''
   Referring to the projected cash balance of $400 million or so,
pilots union spokesman Ron Cole said, ``We believe that that's an
extremely optimistic assessment on Eastern's part.''
   Eastern, under bankruptcy protection since March 9, has been
trying to rebuild to about two-thirds its pre-strike size and has
hired new pilots, mechanics and flight attendants to replace the
strikers.
   Andresen declined to say why the decision not to sell the Latin
American routes was made.
   ``There are many factors,'' he said. ``It's not a one-issue
answer.''
   Eastern previously claimed it was doing so well rebuilding from
the crippling strike that it will be bigger than expected after the
reorganization, hinting that the Latin American routes might not be
sold.
   Dallas-based American, the chief bidder for the routes, recently
expressed frustration at the lack of progress in the negotiations.
``The frustration factor is very real _ it's really not clear that
they want to sell,'' American spokesman Ed Stewart said in
mid-August.
   Raymond Neidl, an analyst for Dillon, Read &amp; Co. Inc., suggested
Thursday that Texas Air wanted top dollar for the routes and
probably was holding out for a higher figure than anyone offered.
   ``Long term, I think they're in better shape not selling it,'' he
said. ``If there is a cash shortfall, then they could take some
other actions.''
   Andresen said Eastern has received ``good prices'' for the assets
it has sold in recent months, mainly aircraft and airport gates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
