<FIRST>r f PM-AutoRecall     09-01 0097</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Recall,0101</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Recalls Merkur Summary Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 18,000 1988-89 Merkur Scorpio cars,
marketed by Lincoln-Mercury dealers, were recalled by Ford Motor Co.
because of a problem with a throttle sensor.
   The problem may cause the sensor to stick, making the West
German-made vehicles equipped with 2.9-liter engines to idle roughly
or too fast. The engine also may hesitate when put into gear.
   Ford said Thursday it will notify owners by mail and tell them to
return the cars to Ford dealers, where the sensor will be replaced
at no cost.
</TEXT>
