<FIRST>r f PM-ElDiario     09-01 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-El Diario,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>El Diario-La Prensa Sold to NY Investors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   El Diario-La Prensa, the Gannett Co.
Spanish-language daily newspaper with a 60,000 circulation, has been
sold to a group of New York investors who include the paper's
publisher.
   The paper's predecessors have a history of more than 100 years of
continuous publication in New York. The paper was formed by a merger
of two Spanish-language papers in the late 1960s.
   Gannett, the nation's largest newspaper group, paid $9 million
for the paper in 1981, according to The New York Post, but the
Thursday sale price was not disclosed. The Post, quoting
unidentified sources, reported that the daily was sold for $25
million. Newsday reported that it was sold for $12 million to $14
million.
   Carlos Ramirez, the paper's publisher since 1984, will continue
in that capacity. Joining him on the new ownership management team
are Peter W. Davidson, a New York investment banker, and Rupert
Phillips, an owner and operator of several daily papers.
</TEXT>
