<DOCNO> AP890901-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HousingAffordability     09-01 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Affordability,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ability to Buy a House Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An index measuring the ability of the typical
American family to buy a home fell in July to the lowest level in
nearly four years, reflecting rising home prices.
   The National Association of Realtors said Thursday that a family
with a median income of $32,876, meaning half of the nation's
families earned more and half less, had only 98 percent of the
income necessary to buy a median-priced existing home costing
$96,400.
   That was the index's lowest level since September 1985 and marked
a decline from 99.1 percent in June when the index dipped below 100
percent for the first time since March 1986.
   The decline in affordability in July was blamed on a $3,000
increase in median home prices nationally. That more than offset the
effects of a decline in the average mortgage rate from 10.59 percent
to 10.39 percent. The association uses a composite rate reflecting
both fixed-rate and adjustable-rate mortgages.
   The changes increased the monthly principal and interest payment
on a median home by $10 to $699, which represents 25.5 percent of
the median family's income.
   By region, the median family in the Midwest had 129.2 percent of
the income needed to buy a median home; Southern families, 97.8
percent; families in the West, 73.5 percent, and residents of the
Northeast, 70.5 percent.
   ``Consumers' incomes have not kept pace with home prices in the
Northeast and West. First-time buyers simply don't make what it
takes to buy in those regions,'' said Ira Gribin, president of the
Realtors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
