<DOCNO> AP890901-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TelephoneTips Bjt   09-01 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Telephone Tips, Bjt,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Tipster Defiant In Face Of Scrutiny</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The embattled founder of a stock-tip
telephone line says he's only ``helping the little guy'' by passing
on the research of major Wall Street firms along with his own market
recommendations.
   But state regulators say the fast-talking Barry K. Davis, barred
from the securities industry 18 years ago, may be giving investment
advice illegally.
   In a telephone interview Thursday, Davis fumed at the state
Bureau of Securities, a recent news story about his service and the
attitude of Wall Street firms.
   ``Let's say my background hasn't been wonderful. What has that
got to do with what I'm doing for the little guy in America today?''
he said.
   What he does for the little guy is help prepare a recorded phone
message changed thrice daily with a menu of rumors, tips, boasts
about past successes and the state of the economy.
   Subscribers to Traders &amp; Investors Alert of Fort Lee pay $695 a
year. For $1,750, subscribers receive a beeper so they can be
summoned to phone for special reports.
   It's not just the little guy on a subscriber list of 1,600 Davis
says he helps. He claims that a long list of brokers from major Wall
Street research firms call him, though he would not identify them.
   He says they provide some of the line's information from the
firms' research departments. Davis said he also talks to exchange
floor sources, goes to other advisory services and computer bases
and takes tips from people invited to call in.
   Brokers say they call to find out what other firms are saying,
what they may have missed from the newspapers or to crystalize the
day's information.
   ``Everything he says is not etched in stone, but it gives you an
idea of why things are moving and it gives you ideas of what to
do,'' said Howard Borenstein, a broker at the Chicago firm David
Noyes &amp; Co.
   Davis says the large Wall Street firms are not too happy with him
for cutting into their business.
   Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. spokesman Peter Roche said the service had
gotten hold of some daily announcements from the brokerage's
research department, and sales staff were reminded that sharing the
information was forbidden.
   ``The brokers at Goldman, Sachs don't need to call something like
that,'' said a spokesman for that firm. He also doubted how much
help Davis gets. ``There's no such thing as free research.''
   Nor is the state Bureau of Securities too happy.
   Bureau chief James McL. Smith said Davis may be operating as an
unlicensed investment adviser. The investigation is continuing.
   Bureau enforcement director Richard Barry said regulators
naturally gravitate to a once-banned industry member who returns to
it. He also referred to a potential for such a service to be used
for market manipulation.
   ``There's a lot of possibilities of investment advisers to take
unfair advantage of the market,'' he said.
   ``All I am is a research reporter,'' said Davis, who speaks so
quickly he is sometimes difficult to understand. His conversation is
laced with profanity and constantly interrupted by shouts at
co-workers.
   ``We claim under the freedom of the First Amendment that we are
doing electronic broadcasting,'' he said.
   When known as Barry Sutz in 1971, Davis was barred by the
Securities and Exchange Commission from the industry, for, he says,
under-capitalizing his brokerage firm. Until setting up the line in
September, Davis, 46, of Cresskill, said he traded for himself,
worked in the insurance business and sold franchises.
   He said he changed his name because he tired of Sutz. ``I also
had a nose job because my nose was too big. I change anything I want
to change. That's why I'm a great trader,'' he said.
   He called himself chief of research for TIA and the original
brains behind it, but declined to identify its principals or top
executives.
   He said he now welcomes scrutiny by the SEC and state regulators,
though when three of Smith's investigators paid a call in May,
police were called to eject them.
   ``Tell us what the law is and we'll pay attention to it,'' he
said. ``Does a checkered past have the same rights as anybody else
unless he's proven guilty?''
   He also criticized The Wall Street Journal for running what he
called an unflattering article two weeks ago. He said the
newspaper's owner, Dow Jones &amp; Co., which runs a financial news
service aimed at stockbrokers, wanted to ``wipe us out because we're
in competition.''
   Dow Jones spokesman Roger May had no comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
