<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   09-01 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Back-to-School Sales Benefit Apparel Retailers; Mass Merchandisers
Slump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Clothing merchants and department stores benefited from
back-to-school shopping during August, but mass merchandisers
suffered as consumers generally remained hesitant about big
purchases.
   ``We saw good sales in the apparel department, but many of the
other departments show a cautious consumer,'' Walter Loeb, an
analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. Inc., said Thursday after the
nation's biggest retailers announced their August sales results.
   Consumers generally are in a strong financial position and are
confident right now, but their spending ``is drifting sideways,''
agreed Jeffrey Edelman, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Consumers have cut back on purchases of what are called
discretionary items, as opposed to necessities such as food, because
of rising mortgage payments and other credit costs.
   August sales are important because the month marks the beginning
of the retailers' most critical season. Shopping generally
accelerates in mid-August as families prepare for the new school
year and then continues to build through the holiday season, when
stores earn about half their annual profits.
   Economists track retail sales because the figures are a component
consumer spending, which in turn accounts for about two-thirds of
U.S. economic activity.
   Consumer caution has hurt big general storeowners such as the
nation's largest retailer, Sears, Roebuck and Co. Sears said its
August sales were up 2.3 percent overall, but sales at stores open
at least a year _ known as same-store or comparable-store sales _
fell 1.1 percent.
   Retailers and analysts consider same-store sales a more accurate
reflection of a company's performance than totals that include sales
at recently opened stores.
   Another mass merchandiser, K mart Corp., also had a disappointing
August, with overall sales up 4.8 percent and same-store sales up
1.5 percent.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the discount chain that consistently has
outperformed its competitors, said its overall sales jumped 26
percent in August, while comparable-store results rose 11 percent.
   Positive results at stores that specialize in apparel, such as
J.C. Penney Co. Inc., were due largely to back-to-school shopping.
Penney, where sales have steadily improved in recent months
following a prolonged slump, reported a 17.1 percent surge in
overall August sales, while same-store sales increased 15.7 percent.
   Limited Inc., the nation's biggest specialty apparel retailer,
reported an 11 percent increase in overall August sales and a 7
percent jump in same-store sales.
   Department stores also had a good month.May Department Stores Co.
said its overall sales rose 9.6 last month and same-store sales grew
6.5 percent.
   Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said the
improvement at the apparel and department stores was better than he
had expected and the trend bodes well for retailers' third-quarter
profits.
   Edelman, meanwhile, cautioned that some of the rosier sales
reports looked stronger than they actually were because the figures
were compared with weak results of August 1988. A year ago, the
fashion industry was just beginning to emerge from a severe drought.
   The figures reported Thursday were from major general merand
apparel retailers. The government's monthly retail sales report is
more comprehensive, incl dealers, supermarkets, restaurants and
elsewhere.
   Other rg August sales included:
   _Dayton Hudson Cor a 5.1 increase in same-store results.
   _Montgomery Ward &amp; Co., which reported a 1 percent overall sales
gain, and a 0.8 percent comparable-store sales increase.
   _Woolworth Corp., which said its sales rose 13.3 percent overall
and 7.8 on a same-asis.
</TEXT>
