<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0837EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MercTradersFined     09-01 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Merc Traders Fined,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Merc Fines 4 For Pre-Arranged Trades During Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, whose
self-policing practices are under federal scrutiny, has suspended
four traders and fined them a total of $450,000 for alleged
violations during the 1987 stock market crash.
   Two of the traders were suspended for two years and ordered to
return $44,500 each to customers who were allegedly cheated.
   The traders are accused of making pre-arranged transactions of
stock-index futures in violation of exchange rules.
   They allegedly cheated their customers by executing their orders
privately for their own enrichment, instead of in the open auction
of the Merc's Standard &amp; Poor's 500 stock-index futures trading pit.
   None of the traders has admitted or denied the allegations.
   The stiff penalties suggest that the Merc, the world's
second-largest futures market, is taking a tougher stand against
wrongdoing in the face of intense scrutiny of the industry's
self-policing.
   Federal prosecutors on Aug. 2 announced indictments for alleged
trading fraud against 45 traders and one clerk at the Merc and the
Chicago Board of Trade. The next day, Leo Melamed, chairman of the
Merc's executive committee, promised to ``instill the fear of God''
in any traders who think of stealing.
   Most complaints against traders are settled before they get to a
full-blown hearing, and the case against the four traders was headed
in that direction until the federal investigation became known.
   Afterward, the Merc broadened its probe to include more trades
and brought added charges against the two main targets.
   Traders Albert V. Furman III and Patrick J. Shannon Jr. were
suspended from exchange membership for two years and ordered to make
restitution of $44,500 each.
   Furman was fined $125,000 by the exchange. In addition to
pre-arranged trading, the exchange found Furman guilty of failing to
fully answer all questions during an investigation of his case.
   Furman previously had been fined $125,000, suspended two months
and ordered to pay $127,500 restitution, in connection with other
alleged improper stock-index futures trades made during the week of
Oct. 19, 1987.
   Shannon was fined $225,000 in addition to his suspension.
   Peter Shannon, Patrick's brother, was fined $50,000 and suspended
from exchange membership for two months.
   Sidney L. Rabin was also fined $50,000 and suspended from
exchange membership for two months.
   Stock-index futures are contracts for future delivery of groups
of stocks. Futures traders can use stock-index futures to hedge
against losses on actual stock market investments or simply to
speculate on the prices of the underlying stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
