<DOCNO> AP890901-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0859EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Lawyer-InsiderTrading     09-01 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lawyer-Insider Trading,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Law Partner Sentenced to Five Years For Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former partner in a prominent Chicago law firm
has been sentenced to five years in prison, believed to be the
longest term ever issued for illegal insider stock trading.
   U.S. District Judge Marvin Aspen on Thursday also ordered Alfred
Elliott, 45, a former law partner in Schiff, Hardin &amp; Waite, to pay
the government $332,000 in fines and $353,000 in profits he made
from trading stocks based on inside information he obtained over a
two-year period.
   ``You are a brilliant, talented man who could have accomplished
anything you wanted in the practice of law,'' Aspin told Elliott
before the sentencing. ``But to accumulate money and stockpile it
the way you did, that kind of greed boggles the mind.''
   Elliott was one of two lawyers at the firm who represented
companies on imminent corporate mergers and acquisitions. He was
indicted last July and convicted later on 70 counts of using
confidential information to buy and sell stock. He reportedly made
more than $600,000 between March 1984 and April 1986.
   Elliott said he knew he had made a mistake and that he had tried
to right the wrongs made against the law firm, which he left in 1986
after his actions became known.
   ``I realize what I did was wrong. It was crazy, nuts,'' Elliott
said. ``I am a person of integrity and I really am sorry this
happened.''
   Elliott's attorney, James Streicker, also had argued for leniency
in the sentencing, and compared his client's case to that of
financier Ivan F. Boesky, The Wall Street speculator is serving a
three-year prison sentence for conspiracy to lie to the Securities
and Exchange Commission, a sentence he received after striking a
plea bargain with federal prosecutors in return for his cooperation.
   Boesky had agreed in 1986 to pay $100 million to settle insider
trading charges filed by the SEC.
   For his part, Elliott paid more than $500,000 in damages and
repaid profits after insider-trading allegations in a 1986 civil
case filed in federal court by the SEC.
   But Aspen rejected the comparison of Elliott to Boesky, and
sentenced Elliott to five years, which the U.S. attorney's office
believes to be the stiffest sentence ever imposed in such a case.
</TEXT>
