<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingOrders     09-01 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Orders,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Canada Orders $1 Billion In Boeing Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. picked up its second big commercial
airplane order in about a month with Air Canada ordering nine
extended-range 767-300s valued at about $936 million.
   In addition to the nine firm orders, Air Canada took options on
another nine 767-300ERs, Boeing said Thursday.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes said the firm orders, including spare
parts, would be worth nearly $1.9 billion, if all options are
exercised.
   Late in July, Texas Air Corp. placed a $2.8 billion order with
Boeing, the world's leading airplane maker, to upgrade its
Continental and Eastern airline units.
   Aloha Airlines also ordered four 737-300s worth about $125
million, Boeing confirmed. Aloha also has options for four more
737-300s.
   Pierre J. Jeanniot, Air Canada's president and chief executive
officer, said it chose the long-range widebody jet as its principal
plane for long-range domestic and international service.
   The new jets will replace 14 Lockheed L-1011s and allow for fleet
expansion. Air Canada already has 21 smaller 767-200s, including 13
with extended-range capability.
   The two-engine, extended-range jets can carry 210 passengers
6,200 nautical miles. Air Canada will receive the first of the new
planes in 1993 and plans to use it on North Atlantic routes,
including Toronto-Frankfurt and Montreal-London.
   Boeing said the planes, equpped with Pratt &amp; Whtiney engines,
will burn about 30 percent less fuel than the three-engine L-1011s
they will replace and cost about 25 percent less to operate.
   Aloha is to receive the first of its newly ordered planes in
November 1992. Aloha, a major inter-island carrier in Hawaii, has 13
twin-engine 737s, including two new 737-300s.
   The 737-300, powered by CFM International engines, can carry 128
passengers about 3,000 nautical miles.
   So far this year, Boeing has received orders for 692 jetliners
worth a total $36.4 billion, an industry record.
</TEXT>
