<FIRST>r f PM-GrandMet     09-01 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grand Met,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Met Sells S. American Operations To Cargill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC has agreed to sell
operations in three South American countries owned by its Pillsbury
Co. subsidiary, the company said.
   Cargill Inc. will buy Pillsbury's flour mill and pasta plant in
Venezuela. Separate agreements were reached with local investors to
sell Pillsbury's two consumer foods plants in Guatemala and its 10
percent share in a flour mill in El Salvador.
   Neither side would discuss the terms of the transaction or size
of the operations, except to say there were 400 employees in the
Venezuelan plants and 200 employees in the Guatemalan plants.
   Since acquiring Minneapolis-based Pillsbury early this year,
London-based Grand Met has been selling off Pillsbury subsidiaries
that don't fit its long-term strategies. The divestitures also help
reduce its large acquisition debts.
   ``It may have been so small they found it not worth keeping or
developing,'' said L. Craig Carver, a securities analyst with Dain
Bosworth.
   Since Venezuela has been plagued by such problems as the collapse
in the price of oil, a staggering national debt, uncontrolled
inflation, a weak currency and social unrest, its troubles made
Pillsbury's operations there ``unpredictable from a financial
standpoint,'' said Marlene Johnson, a public relations official with
Pillsbury.
   ``But, essentially, we decided they didn't fit our long-term
stragegy,'' Johnson said.
   Cargill, the privately held grain giant based in Wayzata west of
Minneapolis, already has 15 flour mills in the U.S. and three in
Venezuela.
   ``We feel that that country is taking some sound steps to correct
some international problems. We have long-term confidence,'' said
Alan Holbert, a public relations official with Cargill.
</TEXT>
