<FIRST>r f BC-Nordstrom-Lawsuit     09-01 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nordstrom-Lawsuit,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Department Store Settles False Advertising Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nordstrom Inc., which operates nearly two
dozen upscale department stores throughout California, has agreed to
pay a $200,000 fine and penalties to settle a false advertising
lawsuit.
   The Seattle-based chain, which didn't admit any wrongdoing, also
agreed Thursday to a six-year injunction that bars it from falsely
representing special purchase merchandise as clothing on sale that
is regularly available.
   A lawsuit filed by the District Attorney's Consumer Protection
Division alleged that seven of the stores in Southern California
used ``fictitious original or regular price'' labels for a
comparison to sale prices, but that the items actually were never
available at the higher prices.
   ``When the district attorney's office brought the problems to our
attention, we took steps immediately to make sure it doesn't happen
again,'' Nordstrom spokeswoman Chris Breidenbaugh said. ``In the
future, we will be careful to be as specific as we can.'' The
charges stemmed from sales ads from last October and December.
</TEXT>
