<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0394</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market got off to a weak start today as
traders weighed the implications of new economic reports.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dipped by 1.52 to
2,735.75 by 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Little distance separated advancing and declining issues on the
New York Stock Exchange as 421 stocks gained in price, 453 declined
and 554 were unchanged.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
down 0.14 to 195.13.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 18.92 million shares after the
first 30 minutes of trading.
   Before the market opened, the government issued a report on the
job market that indicated the economy is growing at a moderate rate,
making the threat of recession seem more remote. The Labor
Department said the nation's unemployment rate remained at 5.2
percent in August. Non-farm payrolls expanded by 110,000, a total
that was reduced by about 108,000 due to strikes.
   A Commerce Department report pointed to a possible buildup in
momentum after months of sluggish economic activity earlier this
year. The Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose a modest 0.2
percent in July after registering no gain in June and plunging by
1.3 percent in May, the biggest drop since late 1987 following the
stock market crash.
   The early leader on the Big Board's list of actively traded
shares was Niagara Mohawk Power, which was up [ at 12}.
   Union Carbide was the second most heavily traded share in the
early going and lost [ to 31.
   UAL, parent of United Airlines, jumped 5 to 284} on word that the
airline's pilots union is preparing to make a bid for the carrier.
   On Thursday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials ended at its
second-highest close ever after trading near its opening level for
much of a fairly sluggish session. The industrial average rose 9.12
to 2,737.27, pushed up by a late round of buying.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by nearly 6 to 5 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 801 up, 672 down and
510 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board eased to 143.42 million
shares from 174.35 million Wednesday.
   The NYSE's composite index rose 0.36 to 195.27.
