<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-01 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed As Frost Fears Recede</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with
some of the selling reflecting an easing of frost fears in corn and
soybean country.
   Soybean futures had run up sharply Thursday after at least one
private weather forecasting firm predicted patchy frost in some
parts of the Midwest late next week. But many other private
meteorological firms issued frost-free forecasts this morning.
   Overnight rainfall in much of the Corn Belt added to the selling
pressure on ideas that the moisture may improve soybean yields.
   And an increase in farmer selling of corn was an additional drag
on the corn market.
   Wheat futures were mostly higher in moderate trading, partly in
reaction to news of an increase in export sales of wheat last week.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 2{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was
} cent to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.33} a bushel; oats
were { cent to 1 cent lower with September at $1.34{ a bushel;
soybeans were \ cent to 2\ cents lower with September at $5.87} a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent lower to .08 cent higher with October
at 73.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .15 cent
lower with September at 82.57 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
to .35 cent lower with October at 40.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .45 cent higher with February at 44.30
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures
advanced.
</TEXT>
