<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv04   09-01 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 04,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Sept. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Creditors May Not Be Burnt By Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months after Eastern Airlines filed for
bankruptcy protection, analysts are optimistic that bondholders and
other creditors of the troubled carrier won't get burnt.
   ``Eastern's creditors are coming out better than they probably
would have expected at the start of the bankruptcy,'' said Philip
Baggaley, who follows the airline for Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., a
credit rating agency.
   Eastern appears well on its way toward selling assets as proposed
under its reorganization plan, added analyst Robert Decker of Duff &amp;
Phelps Inc., a Chicago investment research firm.
   ``I give Eastern a pretty good chance of being able to meet their
object that they've been stating, that they'll be able to pay off
their debt holders in full,'' Decker said this past week.
   Eastern owes about $3.5 billion to creditors, including
bondholders, banks, ticketholders, fuel suppliers, and equipment
trust certificate holders.
   A crippling strike March 4 virtually grounded the Texas Air Corp.
division, and five days later it filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization. Since then it gradually has been rebuilding its
flight schedule.
   It also has been selling assets to raise cash, such as its
Northeast shuttle service, which went to developer Donald Trump for
$365 million.
   Eastern said last week that its rebuilding plan is going better
than expected and that the carrier may not sell the full $1.8
billion in assets envisioned under its original rebuilding plan.
Among the assets no longer up for sale are its valuable South
American routes.
   However, since it has not sold as many assets, Eastern said it
may not have the cash to make as many prepayments on debt as it
expected.
   Among Eastern's debts are $39 million in industrial revenue
bonds, which financed construction of airport facilities used by
Eastern; about $200 million in subordinated debentures; and more
than $700 million in equipment trust certificates, which financed
aircraft purchases. All these securities are publicly traded.
   Recently, holders of $63 million in Eastern equipment trust
certificates were paid in full when the certificates' issuer, GE
Capital Corp., decided to redeem them early. Now GE Capital will
receive payments from Eastern for use of the jets, S&amp;P said.
   S&amp;P's Baggaley said the early redemption of the certificates,
which was allowed because of Eastern's bankruptcy filing,
``indicates that GE Capital feels that they're going to continue to
get their rental payments. It's at a high lease rate and GE decided
they wanted it all for themselves.''
   Raymond Neidl, an analyst at the New York brokerage Dillon, Read
&amp; Co. Inc., said Eastern has been making interest payments on its
remaining equipment trust certificates, but the creditors have no
recourse if it stops.
   These certificates, unlike the GE Capital ones, do not allow the
certificate holders to repossess the planes should Eastern stop
making payments.
   Owners of Eastern's subordinated debt haven't fared as well as
the certificate holders. Eastern has halted interest payments on
these convertible securities.
   But all is not gloomy here. The price of these debentures, which
dropped when the carrier filed for bankruptcy, rebounded sharply as
it became more likely that Eastern would pay off its creditors in
full, Neidl said.
   ``Nobody's been really hurt so far,'' he said. ``The prices of
all issues have moved up very strongly.''
   He said investors holding Eastern debt certificates may win no
matter how the airline's saga ends.
   If Eastern's reorganization goes as planned and it emerges as a
profitable carrier, the price of the debt issues will continue to
rise. Should Eastern's plans go awry, creditors need not worry
because the carrier's assets would fetch enough at auction to cover
its debts.
   Neidl also was optimistic about Eastern's future. But, he said,
recent comments by Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo that he may sell
all or part of Continental Airlines, the holding company's other
airline unit, complicate the picture.
   Should he sell a partial stake, the cash could be funneled to
Eastern to help it pay off debt. But if Continental is sold
outright, Eastern may not survive as an independent carrier, and it
could be put up for sale or liquidated, the analyst said.
   ``I don't think Eastern could make it on its own,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
