<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     09-01 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0380</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices bounded forward today, pushed by
futures-related program buying and takeover speculation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 18.81 to 2,756.08 by
noon on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues took a widening lead over declining ones on the
New York Stock Exchange with 818 up, 410 down and 559 unchanged.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks went up
by 1.15 to 196.42.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 74.64 million shares at midday
compared to 73.17 million at the same point Thursday.
   The market's advance was touched off at mid-morning by
futures-related program buying. Strength in the bond market also
aided stocks.
   Before the market opened, the government issued a report on the
job market that indicated the economy is growing at a moderate rate,
making the threat of recession seem more remote. The Labor
Department said the nation's unemployment rate remained at 5.2
percent in August. Non-farm payrolls expanded by 110,000, a total
that was reduced by about 108,000 due to strikes.
   A Commerce Department report pointed to a rebound in momentum
after months of sluggish economic activity earlier this year. The
Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose a modest 0.2 percent in
July after registering no gain in June and plunging by 1.3 percent
in May, the biggest drop since late 1987 following the stock market
crash.
   The leader on the Big Board's list of actively traded shares was
Niagara Mohawk Power, which was down [ at 12{.
   Among actively traded blue chips contributing to the advance in
the Dow Jones industrial average were: General Motors, up 1 to 50;
International Business Machines, up ~ to 118; American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up { to 40|; Exxon, up \ to 44 and McDonald's, up \ to
29[.
   Johnson &amp; Johnson rose 1[ to 53{ amid what were described as
vague takeover rumors.
   Airline stocks made a comeback from Thursday's selloff. UAL,
parent of United Airlines, jumped 5{ to 285\ on word that the
airline's pilots union is preparing to make a bid for the carrier.
AMR, owner of American, rose 1| to 89| and Delta gained 1 to 80~.
</TEXT>
