<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USW-BethlehemSteel     09-01 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USW-Bethlehem Steel,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Strikes Freight Car Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first steel strike in this
manufacturing city since 1959 began Friday when about 800 United
Steelworkers members walked off the job against the freight car
division of Bethlehem Steel Corp.
   The division's 11 p.m. shift walked off the job about 12:01 a.m.
on Friday and was cheered by about 100 workers standing outside the
plant.
   USW Local 2635 voted 785-29 Wednesday to oppose the company's
two-year contract offer and go on strike. The office and technical
workers, USW Local 9157, voted 15-2 against the contract.
   Bethlehem Steel called its last offer fair in view of current
business conditions.
   The union's negotiating committee said the company's offer of 50
cents per hour in wage increases would have left compensation below
1982 levels.
   ``I think we're going to be out for a long time,'' Andrew
``Lefty'' Palm, director of USW's District 15, said late Thursday.
   ``When they lost money, we saved (them) and now they're making
money and don't want to share it,'' Palm said.
   The union made concessions in 1983 to keep the then-struggling
plant operating. It accepted a wage and benefit freeze in 1986 and
agreed to extend the freeze through a wage-reopener vote in 1988.
   The division, which had slumped to fewer than 10 employees in the
early 1980s, has increased employment dramatically since 1987,
Bethlehem Steel spokesman Gary Graham said.
   Employment now is at about 1,000, including salaried workers.
   Graham acknowledged that the division turned a profit in 1988
from making railroad freight cars, but said it had lost a total $30
million in the five previous years. It has orders booked into next
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
