<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1447EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Coastal-Wyatt     09-01 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coastal-Wyatt,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastal Corp. To Resign As CEO, Remains Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. announced Friday that Oscar S.
Wyatt Jr. will resign as the company's chief executive, but will
continue as chairman.
   Wyatt, 65, has recommended that James R. Paul, president and
chief operating officer, replace him as chief executive, Coastal
confirmed.
   Wyatt, who founded the company, has been in his position since
1955 and is the company's largest shareholder, with 4.2 percent of
the company's common stock and 21.4 percent of its class A common
stock.
   ``I want to stress that he's not resigning or retiring,'' said
Coastal spokesman Jim Bailey. ``He will remain very active on a
day-to-day basis.''
   Bailey said the board may vote on the appointment of Mr. Paul at
its September meeting. A date has not been announced for the meeting.
   Coastal is a Houston-based diversified energy company with
interests in natural gas pipelines, oil exploration and production,
refining and marketing and coal and independent power production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
