<DOCNO> AP890901-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1434EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-01 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in busy European trading
Friday, aided by the release of bullish U.S. unemployment figures.
   Gold prices fell under pressure from the dollar's gains.
   Dealers said the healthy unemployment data confirmed the market's
expectations that the U.S. Federal Reserve is unlikely to lower
interest rates.
   By showing that the U.S. economy is growing at a moderate pace,
the figures mean ``we're not likely to see interest rate cuts in the
near-term,'' said Marek Stefanowicz, senior dealer at Nomura Bank
International PLC.
   Some traders said they were surprised by the dollar's move. They
said they had expected more profit-taking as U.S. dealers begin to
close their positions before the Labor Day weekend.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.17 yen to a closing 145.45 yen from Thursday's
144.28. Later, in London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 145.23
yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5565 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5735 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
1.9785 West German marks, up from 1.9580; 1.7085 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6880; 2.2200 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2090; 6.6700 French
francs, up from 6.6035; 1.1817 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1758; and
1,413.50 Italian lire, up from 1,406.90.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $358.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $359.95. In Zurich, gold was lower,
closing at a bid $358.40 an ounce, compared with 360.00 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 76 cents to close at a bid
$359.28 an ounce.
   Silver prices fell in London to a late bid price of $5.06 a troy
ounce from Thursday's $5.09.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
