<DOCNO> AP890901-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Iran-Japan     09-01 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Japan,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Demands $1.5 Billion From Mitsui for Unfinished Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran is demanding $1.5 billion in
compensation from Japan's Mitsui conglomerate for its abandonment of
a petrochemical plant in southern Iran, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported Friday.
   The news agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Ahmad Rahgozar,
head of the National Petrochemical Co., as telling the daily
newspaper Kayhan that Japan had offered a ``friendly settlement,''
and that he hoped the dispute would be solved ``shortly.''
   There was no immediate comment from a Mitsui delegation that has
been in Iran since Sunday in an effort to settle the problem.
   Iranian officials have warned that the issue might jeopardize
Japanese business interests in Iran as the country launches a
multibillion-dollar reconstruction program after a cease-fire that
halted the eight-year gulf war with Iraq last year.
   Iran claimed earlier this month that the giant Japanese
conglomerate had offered to pay $1.25 billion after pulling out from
the project, but that the figure was rejected as too low.
   Mitsui and Japan's International Trade Ministry denied the
report. A Mitsui official said a compensation package was being
discussed but that the final figure would be well below the sum
mentioned.
   The plant was 85 percent completed before the gulf war broke out
in September 1980. The Japanese halted work on it October 1984 after
the plant was badly damaged in Iraqi air raids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1455EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-China-Defaults     09-01 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Defaults,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Sets Up Commission to Handle Huge Industrial Debts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has set up a special commission to tackle
the ``increasingly serious problem'' of factories failing to pay
debts and taxes, the official China Daily said Friday.
   The report said the team, to be headed by Finance Minister Wang
Bingqian, will seek to assist enterprises in repaying debts that
have risen to 108.5 billion yuan, or about $29.3 billion at current
exchange rates.
   Wang told the first meeting of the commission that defaults in
the state-run business sector have risen rapidly this year,
disrupting the economy and interfering with the state budget.
   Li Guixian, governor of the People's Bank of China, was quoted by
the daily as saying defaults had intensified the acute shortage of
funds and reduced factories' working capital.
   It said the government's austerity policies, which have reduced
construction projects and cut back on available credit, and the
refusal of some firms to pay taxes, are reasons for the default
problem.
   Li said that in the coming months banks will provide loans to
companies with sound economic records to help clear their debts.
   The daily said that as of the end of June China's industrial and
commercial banks had already provided loans to clear 8 billion yuan.
   Bank experts say many companies with large stockpiles of raw
materials and products must also strive to move their stocks in
order to pay their debts, the daily said.
   The report said the Daqing Oil and Chemical Factory, one of
China's largest enterprises, had been seriously affected by defaults
from subsidiary companies. It said that by the end of July 1,100
companies were in arrears by 300 million yuan to the factory.
   Wang, in a gloomy report to the National People's Congress,
China's parliament, on Thursday said government subsidies for
inefficient state-owned industries have ballooned in recent years.
The government now pays an estimated 40 billion yuan a year to
subsidize money-losing enterprises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
