<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1523EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Lyphomed-Fujisawa Bjt   09-01 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lyphomed-Fujisawa, Bjt,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fujisawa Buying Lyphomed for $670 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujisawa Pharmaceutical Co. announced Friday it is
acquiring Lyphomed Inc. for about $670 million, the first major
acquisition of a U.S. drug company by a Japanese pharmaceutical
maker.
   ``We believe the merger of Lyphomed and our U.S. operations will
further strengthen our position in the U.S. and will allow Fujisawa
to compete more effectively in world markets,'' Dr. Tomokichiro
Fujisawa, president of the Osaka, Japan-based company, said in a
statement released by the two companies.
   Fujisawa has owned nearly 30 percent of Lyphomed _ about 9
million of the company's 29.9 million common shares _ since October
1986, according to Lyphomed spokeswoman Melissa Marsden.
   The $31.87-a-share purchase price exceeds Fujisawa's $31-a-share
offer last week for Lyphomed, based in the Chicago suburb of
Rosemont. The final figure represents an all-time high for Lyphomed
shares, which are traded over the counter.
   Ms. Marsden put the purchase price at approximately $670 million,
which includes conversion of the company's preferred stock.
   The merger should be completed April 1, the companies said.
   Dr. John N. Kapoor, Lyphomed's chairman, said the new merged
organization has the ``potential to be a worldwide leader.''
   ``We eagerly anticipate building on our past achievements and
contributing Lyphomed's many talents as part of Fujisawa's team,''
Kapoor said in the statement.
   Kapoor owns about 14 percent of Lyphomed's stock, a stake he had
previously agreed to sell to Fujisawa once Lyphomed's board approved
a buyout.
   ``This is the first major acquisition ever of a U.S. drug company
by a Japanese drug company,'' said John Boettiger, first vice
president of Rotan-Mosle Inc., a Houston securities firm. ``I think
it's a good deal for both companies.''
   ``Fujisawa sells pills primarily, and Lyphomed is the largest
provider of intravenous drugs to hospitals,'' Boettiger said.
   ``The buzz word in health care is combination therapy, and this
allows either company to provide both intravenous and oral
medicine.''
   Fujisawa is the largest research-based drug company in Japan,
Boettiger said. Its sales for the fiscal year ended March 1 were
$1.46 billion.
   The deal will give Fujisawa access to Lyphomed's U.S. sales
network, which already markets about 400 products to more than 95
percent of U.S. hospitals, he said.
   Lyphomed enjoyed explosive growth in the mid-1980s, particularly
after it became the only company federally licensed to make
pentamidine, a drug used to treat AIDS-related pneumonia.
   Overall sales soared from $4 million in 1981 to $172 million in
1987.
   But the company ran into hard times last year after the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration uncovered quality-control problems at
several Lyphomed plants. Lyphomed lost $21.1 million in 1988.
   Lyphomed has since shuffled top management and posted a profit of
$105,000 on revenues of $71.7 million in the first six months of
1989. Boettiger said that Lyphomed's future prospects looked good,
particularly since the company received FDA approval last month to
open its new plant in Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 0541EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WorkplaceKindergarten Adv05   09-01 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Workplace Kindergarten, Adv 05,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Tuesday, Sept. 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Public Kindergarten at Workplace for Employees' Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When banking assistant Barbara DeVahl
takes her 4-year-old daughter Erin to public kindergarten starting
this week, she'll go to work a few feet away.
   Ms. DeVahl's employer, First Bank System, has donated space for
Downtown Kindergarten, part of St. Paul's municipal school system.
It's a combination of school and day care aimed at recruiting
parents with young children.
   ``The school district needs space, the corporation needs
employees who hang around _ it really helps with turnover _ and the
youngsters really need a quality education and parental involvement
in that education,'' said Barbara Roy, a First Bank assistant vice
president.
   Only a few employers nationwide have embraced this degree of
responsibility in the education and care of their workers' young
children. But more businesses are looking at such arrangements,
largely because of the changing workforce and in particular the
growing number of working mothers.
   Fifty-seven percent of all women with children under 6 years old
are in the workforce, double the percentage in 1970, U.S. Census
Bureau figures show. A Department of Labor study last year showed
the fastest rate of increase among working mothers are those with
toddlers under age 2.
   Ms. DeVahl said one of the biggest advantages to the First Bank
arrangement is that she won't have to worry about transporting her
daughter from kindergarten to day care during the middle of the
workday.
   That's one problem First Bank wanted to eliminate for employees
when it donated the space to the school district. There are other
benefits too.
   ``I'm really looking forward to having lunch with my daughter,''
Mrs. DeVahl said.
   Since her husband works downtown, the family can commute
together. ``I think it will give us a little bit more relaxed
time,'' she said.
   Bank officials are aggressively promoting the Downtown
Kindergarten, as it will be known until parents and students rename
it, as a recruitment tool.
   ``We also knew that kindergarten is a particularly tricky year
for making child-care arrangements because of the children being in
school part day and then needing some other kind of a program,'' Roy
said.
   School Superintendent David Bennett, who has been a supporter of
workplace schools, agreed.
   ``For children, it's very disruptive at a young age to have to
adjust to family life and school life and day care. You begin to
wonder who the stable and predictable adult in your life is,''
Bennett said.
   Once kindergarten is completed every day, children will remain at
the site for day care, which will cost $75 a week for 4-year-olds
and $70 a week for 5-year-olds. Public aid defrays the cost for
low-income families.
   Roy was instrumental in establishing the combined kindergarten
and day-care program. In 1986 and 1987, she headed a local task
force that worked to expand child-care availability in St. Paul.
   Children of First Bank's employees will have priority in
enrollment, but at least two children of non-bank employees have
enrolled. Spaces were offered to other downtown employees to help
fill the class.
   St. Paul public school officials, who have modeled the program
after a similar one in Dade County, Fla., have sent letters to 10
large local corporations encouraging them to consider donating space
for kindergartens and expanded day-care for their own employees'
children, Bennett said.
   ``I think they really are going to put their very best energy
into having this work out because the spotlight is on it,'' Roy said.
   Just west of Minneapolis, Wayzata public school officials are
trying to persuade Trammel Crow Co., a commercial real estate
developer, to set aside space in another office tower planned at the
Carlson Center for a similar program. In a recent survey of tenants,
100 employees said they would be interested in enrolling their
children in a similar program, said James Brandl, the community
education director for Wayzata schools.
   Will Hoeg, a Trammel Crow executive, said he's interested in the
idea as a tenant recruitment tool. ``It's just one of those things
that makes you feel good about doing. We're potentially helping out
our future generation,'' Hoeg said.
   Thomas Schultz, project director for early childhood education at
the National Association of State Boards of Education in Alexandria,
Va., said he's unsure whether the idea will catch on that quickly.
   But he endorsed First Bank program. ``It seems to me any
arrangement that provides a service that offers continuity to the
kids in terms of the day experience they have...is great as an
example of creativity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Tuesday, Sept. 5</NOTE>
