<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures gave up most of the previous
session's gains Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, retreating
along with corn futures prices as fears of an early freeze in the
Midwest faded.
   Wheat futures prices rose substantially, though, partly on
expectations for increased export sales.
   Fears of a freeze late next week in patches of the Midwest were
greatly diminished Friday as most forecasters discounted the
possibility. Among them was USDA Chief Meteorologist Morton
Strommen, who said he saw no evidence of weather patterns that might
produce an early freeze.
   At the close, wheat futures were { cent lower to 6 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.92 a bushel; corn
was 1{ cents to 2\ cents lower with September at $2.32{ a bushel;
oats were { cent to 3 cents lower with September at $1.33} a bushel;
soybeans were 5{ cents to 9\ cents lower with September at $5.82{ a
bushel.
