<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1617EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DowJonesTransportation     09-01 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dow Jones Transportation,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Preparing to Add OTC Stock To Transport Average</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. said Friday it is preparing to
put an over-the-counter market stock into its transportation average
because a wave of mergers and buyouts is making it impossible to
find enough big transport companies on the New York Stock Exchange.
   It would be the first time any of the three Dow Jones averages _
industrials, utilities and transportations _ has included a stock
that was not traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
   UAL Corp. could be the next NYSE stock to disappear from the Dow
Jones average of 20 transportation stocks. UAL, parent of United
Airlines, has received a $6.19 billion bid from investor Marvin
Davis. A joint bid of more than $6.5 billion from United's pilots
union, management, and British Airways also reportedly was being
formulated.
   The over-the-counter market is a network of dealers that trades
issues by computer over phone lines without any central exchange.
Over-the-counter companies generally are smaller than those listed
on the New York Stock Exchange and many are regarded as more
speculative because they have not had the opportunity to establish
records as seasoned businesses.
   Preparations for adding an over-the-counter stock have been going
on at least since January, but have gained urgency with the dealings
over UAL.
   ``We're not going to do this until we have to do it, but we
wanted to make sure people were prepared for it,'' said Dan Hinson,
an assistant managing editor at Dow Jones' Wall Street Journal. ``In
a week, United could be gone.''
   Yellow Freight System Inc. and Roadway Services Inc. are among
the over-the-counter candidates to replace the next NYSE stock that
drops out, said Charles Stabler, an editorial consultant to Dow
Jones.
   The industry body that oversees over-the-counter trading welcomed
Dow Jones' decision.
   ``This is just another example and testimonial to the stocks that
trade in NASDAQ,'' said John T. Wall, executive vice president for
marketing and market services at the Washington-based National
Association of Securities Dealers.
   At the New York Stock Exchange, spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin said
that while mergers and acquisitions have taken away some stocks, the
NYSE's total listings were at a record level.
   Seven stocks have dropped out of the Dow Jones average of 20
transportation stocks and been replaced since the end of 1986.
   TWA dropped out in October 1988 when its chairman and owner, Carl
Icahn, took the company private. Most recently NWA, parent of
Northwest Airlines, dropped out in July when it was bought by a
group led by investor Alfred Checchi.
   The transportation average traces its origins to 1884, when Dow
Jones &amp; Co. began occasionally reporting on an index of 11
representative stocks, most of which were railroad companies. In
1897 the company began separate indexes for railroad and industrial
stocks.
   The railroad average was renamed the transportation average in
1970 to reflect its changing composition. It now consists mainly of
airlines, trucking companies and a handful of railroads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PurchasingManagers Bjt   09-01 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Purchasing Managers, Bjt,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Index Shows Continued Economic Decline In August</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The industrial side of the U.S. economy continued
to weaken during August and a growth index fell to its lowest level
since the economic expansion began in late 1982, the nation's
corporate purchasing managers said Friday.
   But many economists said they weren't concerned about a possible
recession, noting that inflation remains under control and other
economic indicators point to continued growth.
   The government said Friday that August unemployment held steady
at 5.2 percent with the creation of more than 200,000 new non-farm
jobs excluding the effects of phone strikes.
   In other reports, the government said construction spending
inched up 0.02 percentage point in July and the Index of Leading
Economic Indicators rose a modest 0.2 percentage point in July.
   The Purchasing Managers' Index, a widely watched barometer of the
economy's direction, fell to 45.2 percent last month from 46 percent
in July. That was the lowest reading since December 1982, the month
after the beginning of the current economic expansion.
   A reading below 50 percent indicates that the manufacturing
sector of the economy is in decline while a reading above 50 percent
indicates growth, according to the National Association of
Purchasing Management.
   Robert J. Bretz, chairman of the association's Business Survey
Committee, said all major indicators of the manufacturing sector
pointed down in August.
   A measure of production growth fell for the second consecutive
month to its lowest level in more than 6{ years. New orders also
declined, but at a lesser rate than in July. Inventories fell for an
eighth consecutive month as purchasers adjusted to slowing
production and new orders.
   ``The bright spot on the economic horizon continues to be
relatively strong exports and sharply decreasing inflation,'' said
Bretz, who also is director of materials management at Pitney Bowes
Inc.
   Of the 67 percent of the purchasing executives exporting, 23
percent reported better export orders, up from 22 percent who said
so in July, according to the survey.
   It also said prices fell in August, the third consecutive monthly
decline, with purchasing executives finding 29 out of 38 selected
commodities lower in price, up from 21 in July.
   ``All this says the economy is growing but it's slowing,'' said
Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. ``The weakness in the manufacturing sector is
very pronounced.''
   Brusca said the Federal Reserve may soon be forced to ease its
credit policies, by lowering interest rates a bit, to keep the
economy moving. That sentiment helped push bond prices sharply
higher Friday, which in turn gave the stock market a boost.
   But while some economists expressed concern about the economy's
future, others painted a less gloomy picture.
   ``We may have a pocket of weakness in the manufacturing sector
but we've seen recent indications that show the consumer is alive
and well and spending money,'' said Elizabeth G. Reiners, a money
market economist for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``And that's keeping
the economy going.''
   She noted the government recently reported that new home sales
surged 14.4 percent in July _ the fastest pace in three years _
because interest rates had been dropping in recent weeks.
   Here are some details from the August purchasing managers report:
   _The index of manufacturing production fell to 46.5 percent, down
from 48.3 percent in July. That was the lowest since a reading of 44
percent in December 1982.
   _New orders declined for the third consecutive month. However,
the new orders index stood at 45.1 percent, up slightly from 44.8
percent in July.
   _Inventories fell for an eighth straight month to 43.3 percent
from 45.5 percent in July.
   _The pace of vendor deliveries quickened, with the index at 44.9
percent vs. 46.9 percent, even though slightly more commodities were
in short supply.
   _An employment index stood at 44.7 percent, up slightly from 44.4
percent in July.
   The monthly report is based on replies to questions asked of
purchasing executives in more than 250 industrial companies. The
index is a composite of five separate indicators, including new
orders, production, vendor deliveries, inventories and employment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
