<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     09-01 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0324</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pushed higher today but trading
slowed ahead of the long Labor Day weekend.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials posted another all-time
high.
   The stock market benefited from strength in the bond market and
futures-related program buying with traders engaging in maneuvers
aimed at profiting from the differences between prices of
stock-index futures and actual stocks.
   A collection of economic reports out today were open to varying
interpretations but, on balance, the markets reacted favorably to
the figures.
   Bonds sported big gains after an abbreviated pre-holiday session,
helped by a bullish response to the August survey from the nation's
purchasing managers. The National Association of Purchasing
Management said its monthly poll showed lingering weakness in the
industrial side of the economy.
   The bond market initially sold off in reaction to a report on the
job market that suggested the economy is growing at a moderate rate,
making the threat of recession seem more remote and the chances of
interest rate declines less likely.
   The Labor Department said the nation's unemployment rate remained
at 5.2 percent in August. Non-farm payrolls expanded by 110,000, a
total that was reduced by about 108,000 due to strikes.
   A separate Commerce Department report pointed to a possible
rebound in momentum after months of sluggish economic activity
earlier this year. The Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose a
modest 0.2 percent in July after registering no gain in June and
plunging by 1.3 percent in May, the biggest drop since late 1987
following the stock market crash.
   Takeover speculation continued to fuel buying. Airline stocks
made a comeback from Thursday's selloff. UAL, parent of United
Airlines, jumped 7{ to 287\ on word that the airline's pilots union
is preparing to make a bid for the carrier. AMR, owner of American,
rose 1} to 89}.
</TEXT>
