<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-France-TakeoverBid     09-01 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Takeover Bid,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dispute Heats Up in France's Largest Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Cie. Industrielle said Friday he
does not plan to fend of an unwelcome takeover bid for the insurance
holding company with a formal counter-offer.
   But Jean-Marc Vernes indicated he will continue the fight against
Cie. Financiere de Suez, a financial holding company whose $3.6
billion bid is the largest ever on the French market.
   In an interview on French radio, Vernes said he had two main
reasons for deciding against a formal counterbid _ the cost, and a
concern that overt hostility could jeopardize approval for Cie.
Industrielle's purchase of the insurance group Colonia Versicherung
AG.
   Under French stock exchange rules, a counter-offer would have to
be at least 5 percent more than the Suez offer.
   Vernes also alleged that Suez had offered him $2,424 a share for
his Cie. Industrielle interests before it launched its takeover bid
in the market for $1,970 a share.
   Suez said later it ``challenges'' Vernes' allegations. In a brief
statement, it said the price offered to Vernes in private
discussions was ``coherent'' with the proposed $1,970 tender, given
technical details of the payment. It did not elaborate.
   Friday's announcement by Vernes leaves the road clear for Suez to
pursue its takeover bid.
   The Cie. Industrielle president left his defensive strategy
unclear. He said, however, that he has asked for an investigation
into heavy orders for the group's stock that blocked efforts to
trade on the Bourse last week.
   Vernes said he was ready to negotiate a solution with Suez,
although he stipulated that he is prepared to do so only on the
condition that he retains control of Cie. Industrielle.
   Suez already has 18.47 percent of Cie. Industrielle and 32
percent of Groupe Victoire. Cie. Industrielle, in turn, holds 40
percent of Groupe Victoire. The tender offer by Suez is scheduled to
expire on Sept. 18.
</TEXT>
