<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-01 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against all major foreign
currencies Friday following the release of positive economic data,
including a report showing strength in the nation's job market
during August.
   Gold prices rose domestically after weakening overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $360.60 a troy ounce, up 70 cents from late
Thursday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for
gold of $359.25 an ounce, up 65 cents.
   The dollar's ascent began after the government reported that the
August unemployment rate held steady at 5.2 percent with the
creation of more than 200,000 new non-farm jobs excluding the
effects of phone strikes.
   The government also reported that construction spending inched up
0.02 percentage point in July and the Index of Leading Economic
Indicators rose a modest 0.2 percentage point that month.
   ``The numbers were very positive in terms of showing economic
strength,'' said Robert Ryan, a senior trader with Irving Trust Co.,
``and that indicates that (interest) rates will remain firm.''
   Marek Stefanowicz, a senior dealer at Nomura Bank International
PLC in London, agreed, ``We're not likely to see interest rate cuts
in the near-term.''
   Higher rates support the dollar because they make
dollar-denominated securities, such as stocks and bonds, more
attractive to foreigners, thereby increasing the need to convert
foreign currencies into dollars.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.17 yen to a closing 145.45 yen from Thursday's
144.28. It was quoted at 145.23 yen in London, and at 145.60 yen in
New York, up from 145.065. The dollar gained against the British
pound. It cost $1.5565 to buy one pound in London, cheaper than
$1.5735 late Thursday. Sterling fetched $1.55775 in New York, down
from $1.5650.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.9790 West German marks, up from 1.9675; 1.70725 Swiss
francs, up from 1.7005; 6.6665 French francs, up from 6.6290; 1.1815
Canadian dollars, up from 1.17935; and 1,417.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,411.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Thursday: 1.9785 West
German marks, up from 1.9580; 1.7085 Swiss francs, up from 1.6880;
2.2200 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2090; 6.6700 French francs, up from
6.6035; 1.1817 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1758; and 1,413.50
Italian lire, up from 1,406.90.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $358.50 an ounce from
Thursday's $359.95. In Zurich, gold closed at $358.40 an ounce, down
from $360.00.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 76 cents to close at a bid
$359.28 an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery settled at $5.076 a troy ounce, up from $5.045.
Silver fell in London to $5.06 an ounce from $5.09.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
