<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1656EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     09-01 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Rise on Purchasing Managers' Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices surged higher Friday, boosted by a
report that suggested a possible slowdown in manufacturing.
   Release of the report by the National Association of Purchasing
Management helped wipe out losses the market suffered earlier in the
session in response to a stronger-than-expected employment report.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose 13-16 point, or about
$8.13 per $1,000 face amount, while its yield slumped to 8.12
percent from 8.19 percent late Thursday.
   Trading was light and ended early ahead of the three-day Labor
Day weekend.
   Bond prices fell in early trading after the Labor Department
reported that the unemployment rate remained at 5.2 percent in
August and that a resurgent economy had created more than 200,000
new jobs.
   The prospect of a vigorous economy dashed traders' hopes that the
Federal Reserve would relax credit, allowing interest rates to fall
and bond prices to rise.
   But prices roared back after release of the Purchasing Managers'
Index, which is compiled from a survey of purchasing executives in
industrial companies. The index fell to 45.2 percent in August from
46 percent in July, reaching its lowest level since December 1982.
   A reading below 50 percent indicates the manufacturing sector of
the economy is in decline while a reading above 50 percent indicates
growth.
   The report ``suggested that both manufacturing activity and
prices at the producer level are going to be quite weak going
ahead,'' said Ward McCarthy, a managing director of Stone &amp; McCarthy
Research Associates Inc.
   But the market's reaction to the purchasing managers survey
confounded some analysts. William Sullivan, director of money market
research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said traders should have
paid more attention to the unemployment data.
   The purchasing managers report ``is an extremely narrow snapshot
of the manufacturing sector in contrast to employment, which is a
broad-based picture of the U.S. economy,'' including the service,
financial and other industries, Sullivan said.
   ``The bottom line of the employment report is that the Fed policy
is on hold,'' he said.
   However, Robert Brusca, chief economist with Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc., found weakness in the unemployment report,
noting among other things that it showed a decline in worker hours.
   Brusca also said there was evidence of a slowing economy in other
recent statistics, including Thursday's government report that
factory orders fell 1.7 percent in July.
   ``I think the reaction (to the unemployment report) today in some
sense was on target,'' he said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues picked up [ point to \ point, intermediate
maturities were up between 13-32 point and | point and longer-term
issues rose 21-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., a financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 5.21 to 1,177.88.
   Corporate issues were lower. Moody's Investment Grade Corporate
Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of 80 bonds
with maturities of five years or longer, slipped 0.05 to 328.00.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose [ point to 92 27-32. The average yield
to maturity edged down to 7.35 percent from 7.36 percent late
Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.09 percent as the
discount slipped 6 basis points to 7.83 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 8.17 percent as the discount dropped 3 basis points to
7.75 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.21 percent as the
discount fell 5 basis points to 7.64 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8 15-16, up from 8~ percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
