<FIRST>r f AM-Chile-CopperStrike     09-01 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Copper Strike,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike At Chile's Third Largest Copper Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by miners protesting a new work
schedule Friday virtually paralyzed the government-owned El Salvador
copper mine, both the company and union leaders said.
   Nearly 4,000 workers are ordinarily employed at El Salvador,
Chile's third largest copper mine with an output of around 100,000
tons a year. Chile produces around 1.1 million tons of copper a year.
   The stoppage, which was voted by workers earlier in the week, is
legal.
   Darwin Bustamante, president of the National Copper Workers
Federation, said at a news conference that the strike ``almost
completely paralyzed the mine.''
   An official at the mine, who asked not to be identified by name,
told the AP by telephone that the strike ``has paralyzed the mining
operations,'' but other activities such as refining, were not
affected.
   He said no figures were immediately available on absenteeism.
   The strikers are protesting a decision by the government's copper
company, CODELCO, to add 412 miners to 300 already under a work
schedule known as ``continued week,'' which means they would would
take their day off on weekdays instead of Sunday.
   The company said the measure is needed to ensure that the mine
will remain in operation ``every day of the year.''
   According to the Chilean labor law, a legal strike can not last
longer than 59 days.
   New efforts to settle the strike were reported under way Friday.
Union leader Bustamente said the Mining Ministry could soon start a
mediation effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
