<FIRST>r f BC-PolyGram-A&amp;M     09-01 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PolyGram-A&amp;M,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>PolyGram to Buy A&amp;M Records for $500 Million, Reports Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch-owned PolyGram International Ltd. is set
to acquire most of independent A&amp;M Records for about $500 million,
according to published reports.
   PolyGram, the third largest label behind Warner Bros. and CBS,
will buy all of A&amp;M's holdings except its publishing concerns and
real estate holdings, the Hollywood Reporter said Thursday.
   The two companies refused to comment publicly. The Wall Street
Journal said in its Friday editions that a deal was close to being
completed.
   A&amp;M, one of the last privately held major labels, claims a talent
roster headed by Janet Jackson, Sting, Toni Childs, Joe Jackson, Al
Green, Brenda Russell, Human League and Suzanne Vega. The label was
founded in 1962 by trumpet player Herb Alpert and partner Jerry
Moss, who used their initials to name it.
   The company's purchase by PolyGram had been rumored previously.
   PolyGram already distributes A&amp;M records in Europe; RCA records
is the label's American distributor.
   PolyGram, 90 percent owned by Dutch electronics giant NV Philips,
bought Island Records in August for around $300 million. PolyGram's
artists include Bon Jovi, Fine Young Cannibals, U2, Andrew Lloyd
Webber and Luciano Pavarotti.
