<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-01 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cotton Futures Down Sharply in Technical Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cotton futures prices fell sharply Friday on the New York Cotton
Exchange in what appeared to be another leg of a technical
correction that began a week earlier after prices reached their
highest levels in nearly two years.
   On other markets, copper futures prices fell on perceptions that
a Chilean miners strike will be short-lived, and soybean futures
wilted amid diminishing fears of an early freeze in the Midwest.
   Cotton futures settled .15 cent to 1.49 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in October at 72.06 cents a pound.
   Friday's decline marked the fifth daily drop in cotton futures
prices in six trading sessions. The downtrend began Aug. 25, the day
after most contracts set new lifetime highs on concerns that the
effects of too much rain in the Southeast and too little in Texas
have cut sharply into yield prospects for the 1989 U.S. cotton crop.
   On Aug. 24, the October contract traded as high as 76.60 cents a
pound, the highest price for a near-month cotton contract since
Sept. 24, 1987.
   But in its rapid run up to that level, the market sometimes
leapfrogged prices between one day's close and the next day's
opening. One school of technical analysis contends that markets must
return to fill these ``gaps'' before continuing a trend.
   Ernest Simon, a cotton specialist with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., said the market may be on its way to filling a gap
in the December contract's progress.
   ``We are right now near the top of a gap formed some time ago,''
he said.
   The December contract reached an intra-day low Friday of 72.75
cents a pound and would have to fall to 72 cents to fill the gap, he
said.
   ``It was strictly technical,'' Simon said of Friday's trading.
``The technicians started to sell it, the funds started to sell it,
it got into a lot of sell stops and just went down.''
   Copper futures prices fell steeply on New York's Commodity
Exchange following a wire service report that the leader of a miners
union in Chile said a strike that began Friday at the Chilean Copper
Co.'s El Salvador mine would likely be settled within 48 hours.
   Copper settled 2.25 cents to 2.55 cents lower with September at
$1.297 a pound.
   In precious-metals trading on the Comex, gold settled 70 cents an
ounce higher across the board with October at $362.40 a troy ounce;
silver was 3 cents to 3.7 cents higher with September at $5.076 a
troy ounce.
   Soybean futures gave up most of the previous session's gains on
the Chicago Board of Trade, retreating along with corn futures
prices as fears of an early freeze in the Midwest faded.
   Wheat futures prices rose substantially, though, partly on
expectations for increased export sales. Afte the close, the
Agriculture Department announced a sale of 200,000 metric tons of
wheat to China.
   Wheat settled } cent to 5{ cents higher with September at $3.91{
a bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2} cents lower with September at
$2.32} a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to 2{ cents lower with September
at $1.33} a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents to 9} cents lower with
September at $5.81{ a bushel.
   Livestock futures retreated in light, pre-holiday book-squaring
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange but frozen pork-belly futures
rallied on hopes that surplus U.S. pork bellies may be shipped to
Poland as part of an aid package.
   Live cattle settled .45 cent lower to .03 cent higher with
October at 73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .27
cent lower with September at 82.45 cents a pound; live hogs were
unchanged to .62 cent lower with October at 40.15 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .05 cent lower to .40 cent higher with
February at 44.07 cents a pound.
   Most energy futures retreated modestly on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on reports that OPEC may be planning higher crude-oil
production quotas.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents lower to 1
cent higher with October at $18.82 a barrel; heating oil was .30
cent to .50 cent lower with October at 53.90 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .23 cent lower to .30 cent higher with October
at 53.30 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
