<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-StockBaskets     09-01 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stock Baskets,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Seeks Appeals Court Rehearing on `Stock Baskets'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission will
appeal a court ruling that it erred in authorizing trading in a
security that is based on the value of broad stock market indexes,
officials said Friday.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last month that the
securities, known as ``stock baskets,'' resemble futures contracts,
not stocks, and as such, they should be regulated by the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, which originally sanctioned them.
   After the SEC authorized the American Stock Exchange and the
Philadelphia Stock Exchange to begin trading the stock baskets in
April, the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, which trade in similar financial instruments, sued in
federal court.
   A three-judge 7th Circuit panel ruled in favor of the two Chicago
exchanges, saying any stock basket security must be registered with
the CFTC.
   The SEC decided to seek a re-hearing by the same panel or a rare
hearing by the entire 7th Circuit, known as an ``en banc'' hearing,
said Brandon Becker, associate director of the SEC's self-regulatory
oversight and market structure office.
   CFTC officials said they had not seen the SEC court papers and
could not comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890901-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 1832EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-FAA     09-01 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-FAA,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Says Claims Settled, Operations Safe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines on Friday said it has settled
pre-strike safety claims by the Federal Aviation Administration and
gotten favorable marks for the safety of its rebuilding effort.
   ``The FAA has concluded that the company is operating at the very
high safety standards required by its operating certificate,''
Eastern said in a statement.
   Charles E. Bryan, head of the Machinists union at Eastern, said
the statement was ``typical of the FAA's relationship with (Texas
Air Corp. Chairman) Frank Lorenzo's airlines.'' The unions, marking
the end of their sixth month on strike Monday by joining the Labor
Day parade in New York, say Eastern is unsafely rushing its
rebuilding without the unions.
   Company spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said Eastern is paying some
$11.5 million in FAA fines. The FAA safety charges were from 1985 to
1988, she said, and the claims were settled to meet an Aug. 31 U.S.
Bankruptcy Court deadline for old claims against the carrier.
   Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization on March
9, five days after its three unions went on strike.
   Ms. Ceremsak said $8.5 million Eastern is paying stems from a
1986 civil penalty of $9.5 million the FAA assessed because of
numerous record-keeping violations. She said all the fines had to do
with the pre-strike workforce.
   ``This is old news, it's housekeeping for the FAA,'' she said.
``This was a completely different workforce.''
   The FAA expressed satisfaction with Eastern's current maintenance
personnel, its supply of tools and spare parts, and the ability of
its newly hired pilots, Eastern said.
   Eastern released its statement late in the afternoon, and no FAA
officials were immediately available in Washington. Ms. Ceremsak
said Eastern had been delaying its announcement while working out
details and trying to coordinate its statement with the FAA.
   ``The FAA also acknowledges the numerous improvements made by
Eastern subsequent to March 4, 1989, which have enhanced the
company's regulatory compliance posture,'' Eastern said.
   Eastern said its past violations didn't affect passenger safety.
The Miami-based carrier said it has carried more than 485 million
passengers since 1975 with 29 fatalities, one of the best records in
the airline industry.
   Bryan said union officials know that Eastern has been cutting
corners on maintenance, such as failing to certify altimeters.
   ``They're whitewashing it,'' Bryan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
