<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     09-01 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0825</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment steadied at 5.2 percent last
month, the government said in a report prompting forecasts that the
record-long expansion will survive past its seventh anniversary.
   The government on Friday also revised its July job growth figure
upward to 184,000 from 169,000, and the June totals up again from
250,000 to 297,000, further signs that the economy continues to
expand at a pace that will keep it out of recession. The bond market
largely shrugged off the news.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The industrial side of the U.S. economy continued
to weaken during August and a growth index fell to its lowest level
since the economic expansion began in late 1982, the nation's
corporate purchasing managers said.
   The Purchasing Managers' Index, a widely watched barometer of the
economy's direction, fell to 45.2 percent last month from 46 percent
in July. That was the lowest reading since December 1982, the month
after the beginning of the current economic expansion.
   Bond prices rose on the news as traders believed the slowdown
could lead the Federal Reserve to relax credit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said its chief economic
forecasting gauge rose in July for the first time in three months,
posting a modest 0.2 percent gain which many economists interpreted
as further evidence that a recession isn't looming.
   The Commerce Department said Friday the gain in the Index of
Leading Economic Indicators followed no increase at all in June and
a steep 1.3 percent drop in May, the biggest decline since late
1987. The index had risen 0.6 percent in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending recorded a slight
increase in July as strength in non-residential building offset
weakness in housing and government projects, the Commerce Department
reported.
   The department said Friday spending rose by a tiny 0.02 percent,
a gain of $100 million, putting the seasonally adjusted annual rate
at $415.7 billion in July.
   While the July rebound was modest, analysts said it offered at
least the hope that the lengthy construction slump may be coming to
an end.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s directors considered a $6.5 billion
buyout proposal from a group that included the airline company's
employees, senior management and British Airways PLC.
   The board's announcement Friday capped a week of frenzied
takeover speculation involving the nation's biggest airlines and
kicked off a full-scale bidding war for the Chicago-based carrier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. said it is preparing to put an
over-the-counter market stock into its transportation average
because a wave of mergers and buyouts is making it impossible to
find enough big transport companies on the New York Stock Exchange.
   It would be the first time any of the three Dow Jones averages _
industrials, utilities and transportations _ has included a stock
that was not traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujisawa Pharmaceutical Co. announced it is
acquiring Lyphomed Inc. for about $670 million, the first major
acquisition of a U.S. drug company by a Japanese pharmaceutical
maker.
   Fujisawa has owned nearly 30 percent of Lyphomed _ about 9
million of the company's 29.9 million common shares _ since October
1986. The $31.87-a-share purchase price announced Friday exceeds
Fujisawa's $31-a-share offer the previous week. The final figure
represents an all-time high for Lyphomed shares, which are traded
over the counter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge absolved the National
Weather Service and air traffic controllers of negligence in the
1985 fatal crash of a Delta Air Lines jet during a severe
thunderstorm.
   The judge said Friday the crew was negligent for trying to land
in the storm, rejecting arguments by Delta's attorneys.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will pay a $92,000 penalty and
its warranty will cover additional emission control hardware under
an out-of-court settlement with the Environmental Protection Agency.
   EPA last year accused the automaker of violating the federal
Clean Air Act by refusing to replace some emission control
components at no cost. The agency said it had received 23
complaints, all of which Ford has agreed to settle.
   Ford will reimburse about 500 other vehicle owners who were
denied warranty coverage for similar repair work, EPA said Friday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An upbeat attitude about the economy's health sent the stock
market higher Friday, carrying the Dow Jones industrial average and
broader indicators to record heights. The average rose 14.82 to a
new high of 2,752.09.
   The dollar rose against all major foreign currencies following
the release of positive economic data, including a report showing
strength in the nation's job market during August.
   Elsewhere, bond prices rose, while on the commodity markets,
cotton, copper soybean and oil futures fell.
</TEXT>
