<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-01 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures finished mostly lower Friday, ending
a quiet, uneventful week.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, edged up 2 cents to $18.85 a barrel on the
New York Mercantile Exchange. Most later delivery months, however,
declined slightly.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline slipped 0.21 cent to 53.32
cents a gallon.
   Home heating oil for October delivery was down 0.31 cent at 53.97
cents a gallon.
   Analysts described the market as directionless, with little
momentum behind any price moves.
   The market has been listless throughout this week in the absence
of any news developments. Many participants have been on vacation.
   ``It certainly was quiet,'' said Bob Baker, a futures analyst
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
</TEXT>
