<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-89 2002EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-CurrentAccount     09-01 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Current Account,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Bush and Kaifu Discuss Trade, Japan's Trade Figures Continue to
Improve</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese government said Friday the nation's
surplus in the broadest measure of trade fell in July for the fifth
month in a row.
   The announcement came as President Bush and Japanese Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu discussed trade in Washington.
   Japan's current account surplus, which includes merchandise
trade, shipping, tourism and investment income, fell 18.3 percent
from its level of a year earlier to $5.31 billion, the Finance
Ministry said.
   Car and steel exports were down, while computer and business
machine imports were up.
   Japan's surplus in trade alone, a narrower measure, declined
nearly 20 percent to $6.97 billion in July from a year earlier, the
ministry said.
   Government officials hope the recent trend will help Japan repeat
last year's performance, when it cut its current account surplus 8.7
percent to $79.5 billion.
   Meeting with Kaifu in Washington, Bush said: ``I share the prime
minister's belief that while Japan is noted as an exporting
superpower, the time has also come for Japan to be an importing
superpower.''
   Kaifu said Japan recognized that trade imbalances were a source
of irritation and said his country would continue to ``make efforts
for expanding imports.''
   Friday's figures show that in July a booming economy at home
continued to drive Japan's growth, while exports lagged.
   Japan's imports jumped to $16 billion, 13.5 percent higher than
in July of last year. Imports of computers, business machines, and
textile products were strong, ministry officials said.
   Exports inched up 0.3 percent from a year earlier to $23 billion.
Exports of cars declined 5.3 percent and steel exports declined 3.7
percent compared to last year.
   American and Japanese officials will meet Monday and Tuesday in
Tokyo to discuss ``structural'' ways to reduce their bilateral
imbalance. Japan will probably ask the United States to reduce its
budget deficit, which economists say fuels its trade deficit.
   U.S. officials may ask Japan to stimulate its domestic economy to
increase imports and encourage its people to spend rather than save.
   After adjustment for seasonal fluctuations, the current account
surplus grew to $4.05 billion in July from $2.92 billion in the
previous month.
   The surplus in merchandise trade declined to $5.47 billion in
July from $5.75 billion the previous month.
   Both exports and imports were measured when contracts were
settled. The Finance Ministry each month makes a separate
announcement of trade statistics that are compiled when goods pass
through customs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
